reat Cloud Firelight, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Lightning, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Thunder, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Constant Wisdom Rain, the bodhisattva Great Cloud King Completely Pure Rain, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Flower Tree King, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Utpala Scent, the bodhisattva Precious Cloud Sandalwood Cool Body, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Clearing Darkness, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Clearing Obscured Vision, and so on‍—countless, numberless bodhisattva mahāsattvas, who, during that afternoon, had arisen from resting internally and come into the presence of the Bhagavat. They bowed down their heads to the feet of the Bhagavat, circumambulated him three times, keeping him to their right, and sat to one side."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"2b:T99e,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"Among them were the bodhisattva Anāvaraṇa­dharma­cakra­varta, the bodhisattva Aspiring to Always Turn the Dharma Wheel, the bodhisattva Nityodyukta, the bodhisattva Anikṣiptadhura, the bodhisattva Maitreya, the bodhisattva Mañjuśrī, the bodhisattva Avalokiteśvara, the bodhisattva Dharaṇīśvararāja, the bodhisattva King Fearless Powerful Array, the bodhisattva King of Supreme Mount Meru, the bodhisattva Great Ocean Profound King, the bodhisattva Ratnaketu, the bodhisattva Mahāratnaketu, the bodhisattva Kṣitigarbha, the bodhisattva Ākāśagarbha, the bodhisattva Lord with Jeweled Hands, the bodhisattva Vajrapāṇi, the bodhisattva Ratibala, the bodhisattva Great Dharma Power, the bodhisattva Extremely Radiant Array, the bodhisattva Great Golden Radiant Array, the bodhisattva Pure Ethics, the bodhisattva Always Concentrated, the bodhisattva Extremely Pure Intelligence, the bodhisattva Firm Effort, the bodhisattva Ākāśavat, the bodhisattva Anikṣipta­mahā­praṇidhāna, the bodhisattva Bhaiṣajyadatta, the bodhisattva Curing Affliction, the bodhisattva Bhaiṣajyarāja, the bodhisattva Joyful High King, the bodhisattva Prophesied Attainment, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Completely Pure Radiance, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Dharma Holder, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Renowned Joy, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Renowned Limitless Revealer, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Lion’s Roar, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Supreme Bull’s Sound, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Good Fortune, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Precious Glory, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Sun’s Essence, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Moon’s Essence, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Starlight, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Firelight, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Lightning, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Thunder, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Constant Wisdom Rain, the bodhisattva Great Cloud King Completely Pure Rain, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Flower Tree King, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Utpala Scent, the bodhisattva Precious Cloud Sandalwood Cool Body, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Clearing Darkness, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Clearing Obscured Vision, and so on‍—countless, numberless bodhisattva mahāsattvas, who, during that afternoon, had arisen from resting internally and come into the presence of the Bhagavat. They bowed down their heads to the feet of the Bhagavat, circumambulated him three times, keeping him to their right, and sat to one side."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"2c:T99e,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"Among them were the bodhisattva Anāvaraṇa­dharma­cakra­varta, the bodhisattva Aspiring to Always Turn the Dharma Wheel, the bodhisattva Nityodyukta, the bodhisattva Anikṣiptadhura, the bodhisattva Maitreya, the bodhisattva Mañjuśrī, the bodhisattva Avalokiteśvara, the bodhisattva Dharaṇīśvararāja, the bodhisattva King Fearless Powerful Array, the bodhisattva King of Supreme Mount Meru, the bodhisattva Great Ocean Profound King, the bodhisattva Ratnaketu, the bodhisattva Mahāratnaketu, the bodhisattva Kṣitigarbha, the bodhisattva Ākāśagarbha, the bodhisattva Lord with Jeweled Hands, the bodhisattva Vajrapāṇi, the bodhisattva Ratibala, the bodhisattva Great Dharma Power, the bodhisattva Extremely Radiant Array, the bodhisattva Great Golden Radiant Array, the bodhisattva Pure Ethics, the bodhisattva Always Concentrated, the bodhisattva Extremely Pure Intelligence, the bodhisattva Firm Effort, the bodhisattva Ākāśavat, the bodhisattva Anikṣipta­mahā­praṇidhāna, the bodhisattva Bhaiṣajyadatta, the bodhisattva Curing Affliction, the bodhisattva Bhaiṣajyarāja, the bodhisattva Joyful High King, the bodhisattva Prophesied Attainment, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Completely Pure Radiance, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Dharma Holder, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Renowned Joy, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Renowned Limitless Revealer, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Lion’s Roar, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Supreme Bull’s Sound, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Good Fortune, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Precious Glory, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Sun’s Essence, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Moon’s Essence, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Starlight, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Firelight, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Lightning, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Thunder, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Constant Wisdom Rain, the bodhisattva Great Cloud King Completely Pure Rain, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Flower Tree King, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Utpala Scent, the bodhisattva Precious Cloud Sandalwood Cool Body, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Clearing Darkness, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Clearing Obscured Vision, and so on‍—countless, numberless bodhisattva mahāsattvas, who, during that afternoon, had arisen from resting internally and come into the presence of the Bhagavat. They bowed down their heads to the feet of the Bhagavat, circumambulated him three times, keeping him to their right, and sat to one side."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"2d:T99e,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"Among them were the bodhisattva Anāvaraṇa­dharma­cakra­varta, the bodhisattva Aspiring to Always Turn the Dharma Wheel, the bodhisattva Nityodyukta, the bodhisattva Anikṣiptadhura, the bodhisattva Maitreya, the bodhisattva Mañjuśrī, the bodhisattva Avalokiteśvara, the bodhisattva Dharaṇīśvararāja, the bodhisattva King Fearless Powerful Array, the bodhisattva King of Supreme Mount Meru, the bodhisattva Great Ocean Profound King, the bodhisattva Ratnaketu, the bodhisattva Mahāratnaketu, the bodhisattva Kṣitigarbha, the bodhisattva Ākāśagarbha, the bodhisattva Lord with Jeweled Hands, the bodhisattva Vajrapāṇi, the bodhisattva Ratibala, the bodhisattva Great Dharma Power, the bodhisattva Extremely Radiant Array, the bodhisattva Great Golden Radiant Array, the bodhisattva Pure Ethics, the bodhisattva Always Concentrated, the bodhisattva Extremely Pure Intelligence, the bodhisattva Firm Effort, the bodhisattva Ākāśavat, the bodhisattva Anikṣipta­mahā­praṇidhāna, the bodhisattva Bhaiṣajyadatta, the bodhisattva Curing Affliction, the bodhisattva Bhaiṣajyarāja, the bodhisattva Joyful High King, the bodhisattva Prophesied Attainment, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Completely Pure Radiance, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Dharma Holder, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Renowned Joy, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Renowned Limitless Revealer, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Lion’s Roar, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Supreme Bull’s Sound, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Good Fortune, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Precious Glory, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Sun’s Essence, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Moon’s Essence, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Starlight, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Firelight, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Lightning, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Thunder, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Constant Wisdom Rain, the bodhisattva Great Cloud King Completely Pure Rain, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Flower Tree King, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Utpala Scent, the bodhisattva Precious Cloud Sandalwood Cool Body, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Clearing Darkness, the bodhisattva Great Cloud Clearing Obscured Vision, and so on‍—countless, numberless bodhisattva mahāsattvas, who, during that afternoon, had arisen from resting internally and come into the presence of the Bhagavat. They bowed down their heads to the feet of the Bhagavat, circumambulated him three times, keeping him to their right, and sat to one side."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"2e:T54d,Upon those thrones appeared divine lotus flowers, their colors transformed by the Tathāgata, and adorned by many jewels. Upon those lotuses there appeared the four buddha bhagavats. To the east appeared the Tathāgata Akṣobhya. To the south appeared the Tathāgata Ratnaketu. To the west appeared the Tathāgata Amitābha. To the north appeared the Tathāgata Dundubhisvara. At the moment when those buddha bhagavats appeared upon those lion thrones, the great city of Rājagṛha was filled by a great illuminating light. That light spread throughout the trichiliocosm world realm, throughout as many world realms in the ten directions as there are grains of sand in the Ganges River. A rain of flowers fell. There came the sound of divine music. Through the power of the Buddha, all beings in this trichiliocosm world realm gained divine happiness. Those who had incomplete faculties gained all their faculties. The blind saw forms with their eyes; the deaf heard sounds with their ears; the insane gained their sanity; those with distracted minds became undistracted; the naked became clothed; the hungry had their stomachs filled; the thirsty found drink; beings afflicted by illness were healed; and those with impaired physical faculties became possessed of complete faculties. In those worlds there appeared vast, astonishing, wonderful qualities.2f:T54d,Upon those thrones appeared divine lotus flowers, their colors transformed by the Tathāgata, and adorned by many jewels. Upon those lotuses there appeared the four buddha bhagavats. To the east appeared the Tathāgata Akṣobhya. To the south appeared the Tathāgata Ratnaketu. To the west appeared the Tathāgata Amitābha. To the north appeared the Tathāgata Dundubhisvara. At the moment when those buddha bhagavats appeared upon those lion thrones, the great city of Rājagṛha was filled by a great illuminating light. That light spread throughout the trichiliocosm world realm, throughout as many world realms in the ten directions as there are grains of sand in the Ganges River. A rain of flowers fell. There came the sound of divine music. Through the power of the Buddha, all beings in this trichiliocosm world realm gained divine happiness. Those who had incomplete faculties gained all their faculties. The blind saw forms with their eyes; the deaf heard sounds with their ears; the insane gained their sanity; those with distracted minds became undistracted; the naked became clothed; the hungry had their stomachs filled; the thirsty found drink; beings afflicted by illness were healed; and those with impaired physical faculties became possessed of complete faculties. In those worlds there appeared vast, astonishing, wonderful qualities.30:T54d,Upon those thrones appeared divine lotus flowers, their colors transformed by the Tathāgata, and adorned by many jewels. Upon those lotuses there appeared the four buddha bhagavats. To the east appeared the Tathāgata Akṣobhya. To the south appeared the Tathāgata Ratnaketu. To the west appeared the Tathāgata Amitābha. To the north appeared the Tathāgata Dundubhisvara. At the moment when those buddha bhagavats appeared upon those lion thrones, the great city of Rājagṛha was filled by a great illuminating light. That light spread throughout the trichiliocosm world realm, throughout as many world realms in the ten directions as there are grains of sand in the Ganges River. A rain of flowers fell. There came the sound of divine music. Through the power of the Buddha, all beings in this trichiliocosm world realm gained divine happiness. Those who had incomplete faculties gained all their faculties. The blind saw forms with their eyes; the deaf heard sounds with their ears; the insane gained their sanity; those with distracted minds became undistracted; the naked became clothed; the hungry had their stomachs filled; the thirsty found drink; beings afflicted by illness were healed; and those with impaired physical faculties became possessed of complete faculties. In those worlds there appeared vast, astonishing, wonderful qualities.3"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"1:T54d,Upon those thrones appeared divine lotus flowers, their colors transformed by the Tathāgata, and adorned by many jewels. Upon those lotuses there appeared the four buddha bhagavats. To the east appeared the Tathāgata Akṣobhya. To the south appeared the Tathāgata Ratnaketu. To the west appeared the Tathāgata Amitābha. To the north appeared the Tathāgata Dundubhisvara. At the moment when those buddha bhagavats appeared upon those lion thrones, the great city of Rājagṛha was filled by a great illuminating light. That light spread throughout the trichiliocosm world realm, throughout as many world realms in the ten directions as there are grains of sand in the Ganges River. A rain of flowers fell. There came the sound of divine music. Through the power of the Buddha, all beings in this trichiliocosm world realm gained divine happiness. Those who had incomplete faculties gained all their faculties. The blind saw forms with their eyes; the deaf heard sounds with their ears; the insane gained their sanity; those with distracted minds became undistracted; the naked became clothed; the hungry had their stomachs filled; the thirsty found drink; beings afflicted by illness were healed; and those with impaired physical faculties became possessed of complete faculties. In those worlds there appeared vast, astonishing, wonderful qualities.32:T5ce,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eThe essentially pure nature of mind is obscured and afflicted by various psychological defilements, which destroy the mind’s peace and composure and lead to unwholesome deeds of body, speech, and mind, acting as causes for continued existence in saṃsāra. Included among them are the primary afflictions of desire (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003erāga\u003c/em\u003e), anger (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003edveṣa\u003c/em\u003e), and ignorance (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eavidyā\u003c/em\u003e). It is said that there are eighty-four thousand of these negative mental qualities, for which the eighty-four thousand categories of the Buddha’s teachings serve as the antidote.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003e\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eKleśa\u003c/em\u003e is also commonly translated as “negative emotions,” “disturbing emotions,” and so on. The Pāli \u003cem class=\"foreign text-pi\" lang=\"pi-LATN\"\u003ekilesa\u003c/em\u003e, Middle Indic \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ekileśa\u003c/em\u003e, and Buddhist Hybrid Sanskrit \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ekleśa\u003c/em\u003e all primarily mean “stain” or “defilement.” The translation “affliction” is a secondary development that derives from the more general (non-Buddhist) classical understanding of \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003e√kliś\u003c/em\u003e (“to harm,“ “to afflict”). Both meanings are noted by Buddhist commentators. \u003c/p\u003e"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"33:T5ce,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eThe essentially pure nature of mind is obscured and afflicted by various psychological defilements, which destroy the mind’s peace and composure and lead to unwholesome deeds of body, speech, and mind, acting as causes for continued existence in saṃsāra. Included among them are the primary afflictions of desire (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003erāga\u003c/em\u003e), anger (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003edveṣa\u003c/em\u003e), and ignorance (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eavidyā\u003c/em\u003e). It is said that there are eighty-four thousand of these negative mental qualities, for which the eighty-four thousand categories of the Buddha’s teachings serve as the antidote.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003e\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eKleśa\u003c/em\u003e is also commonly translated as “negative emotions,” “disturbing emotions,” and so on. The Pāli \u003cem class=\"foreign text-pi\" lang=\"pi-LATN\"\u003ekilesa\u003c/em\u003e, Middle Indic \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ekileśa\u003c/em\u003e, and Buddhist Hybrid Sanskrit \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ekleśa\u003c/em\u003e all primarily mean “stain” or “defilement.” The translation “affliction” is a secondary development that derives from the more general (non-Buddhist) classical understanding of \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003e√kliś\u003c/em\u003e (“to harm,“ “to afflict”). Both meanings are noted by Buddhist commentators. \u003c/p\u003e"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"34:T66a,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eThe buddha of the western buddhafield of Sukhāvatī, where fortunate beings are reborn to make further progress toward spiritual maturity. Amitābha made his great vows to create such a realm when he was a bodhisattva called Dharmākara. In the Pure Land Buddhist tradition, popular in East Asia, aspiring to be reborn in his buddha realm is the main emphasis; in other Mahāyāna traditions, too, it is a widespread practice. For a detailed description of the realm, see \u003ca target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh115.html\" title=\"The Display of the Pure Land of Sukhāvatī, Toh 115\"\u003e\u003ccite class=\"title text-en\" lang=\"en\"\u003eThe Display of the Pure Land of Sukhāvatī\u003c/cite\u003e, Toh 115\u003c/a\u003e. In some tantras that make reference to the five families he is the tathāgata associated with the lotus family.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eAmitābha, “Infinite Light,” is also known in many Indian Buddhist works as Amitāyus, “Infinite Life.” In both East Asian and Tibetan Buddhist traditions he is often conflated with another buddha named “Infinite Life,” Aparimitāyus, or “Infinite Life and Wisdom,”Aparimitāyurjñāna, the shorter version of whose name has also been back-translated from Tibetan into Sanskrit as Amitāyus but who presides over a realm in the zenith. For details on the relation between these buddhas and their names, see \u003ca target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh674.html#UT22084-091-072-14\" title=\"The Aparimitāyurjñāna Sūtra (1) Toh 674, i.9\"\u003e\u003ccite class=\"title text-en\" lang=\"en\"\u003eThe Aparimitāyurjñāna Sūtra\u003c/cite\u003e (1) Toh 674, i.9\u003c/a\u003e. \u003c/p\u003e"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"35:T654,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eA set of qualities necessary as a method to attain the enlightenment of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-089-013-2585\"\u003eśrāvaka\u003c/span\u003e, \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-089-013-2578\"\u003epratyekabuddha\u003c/span\u003e, or buddha. There are thirty-seven of these: (1–4) the four kinds of mindfulness: mindfulness of body, \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-089-013-2523\"\u003esensations\u003c/span\u003e, mind, and phenomena; (5–8) the four correct exertions: not to do bad actions that have not been done, to give up bad actions that are being done, to do good actions that have not been done, and to increase the good actions that are being done; (9–12) the foundations for miraculous \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-089-013-2512\"\u003epowers\u003c/span\u003e: intention, diligence, mind, and analysis; (13–17) the five \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-089-013-2512\"\u003epowers\u003c/span\u003e: faith, diligence, mindfulness, \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-089-013-2593\"\u003esamādhi\u003c/span\u003e, and wisdom; (18–22) the five \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-089-013-2530\"\u003estrengths\u003c/span\u003e: even stronger forms of faith, diligence, mindfulness, \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-089-013-2593\"\u003esamādhi\u003c/span\u003e, and wisdom; (23–29) the seven limbs of enlightenment: correct mindfulness, correct wisdom of the analysis of phenomena, correct diligence, correct joy, correct serenity, correct \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-089-013-2593\"\u003esamādhi\u003c/span\u003e, and correct equanimity; (30–37) the eightfold noble path: right view, examination, speech, action, livelihood, effort, mindfulness, and \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-089-013-2593\"\u003esamādhi\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"36:T69c,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eFirst appeared as a bodhisattva beside \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-089-013-2606\"\u003eAmitābha\u003c/span\u003e in the \u003ccite class=\"title break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eSukhāvatīvyūha Sūtra\u003c/cite\u003e ( \u003ccite class=\"title text-en\" lang=\"en\"\u003e\u003ca target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh115.html\" title=\"The Display of the Pure Land of Sukhāvatī\"\u003eThe Display of the Pure Land of Sukhāvatī\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/cite\u003e , Toh 115). The name has been variously interpreted. In its meaning as “the lord of avalokita,” \u003cem class=\"distinct\"\u003eavalokita\u003c/em\u003e has been interpreted as “seeing,” although, as a past passive participle, it is literally “lord of what has been seen.” One of the principal sūtras in the Mahāsāṃghika tradition was the \u003ccite class=\"title text-en\" lang=\"en\"\u003eAvalokita Sūtra\u003c/cite\u003e, which has not been translated into Tibetan, in which the word is a synonym for enlightenment, as it is “that which has been seen” by the buddhas. In the early tantras, he was one of the lords of the three families, as the embodiment of the compassion of the Buddhas. The Potalaka Mountain in South India became important in Southern Indian Buddhism as his residence in this world, but Potalaka does not feature in the \u003ccite class=\"title break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eKāraṇḍavyūha Sūtra\u003c/cite\u003e ( \u003ccite class=\"title text-en\" lang=\"en\"\u003e\u003ca target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh116\" title=\"The Basket’s Display\"\u003eThe Basket’s Display\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/cite\u003e , Toh 116), which is the most important sūtra dedicated to Avalokiteśvara.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003espyan ras gzigs\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"37:T414,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eAn \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-089-013-2559\"\u003easura\u003c/span\u003e king. Indian literary sources describe how Bali wrested control of the world from the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-089-013-2471\"\u003edevas\u003c/span\u003e, establishing a period of peace and prosperity with no caste distinction. \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-089-013-2656\"\u003eIndra\u003c/span\u003e requested \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-089-013-2863\"\u003eViṣṇu\u003c/span\u003e to use his wiles to gain back the world from him for the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-089-013-2471\"\u003edevas\u003c/span\u003e. \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-089-013-2863\"\u003eViṣṇu\u003c/span\u003e appeared as a dwarf asking for two steps of ground, was offered three, and then traversed the world in two steps. Bali, remaining faithful to his promise, accepted the banishment of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-089-013-2559\"\u003easuras\u003c/span\u003e into the underworld. A great Bali festival in his honor is held annually in South India. \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003eba li\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e38:T524,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eIn Buddhist literature, this is an epithet applied to buddhas, most often to Śākyamuni. The Sanskrit term generally means “possessing fortune,” but in specifically Buddhist contexts it implies that a buddha is in possession of six auspicious qualities (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhaga\u003c/em\u003e) associated with complete awakening. The Tibetan term‍—where \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebcom\u003c/em\u003e is said to refer to “subduing” the four māras, \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eldan\u003c/em\u003e to “possessing” the great qualities of buddhahood, and \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003e’das\u003c/em\u003e to “going beyond” saṃsāra and nirvāṇa‍—possibly reflects the commentarial tradition where the Sanskrit \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhagavat\u003c/em\u003e is interpreted, in addition, as “one who destroys the four māras.” This is achieved either by reading \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhagavat\u003c/em\u003e as \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhagnavat\u003c/em\u003e (“one who broke”), or by tracing the word \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhaga\u003c/em\u003e to the root \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003e√bhañj\u003c/em\u003e (“to break”).\u003c/p\u003e39:T4fc,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eThe term \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhikṣuṇī\u003c/em\u003e, often translated as “nun,” refers to the highest among the eight types of prātimokṣa vows that make one part of the Buddhist assembly. The Sanskrit term \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhikṣu\u003c/em\u003e (to which the female grammatical ending \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eṇī\u003c/em\u003e is added) literally means “beggar” or “mendicant,” referring to the fact that Buddhist nuns and monks‍—like other ascetics of the time‍—subsisted on alms (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhikṣā\u003c/em\u003e) begged from the laity. In the Tibetan tradition, which follows the Mūlasarvāstivāda Vinaya, a bhikṣuṇī follows 364 rules and a bhikṣu follows 253 rules as part of their moral discipline.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eFor the first few years of the Buddha’s teachings in India, there was no ordination for women. It started at the persistent request and display of determination of Mahāprajāpatī, the Buddha’s stepmother and aunt, together with five hundred former wives of men of Kapilavastu, who had themselves become monks. Mahāprajāpatī is thus considered to be the founder of the nun’s order.\u003c/p\u003e3a:T434,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eThe Tibetan translates both \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003estūpa\u003c/em\u003e and \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ecaitya\u003c/em\u003e with the same word, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003emchod rten\u003c/em\u003e, meaning “basis” or “recipient” of “offerings” or “veneration.” Pali: \u003cem class=\"foreign text-pi\" lang=\"pi-LATN\"\u003ecetiya\u003c/em\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eA cait"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"ya, although often synonymous with \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003estūpa\u003c/em\u003e, can also refer to any site, sanctuary or shrine that is made for veneration, and may or may not contain relics.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eA stūpa, literally “heap” or “mound,” is a mounded or circular structure usually containing relics of the Buddha or the masters of the past. It is considered to be a sacred object representing the awakened mind of a buddha, but the symbolism of the stūpa is complex, and its design varies throughout the Buddhist world. Stūpas continue to be erected today as objects of veneration and merit making. \u003c/p\u003e3b:T434,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eThe Tibetan translates both \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003estūpa\u003c/em\u003e and \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ecaitya\u003c/em\u003e with the same word, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003emchod rten\u003c/em\u003e, meaning “basis” or “recipient” of “offerings” or “veneration.” Pali: \u003cem class=\"foreign text-pi\" lang=\"pi-LATN\"\u003ecetiya\u003c/em\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eA caitya, although often synonymous with \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003estūpa\u003c/em\u003e, can also refer to any site, sanctuary or shrine that is made for veneration, and may or may not contain relics.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eA stūpa, literally “heap” or “mound,” is a mounded or circular structure usually containing relics of the Buddha or the masters of the past. It is considered to be a sacred object representing the awakened mind of a buddha, but the symbolism of the stūpa is complex, and its design varies throughout the Buddhist world. Stūpas continue to be erected today as objects of veneration and merit making. \u003c/p\u003e3c:T97d,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eAn ideal monarch or emperor who, as the result of the merit accumulated in previous lifetimes, rules over a vast realm in accordance with the Dharma. Such a monarch is called a \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ecakravartin\u003c/em\u003e because he bears a wheel (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ecakra\u003c/em\u003e) that rolls (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003evartate\u003c/em\u003e) across the earth, bringing all lands and kingdoms under his power. The cakravartin conquers his territory without causing harm, and his activity causes beings to enter the path of wholesome actions. According to Vasubandhu’s \u003ccite class=\"title break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eAbhidharmakośa\u003c/cite\u003e, just as with the buddhas, only one cakravartin appears in a world system at any given time. They are likewise endowed with the thirty-two major marks of a great being (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003emahāpuruṣalakṣaṇa\u003c/em\u003e), but a cakravartin’s marks are outshined by those of a buddha. They possess seven precious objects: the wheel, the elephant, the horse, the wish-fulfilling gem, the queen, the general, and the minister. An illustrative passage about the cakravartin and his possessions can be found in \u003ccite class=\"title text-en\" lang=\"en\"\u003eThe Play in Full\u003c/cite\u003e (Toh 95), \u003ca target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh95.html#UT22084-046-001-94\" title=\"3.3\"\u003e3.3\u003c/a\u003e–\u003ca target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh95.html#UT22084-046-001-104\" title=\"3.13\"\u003e3.13\u003c/a\u003e. \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eVasubandhu lists four types of cakravartins: (1) the cakravartin with a golden wheel (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003esuvarṇacakravartin\u003c/em\u003e) rules over four continents and is invited by lesser kings to be their ruler; (2) the cakravartin with a silver wheel (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003erūpyacakravartin\u003c/em\u003e) rules over three continents and his opponents submit to him as he approaches; (3) the cakravartin with a copper wheel (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003etāmracakravartin\u003c/em\u003e) rules over two continents and his opponents submit themselves after preparing for battle; and (4) the cakravartin with an iron wheel (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eayaścakravartin\u003c/em\u003e) rules over one continent and his opponents submit themselves after brandishing weapons. \u003c/p\u003e"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"3d:T43a,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eLiterally, “to flow” or “to ooze.” Mental defilements or contaminations that “flow out” toward the objects of cyclic existence, binding us to them. Vasubandhu offers two alternative explanations of this term: “They cause beings to remain (\u003cem class=\"foreign\"\u003eāsayanti\u003c/em\u003e) within saṃsāra” and “They flow from the Summit of Existence down to the Avīci hell, out of the six wounds that are the sense fields” (\u003ccite class=\"title\"\u003eAbhidharma­kośa­bhāṣya\u003c/cite\u003e 5.40; Pradhan 1967, p. 308). The Summit of Existence (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhavāgra\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003esrid pa’i rtse mo\u003c/em\u003e) is the highest point within saṃsāra, while the hell called Avīci (\u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003emnar med\u003c/em\u003e) is the lowest; the six sense fields (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eāyatana\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003eskye mched\u003c/em\u003e) here refer to the five sense faculties plus the mind, i.e., the six internal sense fields.\u003c/p\u003e3e:T5a8,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eIn the most general sense the devas‍—the term is cognate with the English \u003cem class=\"emph\"\u003edivine\u003c/em\u003e‍—are a class of celestial beings who frequently appear in Buddhist texts, often at the head of the assemblies of nonhuman beings who attend and celebrate the teachings of the Buddha Śākyamuni and other buddhas and bodhisattvas. In Buddhist cosmology the devas occupy the highest of the five or six “destinies” (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003egati\u003c/em\u003e) of saṃsāra among which beings take rebirth. The devas reside in the \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003edevalokas\u003c/em\u003e, “heavens” that traditionally number between twenty-six and twenty-eight and are divided between the desire realm (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ekāmadhātu\u003c/em\u003e), form realm (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003erūpadhātu\u003c/em\u003e), and formless realm (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eārūpyadhātu\u003c/em\u003e). A being attains rebirth among the devas either through meritorious deeds (in the desire realm) or the attainment of subtle meditative states (in the form and formless realms). While rebirth among the devas is considered favorable, it is ultimately a transitory state from which beings will fall when the conditions that lead to rebirth there are exhausted. Thus, rebirth in the god realms is regarded as a diversion from the spiritual path. \u003c/p\u003e"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"3f:T443,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eA series of progressively more subtle states of meditative realization or attainment. There are several presentations of these found in the canonical literature. One of the most common is as follows: (1) One observes form while the mind dwells at the level of the form realm. (2) One observes forms externally while discerning formlessness internally. (3) One dwells in the direct experience of the body’s pleasant aspect. (4) One dwells in the realization of the sphere of infinite space by transcending all conceptions of matter, resistance, and diversity. (5) Transcending the sphere of infinite space, one dwells in the realization of the sphere of infinite consciousness. (6) Transcending the sphere of infinite consciousness, one dwells in the realization of the sphere of nothingness. (7) Transcending the sphere of nothingness, one dwells in the realization of the sphere of neither perception nor nonperception. (8) Transcending the sphere of neither perception nor nonperception, one dwells in the realization of the cessation of conception and feeling.\u003c/p\u003e40:T459,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eFive impediments to meditation (\u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ebsam gtan\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003e\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-089-013-2564\"\u003edhyāna\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/em\u003e): sensory desire (\u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003e’dod pa la ’dun pa\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ekāmacchanda\u003c/em\u003e), ill will (\u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003egnod sems\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003evyāpāda\u003c/em\u003e), drowsiness and torpor (\u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ermugs pa dang gnyid\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003estyāna\u003c/em\u003e and \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003emiddha\u003c/em\u003e), agitation and regret (\u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ergod pa dang ’gyod pa\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eauddhatya\u003c/em\u003e and \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ekaukṛtya\u003c/em\u003e), and doubt (\u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ethe tshom\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003evicikitsā\u003c/em\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e41:T438,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eThe name of the southern continent in Buddhist cosmology, which can signify either the known human world, or more specifically the Indian subcontinent, literally “the \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ejambu\u003c/em\u003e island/continent.” Jambu is the name used for a range of plum-like fruits from trees belonging to the genus \u003cem class=\"foreign\"\u003eSzygium\u003c/em\u003e, particularly \u003cem class=\"foreign\"\u003eSzygium jambos\u003c/em\u003e and \u003cem class=\"foreign\"\u003eSzygium cumini\u003c/em\u003e, and it has commonly been rendered “rose apple,” although “black plum” may be a less misleading term. Among various explanations given for the continent being so named, one (in the \u003ccite class=\"title break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eAbhidharmakośa\u003c/cite\u003e) is that a jambu tree grows in its northern mountains beside Lake Anavatapta, mythically considered the source of the four great rivers of India, and that the continent is therefore named from the tree or the fruit. Jambudvīpa has the Vajrāsana at its center and is the only continent upon which buddhas attain awakening.\u003c/p\u003e42:T427,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eIn Buddhist literature refers to a mythical bird whose call is said to be far more beautiful than that of all other birds, and so compelling that it can be heard even before the bird has hatched. The call of the kalaviṅka is thus used as an analogy to describe the sound of the discourse of bodhisattvas as being far superior to that of śrāvakas and pratyekabuddhas, even before bodhisattvas attain awakening. In some cases, the kalaviṅka also takes on mythical characteristics, being depicted as part human, part bird. It is also the sixteenth of the eighty designs on the palms and soles of a tathāgata.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eWhile it is equated to an Indian bird renowned for its beautiful song, there is some uncertainty regarding the identity "])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"of the kalaviṅka; some dictionaries declare it to be a type of Indian cuckoo (probably \u003cem class=\"foreign\"\u003eEudynamys scolopacea\u003c/em\u003e, also known as the asian koel) or a red and green sparrow (possibly \u003cem class=\"foreign\"\u003eAmandava amandava\u003c/em\u003e, also known as the red avadavat).\u003c/p\u003e43:T470,\u003cp\u003e“One who belongs to the Kuśika lineage.” An epithet of the god Śakra, also known as Indra, the king of the gods in the Trāyastriṃśa heaven. In the Ṛgveda, Indra is addressed by the epithet Kauśika, with the implication that he is associated with the descendants of the Kuśika lineage (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003egotra\u003c/em\u003e) as their aiding deity. In later epic and Purāṇic texts, we find the story that Indra took birth as Gādhi Kauśika, the son of Kuśika and one of the Vedic poet-seers, after the Puru king Kuśika had performed austerities for one thousand years to obtain a son equal to Indra who could not be killed by others. In the Pāli \u003ccite class=\"title break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eKusajātaka\u003c/cite\u003e (Jāt V 141–45), the Buddha, in one of his former bodhisattva lives as a Trāyastriṃśa god, takes birth as the future king Kusa upon the request of Indra, who wishes to help the childless king of the Mallas, Okkaka, and his chief queen Sīlavatī. This story is also referred to by Nāgasena in the \u003ccite class=\"title break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eMilindapañha\u003c/cite\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e44:T66c,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eThe term can be understood to mean “great courageous one” or \"great hero,” or (from the Sanskrit) simply “great being,” and is almost always found as an epithet of “bodhisattva.” The qualification “great” in this term, according to the majority of canonical definitions, focuses on the generic greatness common to all bodhisattvas, i.e., the greatness implicit in the bodhisattva vow itself in terms of outlook, aspiration, number of beings to be benefited, potential or eventual accomplishments, and so forth. In this sense the \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003emahā-\u003c/em\u003e (“great”) is close in its connotations to the \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003emahā-\u003c/em\u003e in “Mahāyāna.” While individual bodhisattvas described as \u003cem class=\"distinct\"\u003emahāsattva\u003c/em\u003e may in many cases also be “great” in terms of their level of realization, this is largely coincidental, and in the canonical texts the epithet is not restricted to bodhisattvas at any particular point in their career. Indeed, in a few cases even bodhisattvas whose path has taken a wrong direction are still described as \u003cem class=\"distinct\"\u003ebodhisattva mahāsattva\u003c/em\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eLater commentarial writings do nevertheless define the term‍—variably‍—in terms of bodhisattvas having attained a particular level (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhūmi\u003c/em\u003e) or realization. The most common qualifying criteria mentioned are attaining the path of seeing, attaining irreversibility (according to its various definitions), or attaining the seventh bhūmi.\u003c/p\u003e"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"45:T493,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eThe bodhisattva Maitreya is an important figure in many Buddhist traditions, where he is unanimously regarded as the buddha of the future era. He is said to currently reside in the heaven of Tuṣita, as Śākyamuni’s regent, where he awaits the proper time to take his final rebirth and become the fifth buddha in the Fortunate Eon, reestablishing the Dharma in this world after the teachings of the current buddha have disappeared. Within the Mahāyāna sūtras, Maitreya is elevated to the same status as other central bodhisattvas such as Mañjuśrī and Avalokiteśvara, and his name appears frequently in sūtras, either as the Buddha’s interlocutor or as a teacher of the Dharma. \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eMaitreya\u003c/em\u003e literally means “Loving One.” He is also known as Ajita, meaning “Invincible.”\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eFor more information on Maitreya, see, for example, the introduction to \u003ccite class=\"title text-en\" lang=\"en\"\u003e\u003ca target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh198.html#UT22084-061-018-3\" title=\"Maitreya’s Setting Out\"\u003eMaitreya’s Setting Out\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/cite\u003e (Toh 198).\u003c/p\u003e46:T786,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eIn Sanskrit, the term \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003enirvāṇa\u003c/em\u003e literally means “extinguishment” and the Tibetan \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003emya ngan las ’das pa\u003c/em\u003e literally means “gone beyond sorrow.” As a general term, it refers to the cessation of all suffering, afflicted mental states (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ekleśa\u003c/em\u003e), and causal processes (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ekarman\u003c/em\u003e) that lead to rebirth and suffering in cyclic existence, as well as to the state in which all such rebirth and suffering has permanently ceased.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eMore specifically, three main types of nirvāṇa are identified. (1) The first type of nirvāṇa, called nirvāṇa with remainder (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003esopadhiśeṣanirvāṇa\u003c/em\u003e), is the state in which arhats or buddhas have attained awakening but are still dependent on the conditioned aggregates until their lifespan is exhausted. (2) At the end of life, given that there are no more causes for rebirth, these aggregates cease and no new aggregates arise. What occurs then is called nirvāṇa without remainder (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003e anupadhiśeṣanirvāṇa\u003c/em\u003e), which refers to the unconditioned element (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003edhātu\u003c/em\u003e) of nirvāṇa in which there is no remainder of the aggregates. (3) The Mahāyāna teachings distinguish the final nirvāṇa of buddhas from that of arhats, the nirvāṇa of arhats not being considered ultimate. The buddhas attain what is called nonabiding nirvāṇa (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eapratiṣṭhitanirvāṇa\u003c/em\u003e), which transcends the extremes of saṃsāra and nirvāṇa, i.e., existence and peace. This is the nirvāṇa that is the goal of the Mahāyāna path.\u003c/p\u003e"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"47:T430,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eThis term is used to refer to the main trainings of a bodhisattva. Because these trainings, when brought to perfection, lead one to transcend \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-089-013-2583\"\u003esaṃsāra\u003c/span\u003e and reach the full awakening of a buddha, they receive the Sanskrit name \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003epāramitā\u003c/em\u003e, meaning “perfection” or “gone to the farther shore.” They are usually listed as six: generosity, correct conduct (or discipline), patience, diligence, meditation (or concentration), and wisdom; four additional perfections are often added to this, totalling ten perfections: skillful methods, prayer, strength, and knowledge. \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eFor a presentation of each one according to the view of this sūtra, see \u003ca href=\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh555#UT22084-089-012-1077\" target=\"UT22084-089-012.html\" data-pointer-type=\"id\"\u003e6.6\u003c/a\u003e–\u003ca href=\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh555#UT22084-089-012-1129\" target=\"UT22084-089-012.html\" data-pointer-type=\"id\"\u003e6.27\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e48:T44b,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eLiterally, “buddha for oneself” or “solitary realizer.” Someone who, in his or her last life, attains awakening entirely through their own contemplation, without relying on a teacher. Unlike the awakening of a fully realized buddha (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003esamyaksambuddha\u003c/em\u003e), the accomplishment of a pratyeka­buddha is not regarded as final or ultimate. They attain realization of the nature of dependent origination, the selflessness of the person, and a partial realization of the selflessness of phenomena, by observing the suchness of all that arises through interdependence. This is the result of progress in previous lives but, unlike a buddha, they do not have the necessary merit, compassion or motivation to teach others. They are named as “rhinoceros-like” (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ekhaḍgaviṣāṇakalpa\u003c/em\u003e) for their preference for staying in solitude or as “congregators” (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003evargacārin\u003c/em\u003e) when their preference is to stay among peers.\u003c/p\u003e49:T55b,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eOne of the five or six classes of sentient beings, into which beings are born as the karmic fruition of past miserliness. As the term in Sanskrit means “the departed,” they are analogous to the ancestral spirits of Vedic tradition, the \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003epitṛ\u003c/em\u003es, who starve without the offerings of descendants. It is also commonly translated as “hungry ghost” or “starving spirit,” as in the Chinese \u003cem class=\"foreign text-zh\" lang=\"zh\"\u003e餓鬼\u003c/em\u003e \u003cem class=\"foreign\"\u003ee gui\u003c/em\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eThey are sometimes said to reside in the realm of Yama, but are also frequently described as roaming charnel grounds and other inhospitable or frightening places along with piśācas and other such beings. They are particularly known to suffer from great hunger and thirst and the inability to acquire sustenance. Detailed descriptions of their realm and experience, including a list of the thirty-six classes of pretas, can be found in \u003ccite class=\"title text-en\" lang=\"en\"\u003eThe Application of Mindfulness of the Sacred Dharma\u003c/cite\u003e, Toh 287, \u003ca target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh287.html#UT22084-068-021-1672\" title=\"2.­1281\"\u003e2.­1281\u003c/a\u003e– \u003ca target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh287.html#UT22084-068-021-1902\" title=\"2.1482\"\u003e2.1482\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e4a:Tc0f,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"\u003cp\u003eThe subsidiary afflictive emotions that arise in dependence upon the six root afflictive emotions (attachment, hatred, pride, ignorance, doubt, and wrong view); they are (1) anger (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ekrodha\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ekhro ba\u003c/em\u003e), (2) enmity/malice (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eupanāha\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003e’khon ’dzin\u003c/em\u003e), (3) concealment (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003emrakśa\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003e’chab pa\u003c/em\u003e), (4) outrage (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003epradāsa\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003e’tshig pa\u003c/em\u003e), (5) jealousy (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eīrśya\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ephrag dog\u003c/em\u003e), (6) miserliness (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ematsarya\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003eser sna\u003c/em\u003e), (7) deceit (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003e\u003cspan\u003emāyā\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003esgyu\u003c/em\u003e), (8) dishonesty (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eśāṭhya\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003eg.yo\u003c/em\u003e), (9) haughtiness (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003emada\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ergyags pa\u003c/em\u003e), (10) harmfulness (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003evihiṃsa\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ernam par ’tshe ba\u003c/em\u003e), (11) shamelessness (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eāhrīkya\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003engo tsha med pa\u003c/em\u003e), (12) non-consideration (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eanapatrāpya\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ekhril med pa\u003c/em\u003e), (13) lack of faith (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eaśraddhya\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ema dad pa\u003c/em\u003e), (14) laziness (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ekausīdya\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ele lo\u003c/em\u003e), (15) non-conscientiousness (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003epramāda\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ebag med pa\u003c/em\u003e), (16) forgetfulness (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003emuśitasmṛtitā\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ebrjed nges\u003c/em\u003e), (17) non-introspection (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003easaṃprajanya\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003eshes bzhin ma yin pa\u003c/em\u003e), (18) dullness (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003enigmagṇa\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ebying ba\u003c/em\u003e), (19) agitation (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eauddhatya\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ergod pa\u003c/em\u003e), and (20) distraction (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003evikṣepa\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ernam g.yeng\u003c/em\u003e) (Rigzin 329, 129).\u003c/p\u003e"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"4b:T5e8,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eA bodhisattva famous for his quest for the Dharma and for his devotion to the teacher. It is told that Sadāprarudita, in order to make offerings to the bodhisattva Dharmodgata and request the Prajñāpāramitā teachings, sets out to sell his own flesh and blood. After receiving a first set of teachings, Sadāprarudita waits seven years for the bodhisattva Dharmodgata, his teacher, to emerge from meditation. When he receives signs this is about to happen, he wishes to prepare the ground for the teachings by settling the dust. Māra makes all the water disappear, so Sadāprarudita decides to use his own blood to settle the dust. He is said to be practicing in the presence of Buddha Bhīṣma­garjita­nirghoṣa­svara. His name means \"Ever Weeping\", on account of the numerous tears he shed until he found the teachings. \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eHis story is told in detail by the Buddha in \u003ccite class=\"title text-en\" lang=\"en\"\u003e\u003ca target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh10.html\" title=\"The Perfection of Wisdom in Eighteen Thousand Lines\"\u003eThe Perfection of Wisdom in Eighteen Thousand Lines\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/cite\u003e (Toh 10, ch. 85–86), and can be found quoted in several works, such as \u003ccite class=\"title text-en\" lang=\"en\"\u003eThe Words of My Perfect Teacher\u003c/cite\u003e (\u003ccite class=\"title text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ekun bzang bla ma’i zhal lung\u003c/cite\u003e) by Patrul Rinpoche.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ertag tu bshums\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"4c:T4c7,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eIn a general sense, \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003esamādhi\u003c/em\u003e can describe a number of different meditative states. In the Mahāyāna literature, in particular in the Prajñāpāramitā sūtras, we find extensive lists of different samādhis, numbering over one hundred.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eIn a more restricted sense, and when understood as a mental state, \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003esamādhi\u003c/em\u003e is defined as the one-pointedness of the mind (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ecittaikāgratā\u003c/em\u003e), the ability to remain on the same object over long periods of time. The \u003ccite class=\"title text-en\" lang=\"en\"\u003eDrajor Bamponyipa\u003c/cite\u003e (\u003ccite class=\"title text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003esgra sbyor bam po gnyis pa\u003c/cite\u003e) commentary on the \u003ccite class=\"title break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eMahāvyutpatti\u003c/cite\u003e explains the term \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003esamādhi\u003c/em\u003e as referring to the instrument through which mind and mental states “get collected,” i.e., it is by the force of samādhi that the continuum of mind and mental states becomes collected on a single point of reference without getting distracted.\u003c/p\u003e4d:T4aa,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eThe Buddha’s speech is said to have sixty aspects and sometimes sixty-four. The list of sixty, as given in Maitreyanātha’s \u003ccite class=\"title break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eMahāyāna­sūtrālaṃkāra\u003c/cite\u003e, are (1) ripening, (2) smooth, (3) direct, (4) cogent, (5) correct, (6) stainless, (7) clear, (8) harmonious, (9) proper, (10) undefeatable, (11) meaningful, (12) taming, (13) gentle, (14) kind, (15) completely taming, (16) pleasing, (17) refreshing, (18) soothing, (19) gladdening, (20) blissful, (21) fulfilling, (22) worthwhile, (23) meaningful, (24) comprehensive, (25) reassuring, (26) inspiring, (27) enlightening, (28) instructive, (29) logical, (30) pertinent, (31) exact, (32) powerful, (33) fearless, (34) unfathomable, (35) majestic, (36) melodious, (37) sustaining, (38) long-lasting, (39) auspicious, (40) authoritative, (41) exhortative, (42) selfless, (43) confident, (44) omniscient, (45) whole, (46) complete, (47) certain, (48) desireless, (49) exhilarating, (50) pervasive, (51) stimulating, (52) continuous, (53) consistent, (54) multilingual, (55) adaptive, (56) reliable, (57) timely, (58) calm, (59) pervasive, and (60) perfecting.\u003c/p\u003e4e:T4b9,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eThe Sanskrit term \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eśrāvaka\u003c/em\u003e, and the Tibetan \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003enyan thos\u003c/em\u003e, both derived from the verb “to hear,” are usually defined as “those who \u003cem class=\"emph\"\u003ehear\u003c/em\u003e the teaching from the Buddha and \u003cem class=\"emph\"\u003emake it heard\u003c/em\u003e to others.” Primarily this refers to those disciples of the Buddha who aspire to attain the state of an arhat seeking their own liberation and nirvāṇa. They are the practitioners of the first turning of the wheel of the Dharma on the four noble truths, who realize the suffering inherent in saṃsāra and focus on understanding that there is no independent self. By conquering afflicted mental states (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ekleśa\u003c/em\u003e), they liberate themselves, attaining first the stage of stream enterers at the path of seeing, followed by the stage of once-returners who will be reborn only one more time, and then the stage of non-returners who will no longer be reborn into the desire realm. The final goal is to become an arhat. These four stages are also known as the “four results of spiritual practice.”\u003c/p\u003e4f:T111a,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eThe five Pure Abodes are the highest heavens of the Form Realm (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003erūpadhātu\u003c/em\u003e). They are called “pure abodes” because ordinary beings (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003epṛthagjana\u003c/em\u003e; \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003eso so’i skye bo\u003c/em\u003e) cannot be born there; only those who have achieved the fruit of a non-returner (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eanāgāmin\u003c/em\u003e; \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ephyir mi ’ong\u003c/em\u003e) can be born there. A summary presentation of them is found in the third chapter of Vasubandhu's \u003ccite class=\"title text-en\" lang=\"en\"\u003eAbhidharmakośa\u003c/cite\u003e, although they are repeatedly mentioned as a set in numerous sūtras, tantras, and vinaya texts.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eThe five Pure Abodes are the last five of the seventeen levels of the Form Realm. Specifically, they are the last five of the eight levels of the upper Form Realm‍—which corresponds to the fourth meditative concentration (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003edhyāna\u003c/em\u003e; \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ebsam gtan\u003c/em\u003e)‍—all of which are described as “immovable” (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eakopya\u003c/em\u003e; \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003emi g.yo ba\u003c/em\u003e) since they are never destroyed during the cycles of the destruction and reformation of a world system. In particular, the five are Abṛha (\u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003emi che ba\u003c/em\u003e), the inferior heaven; Atapa (\u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003emi gdung ba\u003c/em\u003e), the heaven of no torment; Sudṛśa (\u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003egya nom snang\u003c/em\u003e), the heaven of sublime appearances; Sudarśana (\u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003eshin tu mthong\u003c/em\u003e), the heaven of the most beautiful to behold; and Akaniṣṭha (\u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003e’og min\u003c/em\u003e), the highest heaven.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eYaśomitra explains their names, stating: (1) because those who abide there can only remain for a fixed amount of time, before they are plucked out (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003e√bṛh\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebṛṃhanti\u003c/em\u003e) of that heaven, or because it is not as extensive (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eabṛṃhita\u003c/em\u003e) as the others in the pure realms, that heaven is called the inferior heaven (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eabṛha\u003c/em\u003e; \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003emi che ba\u003c/em\u003e); (2) since the afflictions can no longer torment (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003e√tap\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003etapanti\u003c/em\u003e) those who reside there because of their having attained a particular samādhi, or because their state of mind is virtuous, they no longer torment (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003e√tap\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003etāpayanti\u003c/em\u003e) others, this heaven, consequently, is called the heaven of no torment (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eatapa\u003c/em\u003e; \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003emi gdung ba\u003c/em\u003e); (3) since those who reside there have exceptional (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003esuṣṭhu\u003c/em\u003e) vision because what they see (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003e√dṛś\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003edarśana\u003c/em\u003e) is utterly pure, that heaven is called the heaven of sublime appearances (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003esudṛśa\u003c/em\u003e; \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003egya nom snang\u003c/em\u003e); (4) because those who reside there are beautiful gods, that heaven is called the heaven of the most beautiful to behold (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003esudarśana\u003c/em\u003e; \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003eshin tu mthong\u003c/em\u003e); and (5) since it is not lower (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ena kaniṣṭhā\u003c/em\u003e) than any other heaven because there is no other place superior to it, this heaven is called the highest heaven (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eakaniṣṭha\u003c/em\u003e; \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003e’og min\u003c/em\u003e) since it is the uppermost.\u003c/p\u003e"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"50:T4e8,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eOne of the standard epithets of the buddhas. A recurrent explanation offers three different meanings for \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003esu-\u003c/em\u003e that are meant to show the special qualities of “accomplishment of one’s own purpose” (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003esvārthasampad\u003c/em\u003e) for a complete buddha. Thus, the Sugata is “well” gone, as in the expression \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003esu-rūpa\u003c/em\u003e (“having a good form”); he is gone “in a way that he shall not come back,” as in the expression \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003esu-naṣṭa-jvara\u003c/em\u003e (“a fever that has utterly gone”); and he has gone “without any remainder” as in the expression \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003esu-pūrṇa-ghaṭa\u003c/em\u003e (“a pot that is completely full”). According to Buddhaghoṣa, the term means that the way the Buddha went (Skt. \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003egata\u003c/em\u003e) is good (Skt. \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003esu\u003c/em\u003e) and where he went (Skt. \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003egata\u003c/em\u003e) is good (Skt. \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003esu\u003c/em\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e51:T469,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eA frequently used synonym for \u003cem class=\"emph\"\u003ebuddha\u003c/em\u003e. According to different explanations, it can be read as \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003etathā-gata\u003c/em\u003e, literally meaning “one who has thus gone,” or as \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003etathā-āgata\u003c/em\u003e, “one who has thus come.” \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eGata\u003c/em\u003e, though literally meaning “gone,” is a past passive participle used to describe a state or condition of existence. \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eTatha­(tā)\u003c/em\u003e, often rendered as “suchness” or “thusness,” is the quality or condition of things as they really are, which cannot be conveyed in conceptual, dualistic terms. Therefore, this epithet is interpreted in different ways, but in general it implies one who has departed in the wake of the buddhas of the past, or one who has manifested the supreme awakening dependent on the reality that does not abide in the two extremes of existence and quiescence. It is also often used as a specific epithet of the Buddha Śākyamuni.\u003c/p\u003e52:T49d,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eThose of other religious or philosophical orders, contemporary with the early Buddhist order, including Jains, Jaṭilas, Ājīvikas, and Cārvākas. Tīrthika (“forder”) literally translates as “one belonging to or associated with (possessive suffix \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003e–ika\u003c/em\u003e) stairs for landing or for descent into a river,” or “a bathing place,” or “a place of pilgrimage on the banks of sacred streams” (Monier-Williams). The term may have originally referred to temple priests at river crossings or fords where travelers propitiated a deity before crossing. The Sanskrit term seems to have undergone metonymic transfer in referring to those able to ford the turbulent river of saṃsāra (as in the Jain tīrthaṅkaras, “ford makers”), and it came to be used in Buddhist sources to refer to teachers of rival religious traditions. The Sanskrit term is closely rendered by the Tibetan \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003emu stegs pa\u003c/em\u003e: “those on the steps (\u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003estegs pa\u003c/em\u003e) at the edge (\u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003emu\u003c/em\u003e).”\u003c/p\u003e53:T556,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eTuṣita (or sometimes Saṃtuṣita), literally “Joyous” or “Contented,” is one of the six heavens of the desire realm (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ekāmadhātu\u003c/em\u003e). In standard classifications, such as the one in the \u003ccite class=\"title break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eAbhidharmakośa\u003c/cite\u003e, it is ranked as the fourth of the six counting from below. This god realm is where all future buddhas are said to dwell before taking on their final rebir"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"th prior to awakening. There, the Buddha Śākyamuni lived his preceding life as the bodhisattva Śvetaketu. When departing to take birth in this world, he appointed the bodhisattva Maitreya, who will be the next buddha of this eon, as his Dharma regent in Tuṣita. For an account of the Buddha’s previous life in Tuṣita, see \u003ccite class=\"title text-en\" lang=\"en\"\u003eThe Play in Full\u003c/cite\u003e (Toh 95), \u003ca target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://read.84000.co/translation/UT22084-046-001.html#UT22084-046-001-68\" title=\"2.12\"\u003e2.12\u003c/a\u003e, and for an account of Maitreya’s birth in Tuṣita and a description of this realm, see \u003ccite class=\"title text-en\" lang=\"en\"\u003e\u003ca target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh199.html\" title=\"The Sūtra on Maitreya’s Birth in the Heaven of Joy\"\u003eThe Sūtra on Maitreya’s Birth in the Heaven of Joy\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/cite\u003e, (Toh 199).\u003c/p\u003e"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"18:[\"$\",\"$L1f\",null,{\"abbreviations\":[{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"534dc0f1-0060-4518-b1da-99f3a87c2e25\",\"sort\":17353,\"type\":\"abbreviationsHeader\",\"label\":\"ab.\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":2,\"start\":0,\"end\":13,\"uuid\":\"ca891ed3-f192-43cc-9508-edb58a7bf449\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Abbreviations\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":13}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1760fb4d-eafd-4351-826f-f7ebd3aa3c88\",\"sort\":17354,\"type\":\"abbreviations\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"class\":\"flex flex-row gap-2\",\"start\":0,\"end\":57,\"uuid\":\"1760fb4d-eafd-4351-826f-f7ebd3aa3c88\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"abbreviation\",\"text\":\"BG \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":3,\"abbreviation\":\"1760fb4d-eafd-4351-826f-f7ebd3aa3c88\",\"uuid\":\"b99e5e29-5f9f-40f3-a6d7-350e8e31f02c\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"BG \"}]},{\"type\":\"hasAbbreviation\",\"text\":\"Translation by Bao Gui 寶貴, titled 合部金光明經 (Taishō 664).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":3,\"end\":57,\"abbreviation\":\"1760fb4d-eafd-4351-826f-f7ebd3aa3c88\",\"uuid\":\"9dcfb860-3312-4708-b221-96e0992a941c\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation by Bao Gui 寶貴, titled 合部金光明經 (Taishō 664).\"}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"781847f4-d616-4819-8bf5-962b7070b0f7\",\"sort\":17360,\"type\":\"abbreviations\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"class\":\"flex flex-row gap-2\",\"start\":0,\"end\":80,\"uuid\":\"781847f4-d616-4819-8bf5-962b7070b0f7\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"abbreviation\",\"text\":\"TWC \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":4,\"abbreviation\":\"781847f4-d616-4819-8bf5-962b7070b0f7\",\"uuid\":\"f094134d-ca4f-4e8e-ba88-cdf2268b5612\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"TWC \"}]},{\"type\":\"hasAbbreviation\",\"text\":\"Translation by Dharmakṣema, a.k.a. Tan Wuchen 曇無讖, titled 金光明經 (Taishō 663).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":4,\"end\":80,\"abbreviation\":\"781847f4-d616-4819-8bf5-962b7070b0f7\",\"uuid\":\"6892970a-3227-47bd-81f1-0597a5f01e9c\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation by Dharmakṣema, a.k.a. Tan Wuchen 曇無讖, titled 金光明經 (Taishō 663).\"}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c4ca18c9-e54c-4b36-8e57-5ffe887182f8\",\"sort\":17366,\"type\":\"abbreviations\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"class\":\"flex flex-row gap-2\",\"start\":0,\"end\":57,\"uuid\":\"c4ca18c9-e54c-4b36-8e57-5ffe887182f8\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"abbreviation\",\"text\":\"YJ \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":3,\"abbreviation\":\"c4ca18c9-e54c-4b36-8e57-5ffe887182f8\",\"uuid\":\"029728a0-37d9-4ca1-838a-2917e45b4fc6\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"YJ \"}]},{\"type\":\"hasAbbreviation\",\"text\":\"Translation by Yijing 義淨, titled 金光明最勝王經 (Taishō 665).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":3,\"end\":57,\"abbreviation\":\"c4ca18c9-e54c-4b36-8e57-5ffe887182f8\",\"uuid\":\"920c5f44-b5c0-447a-9cf3-7df6466c5111\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation by Yijing 義淨, titled 金光明最勝王經 (Taishō 665).\"}]}]}]}],\"bibliography\":[{\"heading\":\"Primary Sources in Tibetan and Chinese\",\"entries\":[{\"uuid\":\"934db7e1-c7b1-4f02-85b1-32b943976ff5\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003egser ’od dam pa’i mdo\u003c/em\u003e. Toh 555, Degé Kangyur vol. 89 (rgyud ’bum, pa), folios 19.a–151a. English translation \u003cem\u003e\u003ca href=\\\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh555\\\"\u003eThe Sūtra of the Sublime Golden Light (1)\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/em\u003e 2023.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"f5556d52-436b-4c38-9f4b-78c9fbdd8d63\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003egser ’od dam pa mdo sde’i dbang po’i rgyal po zhes bya ba theg pa chen po’i mdo\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eSuvarṇa­prabhāsottama­sūtrendra­rājanāma­mahāyāna­sūtra\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 556, Degé Kangyur vol. 89 (rgyud ’bum, pa), folios 151.b–273.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"fe86650a-2a94-437d-839a-2328f14ddf8a\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003egser ’od dam pa mdo sde’i dbang po’i rgyal po zhes bya ba theg pa chen po’i mdo\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eSuvarṇa­prabhāsottama­sūtrendra­rāja­nāma­mahāyāna­sūtra\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 557, Degé Kangyur vol. 90 (rgyud ’bum, pha), folios 1.a–62.a. English translation \u003cem\u003e\u003ca href=\\\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh557\\\"\u003eThe Sūtra of the Sublime Golden Light (3)\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/em\u003e 2024.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"7af7515b-d3ca-4c5a-8a1b-9e9ead85ed27\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003eHebu jin guangming\u003c/em\u003e \u003cem\u003e合部金光明經\u003c/em\u003e. Taishō 664 (\u003ca href=\\\"https://cbetaonline.dila.edu.tw/en/T0664\\\"\u003eCBETA\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\\\"https://21dzk.l.u-tokyo.ac.jp/SAT2018/T0664.html\\\"\u003eSAT\u003c/a\u003e). (Translation of \u003cem\u003eSuvarṇa­prabhāsottama­sūtra\u003c/em\u003e by Bao Gui \u003cem\u003e寶貴\u003c/em\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"71f2442a-530f-43d5-803b-ab6eb9d38103\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003eJin guangming jin\u003c/em\u003e \u003cem\u003e金光明經\u003c/em\u003e. Taishō 663 (\u003ca href=\\\"https://cbetaonline.dila.edu.tw/en/T0663\\\"\u003eCBETA\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\\\"https://21dzk.l.u-tokyo.ac.jp/SAT2018/T0663.html\\\"\u003eSAT\u003c/a\u003e). (Translation of \u003cem\u003eSuvarṇa­prabhāsottama­sūtra\u003c/em\u003e by Dharmakṣema, a.k.a. Tan Wuchen \u003cem\u003e曇無讖\u003c/em\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"bf2047fc-ee67-4246-8377-da6f6decb39c\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003eJin guangming zuisheng wang jin\u003c/em\u003e \u003cem\u003e金光明最勝王經\u003c/em\u003e. Taishō 665 (\u003ca href=\\\"https://cbetaonline.dila.edu.tw/en/T0665\\\"\u003eCBETA\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\\\"https://21dzk.l.u-tokyo.ac.jp/SAT2018/T0665.html\\\"\u003eSAT\u003c/a\u003e). (Translation of \u003cem\u003eSuvarṇa­prabhāsottama­sūtra\u003c/em\u003e by Yijing \u003cem\u003e義淨\u003c/em\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null}]},{\"heading\":\"Secondary References—Kangyur\",\"entries\":[{\"uuid\":\"477b2040-6b9b-4043-a076-37ea67f26c94\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003edkyil ’khor thams cad kyi spyi’i cho ga gsang ba’i rgyud\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eSarva­maṇḍala­sāmānyavidhi­guhya­tantra\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 806, Degé Kangyur vol. 96 (rgyud, wa), folios 141.a–167.b. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"155afcc2-599d-482a-a8b4-c4b9c8de30bc\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003e’jam dpal gyi rtsa ba’i rgyud\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eMañjuśrīmūlakalpa\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 543, Degé Kangyur vol.88 (rgyud, na), folios 105.a–351.a. English translation \u003cem\u003e\u003ca href=\\\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh543\\\"\u003eThe Root Manual of the Rites of Mañjuśrī\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/em\u003e 2020.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"6fd8e1a7-d2d5-42d0-82bd-a0508b96140d\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003e’od srung kyi le’u zhes bya ba theg pa chen po’i mdo\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eKāśyapa­parivarta­nāma­mahāyāna­sūtra\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 87, Degé Kangyur vol. 44 (dkon brtsegs, cha), folios 119.b–151.b. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"8b688c99-eae5-4093-823c-74f455eaa014\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003eral pa gyen brdzes kyi rtog pa chen po byang chub sems dpa’ chen po’i rnam par ’phrul pa le’u rab ’byams las bcom ldan ’das ma ’phags ma sgrol ma’i rtsa ba’i rtog pa zhes bya ba\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eŪrdhvajaṭā­mahā­kalpa­mahā­bodhi­sattva­vikurvaṇa­paṭalavisarā bhagavatī ārya­tārā­mūla­kalpa­nāma\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 724, Degé Kangyur vol. 93 (rgyud, tsa), folios 205.b–311.a, and vol. 94 (rgyud, tsha), folios 1.a–200.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"e04e9d32-5841-4be3-9550-33e3d55a2710\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003eblo gros mi zad pas zhus pa zhes bya ba theg pa chen po’i mdo\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eAkṣaya­mati­paripṛcchā­nāma­mahāyāna­sūtra\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 89, Degé Kangyur vol. 44 (dkon brtsegs, cha), folios 175.b–182.b.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"efbef59b-abd4-4b2f-8325-182b3457e08a\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003elang kar gshegs pa’i theg pa chen po’i mdo\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eLaṅkāvatāra­mahāyāna­sūtra\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 107, Degé Kangyur vol. 49 (mdo sde, ca), folios 56.a–191.b.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"d8f46541-456e-41a4-9666-67cc169c47ba\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003elas kyi sgrib pa gcod pa zhes bya ba theg pa chen po’i mdo\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eKarmā­varaṇa­prati­praśrabdhi­nāma­mahāyāna­sūtra\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 219, Degé Kangyur vol. 62 (mdo sde, tsha), folios 297.b–307.a. English translation \u003cem\u003e\u003ca href=\\\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh219\\\"\u003ePutting an End to Karmic Obscurations\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/em\u003e 2024.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null}]},{\"heading\":\"Secondary References—Tengyur\",\"entries\":[{\"uuid\":\"2eeb42ec-d659-4366-bab3-8d856b6b5664\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eAjitaśrībhadra. \u003cem\u003edga’ ba’i bshes gnyen gyi rtogs pa\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eNandamitrāvadāna\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 4146, Degé Tengyur vol. 269 (’dul ba, su), folios 240.a–244.b.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"10ff20c0-e5e4-4b0d-9c42-f55e2b661a9e\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eĀnandagarbha. \u003cem\u003erdo rje dbyings kyi dkyil ’khor chen po’i cho ga rdo rje thams cad ’byungs ba\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eVajra­dhātu­mahā­maṇḍalopāyikā­sarva­vajrodaya\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 2516, Degé Tengyur vol. 62 (rgyud, ku), folios 1.a–50.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"b2a04aa3-05de-4334-bba4-10ef13960b26\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eAnonymous. \u003cem\u003ergyal po gser gyi lag pa’i smon lam\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eRāja­suvarṇa­bhuja­praṇidhāna\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 4380, Degé Tengyur vol. 309 (sna tshogs, nyo), folios 309b–310a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"ef0e8b02-1791-45fe-b001-191d983e32ab\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eAnonymous. \u003cem\u003e’jam pa’i rdo rje ’byung ba’i dkyil ’khor gyi cho ga sems can thams cad kyi bde ba bskyed pa\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eMañju­vajrodaya­maṇḍalopāyikā­sarva­sattva­hitāvahā\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 2590, Degé Tengyur vol. 65 (rgyud, ngu), folios 225.a–274.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"a116f427-0d4c-45a1-9a9b-b7bde4f2bf0f\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eAnonymous. \u003cem\u003egser ’od dam pa mdo sde dbang po’i smon lam\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eSuvarṇa­prabhāsottama­sūtrendra­praṇidhāna\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 4379, Degé Tengyur vol. 309 (sna tshogs, nyo), folios 304.b–309.b.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"0e617ff9-af9d-44f5-97ce-6c6d0a869208\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eĀryadeva. \u003cem\u003espyod pa bsdud pa’i sgron ma\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eCaryāmelāpaka­pradīpa\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 1803, Degé Tengyur vol. 65 (rgyud, ngi), folios 57.a–106.b.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"73f7a6e3-5abe-49b3-9001-37dac774892d\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eBhavya. \u003cem\u003edbu ma rin po che’i sgron ma\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eMadhyamaka­ratna­pradīpa\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 3854, Degé Tengyur vol. 199 (dbu ma, tsha), folios 259.b–289.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"ba30bb24-c5dd-4cad-808d-4e70f947288b\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eBhavyakīrti. \u003cem\u003esgron ma gsal bar byed pa dgongs pa rab gsal zhes bya ba bshad pa’i ti ka\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003ePradīpoddyotanābhisaṁdhi­prakāśikā­nāma­vyākhyā­ṭīkā\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 1793, Degé Tengyur vols. 32–33 (rgyud, ki), folios 1.b–292.a, and (rgyud, khi), folios 1.b–155.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"198741bf-b279-4f02-b2ed-8ae04f7f12d1\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eBodhisattva. \u003cem\u003ekun nas sgor ’jug pa’i ’od zer gtsug tor dri ma med par snang ba’i gzungs bklag cing chod rten brgya rtsa brgyad dam mchod rten lnga gdab pa’i cho ga mdo sde las btus pa\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eSamanta­mukha­praveśa­raśmi­vimaloṣṇīṣa­prabhāsa­dhāraṇī­vacana­sūtrāntoddhṛtāṣṭottara­śata­caityāntara­pañca­caitya­nirvapaṇa­vidhi\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 3068, Degé Tengyur vol. 74 (rgyud, pu), folios 140.a–153.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"1199ff28-d0bd-4179-b627-0fdbb4435ecd\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eBuddhānandagarbha. \u003cem\u003ede bzhin gshegs pa dgra bcom pa yang dag par rdzogs pa’i sangs rgyas ngan song thams cad yongs su sbyong ba gzi brjid kyi rgyal po zhes bya ba’i bshad pa\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eSarva­durgati­pariśodhana­tejorāja­tathāgatārhat­samyaksaṃbuddha­nāma­kalpa­ṭīkā\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 2628, Degé Tengyur vol. 68 (rgyud, ju), folios 1.a–97.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"77fbcefe-4600-43c6-88b3-83b8323a8678\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eDharmakīrtiśrī. \u003cem\u003eshes rab kyi pha rol tu phyin pa’i man ngag gi bstan bcos mngon par rtogs pa’i rgyan zhes bya ba’i ’grel pa rtogs par dka’ ba’i snang ba zhes bya ba’i ’grel bshad\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eAbhisamayālaṃkāra­nāma­prajñā­pāramitopadeśa­śāstra­vṛtti­durbodhāloka­nāma­ṭīkā\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 3794, Degé Tengyur vol. 86 (sher phyin, ja), folios 140.b–254.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"d5f766b6-dc21-4e30-9ef1-5f764348984c\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eDharmamitra. \u003cem\u003eshes rab kyi pha rol tu phyin pa’i man ngag gi bstan bcos mngon par rtogs pa’i rgyan gyi tshig le’ur byas pa’i ’grel bshad tshig rab tu gsal ba\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eAbhisamayālaṃkāra­kārikā­prajñā­pāramitopadeśa­śāstra­ṭīkāprasphuṭapadā\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 3796, Degé Tengyur vol. 87 (sher phyin, nya), folios 1.a–110.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"b9edabf4-a5a6-40d4-81b9-18623c9d4b35\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eDīpaṁkaraśrījñāna. \u003cem\u003edbu ma’i man ngag rin po che’i za ma tog kha phye ba zhes bya ba\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eRatna­karaṇḍodghāṭa­nāma­madhyamakopadeśa\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 3930, Degé Tengyur vol. 212 (dbu ma, ki), folios 96.b–116.b.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"b80c2c6e-ebef-4d6e-9a34-978e8bcfe6f8\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eDīpaṁkaraśrījñāna. \u003cem\u003ebyang chub lam gyi sgron ma’i dka’ ’grel\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eBodhi­mārga­pradīpa­pañjikā\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 3948, Degé Tengyur vol. 213 (mdo ’grel, khi), folios 241.a–293.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"a4789f4b-7aed-411a-ace9-239b4a86c9b1\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eDīpaṁkaraśrījñāna. \u003cem\u003emngon par rtogs pa rnam par ’byed pa zhes bya ba\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eAbhisamaya­vibhaṅga­nāma\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 1490, Degé Tengyur vol. 22 (rgyud, zha), folios 186.a–202.b.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"2421c194-4f01-411b-b61b-74be20e569e7\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eEkādaśanirghoṣa. \u003cem\u003erdo rje ’chang chen po’i lam gyi rim pa’i man ngag bdud rtsi gsang ba\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eMahā­vajra­dhara­patha­kramopadeśāmṛta­guhya\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 1823, Degé Tengyur vol. 35 (rgyud, ngi), folios 267.b–278.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"efca091a-4839-4769-b187-5eb4adbecf1b\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eHaribhadra. \u003cem\u003eshes rab kyi pha rol tu phyin pa brgyad stong pa’i bshad pa mngon par rtogs pa’i rgyan gyi snang ba\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eAṣṭa­sāhasrikā­prajñā­pāramitā­vyākhyānābhi­samayālaṃkārāloka\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 3791, Degé Tengyur vol. 85 (sher phyin, cha), folios 1.a–341.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"d23a6da7-79e8-426f-9460-7e725d6322db\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eKāmadhenu. \u003cem\u003engan song thams cad yongs su sbyong ba gzi brjid kyi rgyal po zhes bya ba cho ga zhib mo’i rgyal po chen po’i rgya cher ’grel pa\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eSarva­durgati­pariśodhana­tejorāja­nāma­mahā­kalpa­rāja­ṭīkā\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 2625, Degé Tengyur vol. 666 (rgyud, cu), folios 231.a–341.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"7ef13d93-00c8-4c75-b201-ad6fc109ea71\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eMañjuśrīkīrti. \u003cem\u003e’jam dpal gyi mtshan yang dag par brjod pa’i rgya cher bshad pa\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eMañjuśrī­nāma­saṃgīti­ṭīkā\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 2534, Degé Tengyur vol. 63 (gyud, khu), folios 115.b–301.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"4d151250-3eb0-4a41-bc37-e9473f0a30ed\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003ePaltsek (dpal brtsegs). \u003cem\u003egsung rab rin po che’i gtam rgyud dang shA kya’i rabs rgyud\u003c/em\u003e. Toh 4357, Degé Tengyur vol. 306 (sna tshogs, co), folios 239.a–377.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"d8d55cd6-8195-4853-a547-813c2c876bfb\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003ePaltsek (dpal brtsegs). \u003cem\u003epho brang stod thang lhan dkar gyi chos ’gyur ro cog gi dkar chag\u003c/em\u003e. Toh 4364, Degé Tengyur vol. 308 (sna tshogs, jo), folios 294.b–310.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"4f938f52-c9df-4a22-8664-1ddf2e642301\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003ePramuditākaravarman. \u003cem\u003egsang ba ’dus pa rgyud kyi rgyal po’i bshad pa zla ba’i ’od zer\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eGuhya­samāja­tantra­rāja­ṭīkā­candra­prabhā\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 1852, Degé Tengyur vol. 41 (rgyud, thi), folios 120.a–313.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"218b0f60-5c2f-40e0-8a84-d92be1a346be\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eSahajalalita. \u003cem\u003ekun nas sgor ’jug pa’i ’od zer gtsug tor dri ma med par snang ba de bzhin gshegs pa thams cad kyi snying po dang dam tshig la rnam par blta ba zhes bya ba’i gzungs kyi rnam par bshad pa\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eSamanta­mukha­praveśa­raśmi­vimaloṣṇīṣa­prabhāsa­sarva­tathāgata­hṛdaya­samayavilokita­nāma­dhāraṇī­vṛtti\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 2688, Degé Tengyur vol. 71 (rgyud, thu), folios 269.a–320.b.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"b70901da-c7d7-417b-9bb3-ac65c527e9e5\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eŚāntideva. \u003cem\u003ebslab pa kun las btus pa\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eŚikṣāsamuccaya\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 3940, Degé Tengyur vol. 111 (dbu ma, khi), folios 3.a–194.b.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"016ec1aa-a34c-4bc8-9158-77cf9633aea2\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eSthiramati. \u003cem\u003ergyan dam pa sna tshogs rim par phye ba bkod pa\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eParamālaṃkāra­viśva­paṭala­vyūha\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 2661, Degé Tengyur vol. 68 (rgyud, ju), folios 317.a–339.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"cff30114-45f1-4ad5-a44c-3518c7ec5c0a\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eVairocanarakṣita. \u003cem\u003ebslab pa me tog snye ma\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eŚikṣā­kusuma­mañjarī\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 3943, Degé Tengyur vol. 213 (dbu ma, khi), folios 196.a–217.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"b5f1dcc8-c9d1-4f7c-ac15-da6a719f445f\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eVarious authors. \u003cem\u003ebye brag tu rtogs par byed pa [chen po]\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eMahāvyutpatti*\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 4346, Degé Tengyur vol. 306 (sna tshogs, co), folios 1.a–131.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"8b238683-0480-4e70-b4ef-3c342834905f\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eVarious authors. \u003cem\u003esgra sbyor bam po gnyis pa\u003c/em\u003e. Toh 4347, Degé Tengyur vol. 306 (sna tshogs, co), folios 131.b–160.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"224b4639-6ed8-4004-abe6-08681787e949\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eVinayadatta. \u003cem\u003esgyu ’phrul chen mo’i dkyil ’khor gyi cho ga bla ma’i zhal snga’i man ngag\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eGurūpadeśa­nāma­mahā­māyā­maṇḍalopāyikā\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 1645, Degé Tengyur vol. 25 (rgyud, ya), folios 290.a–309.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"13d069f6-3ccb-47ab-af06-e638c05be4ea\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eVitapāda. \u003cem\u003egsang ba ’dus pa’i dkyil ’khor gyi sgrub pa’i thabs rnam par bshad pa\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eGuhya­samāja­maṇḍalopāyikā­ṭīkā\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 1873, Degé Tengyur vol. 43 (rgyud, ni), folios 178.b–219.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"401eb5d0-8084-4094-96fe-8855771b9318\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eWönch’ük (Wen tsheg). \u003cem\u003edgongs pa zab mo nges par ’grel pa’i mdo rgya cher ’grel pa\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eGambhīra­saṁdhi­nirmocana­sūtra­ṭīkā\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 4016, Degé Tengyur vol. 220 (mdo ’grel, ti), folios 1.b–291.a; vol. 221 (mdo ’grel, thi), folios 1.b–272.a; and vol. 222 (mdo ’grel, di), folios 1.b–175.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"90c42f55-6051-4950-8361-b5bed54d460e\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eYeshe Dé (ye shes sde). \u003cem\u003elang kar gshegs pa zhes bya ba theg pa chen po’i mdo’i ’grel pa de bzhin gshegs pa’i snying po’i rgyan\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eLaṅkāvatāra­nāma­mahā­yāna­sūtra­vṛtti­tathāgata­hṛdayālaṃkāra\u003c/em\u003e), Toh 4019, Degé Tengyur vol. 224 (mdo ’grel, pi), folios 1.a–310.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null}]},{\"heading\":\"Other References in Tibetan\",\"entries\":[{\"uuid\":\"ef0eae1a-b52f-44bf-9bea-0dbc9467a034\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eKalzang Dolma (skal bzang sgrol ma). \u003cem\u003elo tsA ba ’gos chos grub dang khong gi ’gyur rtsom mdo mdzangs blun gyi lo tsA’i thabs rtsal skor la dpyad pa\u003c/em\u003e. In \u003cem\u003ekrung go’i bod kyi shes rig\u003c/em\u003e, vol. 77, pp. 31–53. Beijing: krung go’i bod kyi shes rig dus deb khang, 2007.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"f61fe264-29b2-4347-9d39-dff8341c2e35\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eLotsawa Gö Chödrup (lo tsā ba ’gos chos grub). In \u003cem\u003egangs ljongs skad gnyis smra ba du ma’i ’gyur byang blo gsal dga’ skyed\u003c/em\u003e, pp. 17–18. Xining: kan lho bod rigs rang skyong khul rtsom sgyur cu’u, 1983.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"260c5409-adf6-452f-9587-71978ef66c0d\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eNgawang Lobsang Choden (nga dbang blo bzang chos ldan). \u003cem\u003e’phags pa gser ’od dam pa mdo sde’i dbang po’i rgyal po’i ’don thabs cho ga\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eA Rite That Is a Method for Reciting the Noble Sūtra of the Sublime Golden Light\u003c/em\u003e), s.n. s.l. n.d.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"14e4c6d0-3be1-4924-b299-0f2bc002d762\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003ePema Karpo (pad ma dkar po). \u003cem\u003egser ’od dam pa nas gsungs pa’i bshags pa\u003c/em\u003e. In \u003cem\u003eThe Collected Works of Kun-mkhyen padma dkar po\u003c/em\u003e, vol. 9 (ta), pp. 519–24. Darjeeling: kargyu sungrab nyamso khang, 1973–74.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null}]},{\"heading\":\"Other References in English and Other Languages\",\"entries\":[{\"uuid\":\"7dae85a7-5ac9-4b86-a885-4265a9fa3f5d\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eBagchi, S., ed. \u003cem\u003eSuvarṇa­prabhāsa­sūtram\u003c/em\u003e. Darbhanga: The Mithila Institute, 1967. Digital Sanskrit Buddhist Canon.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"4f5cadad-252f-4a54-a5f2-a4c4f4fb8b7e\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eBanerjee, Radha. \u003cem\u003eSuvarṇa­prabhāsottama­sūtra\u003c/em\u003e. London: British Library, 2006. http://idp.bl.uk/downloads/GoldenLight.pdf.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"fa40517d-d8a9-4fca-b8a8-ee77542ac49c\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eBuswell Jr., Robert E., and Donald Lopez Jr. \u003cem\u003eThe Princeton Dictionary of Buddhism\u003c/em\u003e. Princeton University Press, 2014.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"87adf5f5-8a26-42bf-a77f-cc61f87fec40\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eDi, Guan. “The Sanskrit Fragments Preserved in Arthur M. Sackler Museum of Peking University.” \u003cem\u003eAnnual Report of the Research Institute for Advanced Buddhology at Soka University for the Academic Year 2013\u003c/em\u003e, vol. XVII (Tokyo Soka University, 2014): 109–18.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"6c68bda4-7a67-48d7-8a7c-5b07b98c4f03\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eLewis, Todd T. “Contributions to the Study of Popular Buddhism: The Newar Buddhist Festival of Guṃlā Dharma.” \u003cem\u003eJournal of the International Association of Buddhist Studies\u003c/em\u003e 16, no. 2 (Winter 1993): 309–54.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"b49c532c-84c7-439c-8cfe-c341ad37f398\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eNanjio Bunyiu, Idzumi Hokei. \u003cem\u003eThe Suvarṇaprabhāsa Sūtra: A Mahāyāna Text Called “The Golden Splendour.”\u003c/em\u003e Kyoto: The Eastern Buddhist Society, 1931.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"96047346-9d89-4945-83be-b478931751f4\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eNobel, Johannes (1937). \u003cem\u003eSuvarṇabhāsottama­sūtra. Das Goldglanz-Sūtra: ein Sanskrit text des Mahāyāna-Buddhismus. Nach den Handschriften und mit Hilfe der tibetischen und chinesischen Übertragungen\u003c/em\u003e. Leipzig: Harrassowitz.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"6c80d1e7-7c86-4a4f-863b-e6bda2caddec\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eNobel, Johannes (1944). \u003cem\u003eSuvarṇa­bhāsottama­sūtra. Das Goldglanz-Sūtra: ein Sanskrit text des Mahāyāna-Buddhismus. Die Tibetischen Überstzungen mit einem Wörterbuch\u003c/em\u003e. Leiden: E. J. Brill.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"71fc045b-30f6-4d9d-852a-43f490d73aa5\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eNobel, Johannes (1944, 1950). \u003cem\u003eSuvarṇabhāsottamasūtra. Das Goldglanz-Sūtra: ein Sanskrit text des Mahāyāna-Buddhismus. Die Tibetishcen Überstzungen mit einem Wörterbuch\u003c/em\u003e. 2 vols. Leiden: E. J. Brill.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"090d4597-3630-4601-9fe7-6e0668cdd37e\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eRadich, Michael (2014). “On the Sources, Style and Authorship of Chapters of the Synoptic Suvarṇaprabhasa-sūtra T644 Ascribed to Paramārtha (Part 1).” \u003cem\u003eAnnual Report of the Research Institute for Advanced Buddhology at Soka University for the Academic Year 2013\u003c/em\u003e, vol. XVII (Tokyo Soka University, 2014): 207–44. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"662ae333-110e-437e-b22b-b1a0b1c76d00\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eRadich, Michael (2016). “Tibetan Evidence for the Sources of Chapters of the Synoptic Suvarṇa-prabhāsottama-sūtra T 664 A Ascribed to Paramārtha.” \u003cem\u003eBuddhist Studies Review\u003c/em\u003e 32.2 (2015): 245–70. Sheffield, UK: Equinox Publishing.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"fc9df657-f2f2-4809-af4b-fa0c29adbd93\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eTanaka, Kimiaki. \u003cem\u003eAn Illustrated History of the Mandala From Its Genesis to the Kālacakratantra\u003c/em\u003e. Somerville, MA: Wisdom Publications, 2018.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"20e5e864-d629-49b9-9ae7-0a03653ccf3d\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eTyomkin, E. N. “Unique Sanskrit Fragments of ‘The Sūtra of Golden Light’ in the Manuscript Collection of the St. Petersburg Branch of the Institute of Oriental Studies.” In \u003cem\u003eManuscripta Orientalia\u003c/em\u003e vol. 1, no. 1 (July 1995): 29–38. St. Petersburg: Russian Academy of Sciences.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"c952097f-6d34-44a4-b50a-37baba98885c\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eYuama, Akira. “The Golden Light in Central Asia.” In \u003cem\u003eAnnual Report of the International Research Institute for Advanced Buddhology at Soka University for the Academic Year 2003\u003c/em\u003e (Tokyo: Soka University, 2004): 3–32.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null}]},{\"heading\":\"Translations\",\"entries\":[{\"uuid\":\"187eb87b-1594-4803-9015-42602ca039e6\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eEmmerick, R. E. \u003cem\u003eThe Sūtra of Golden Light\u003c/em\u003e. Oxford: The Pali Text Society, 2004.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"521beb98-4d81-4021-b27e-6a294061c19c\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eFoundation for the Preservation of the Mahayana Tradition (FPMT). \u003cem\u003e\u003ca href=\\\"https://fpmt.org/education/prayers-and-practice-materials/sutras/golden-light-sutra/download/\\\"\u003eSutra of Golden Light, 21-Chapter\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/em\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"6f385b4f-ec0d-417e-8101-4662fc648025\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eNobel, Johannes. \u003cem\u003eSuvarṇa­prabhāsottama­sūtra, Das Goldglanz-Sutra, ein Sanskrittext des Mahayana Buddhismus. I-Tsing’s chinesische Version und ihre Übersetzung\u003c/em\u003e. Leiden: E. J. Brill, 1958.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null}]}],\"endnotes\":[{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"18d7cc5c-f799-4f11-bd65-758fd79f9f42\",\"sort\":17373,\"type\":\"endnotesHeader\",\"label\":\"n.\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":2,\"start\":0,\"end\":5,\"uuid\":\"941f9440-b752-4263-a978-21e92156b5bf\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Notes\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":5}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"476716b6-73b6-4d25-86d1-2a2a464fa670\",\"sort\":17375,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.1\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The work translated here is the twenty-nine-chapter version (hereafter referenced as Toh 556) of The Sūtra of the Sublime Golden Light. There are also the twenty-one-chapter (hereafter referenced as Toh 557) and thirty-one-chapter (hereafter referenced as Toh 555) versions. Both Toh 556 and Toh 557 were translated into Tibetan from Sanskrit, so almost the entirety of Toh 557 is present in an identical translation in Toh 556.\",\"label\":\"i.2\",\"sort\":32,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"ddf289f6-ffb3-40cf-88ad-2b5750f5e150\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-51\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":81,\"uuid\":\"476716b6-73b6-4d25-86d1-2a2a464fa670\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Sūtra of the Sublime Golden Light (3) \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":42},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"8c911291-6026-4b51-973a-2e65bd73e3e8\",\"href\":\"/entity/work/1fc97885-c98f-4571-8920-9b8f3841332d\",\"entity\":\"1fc97885-c98f-4571-8920-9b8f3841332d\",\"type\":\"work\",\"toh\":null,\"linkToh\":\"toh557\",\"start\":0,\"end\":0}},{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"92aaa11d-acfa-424a-9ce6-ed5381ba4086\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":42,\"end\":43}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Suvarṇa­prabhāsottama­sūtra,\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":43,\"end\":71},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7c4550dd-7079-4d12-84af-f6ebba5587ee\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Toh 557).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":71,\"end\":81}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"fd14b65c-ff91-42cf-aa09-4fbf2b37d00b\",\"sort\":17380,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.2\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The work translated here is the twenty-nine-chapter version (hereafter referenced as Toh 556) of The Sūtra of the Sublime Golden Light. There are also the twenty-one-chapter (hereafter referenced as Toh 557) and thirty-one-chapter (hereafter referenced as Toh 555) versions. Both Toh 556 and Toh 557 were translated into Tibetan from Sanskrit, so almost the entirety of Toh 557 is present in an identical translation in Toh 556.\",\"label\":\"i.2\",\"sort\":32,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"ddf289f6-ffb3-40cf-88ad-2b5750f5e150\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-51\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":80,\"uuid\":\"fd14b65c-ff91-42cf-aa09-4fbf2b37d00b\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Sūtra of the Sublime Golden Light (1) \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":42},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"53e4c139-b01a-40ca-b71c-86d78ca2670d\",\"href\":\"/entity/work/1a233f5c-1789-438c-ae48-e2e8c49c7278\",\"entity\":\"1a233f5c-1789-438c-ae48-e2e8c49c7278\",\"type\":\"work\",\"toh\":null,\"linkToh\":\"toh555\",\"start\":0,\"end\":0}},{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9993688c-d374-4adc-914b-baebb3ccc40a\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":42,\"end\":43}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Suvarṇa­prabhāsottamasūtra,\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":43,\"end\":70},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"cb1700f2-863b-4ffd-b33e-d7fc88916c8e\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Toh 555).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":70,\"end\":80}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c2906cd5-5b1e-4327-ae55-f40de6705508\",\"sort\":17385,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.3\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$20\",\"label\":\"i.11\",\"sort\":115,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"b6ba7304-430a-4c35-9135-0e4c69fa862a\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-60\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":66,\"uuid\":\"c2906cd5-5b1e-4327-ae55-f40de6705508\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"dbu ma rin po che’i sgron ma \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":29},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"990edc4a-c0fb-47cf-a551-712b176a9a43\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":30}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Madhyamaka­ratna­pradīpa)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":30,\"end\":55},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c4c46111-1594-468a-97f6-7d5bcd424206\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 3854.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":55,\"end\":66}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4034bf31-9104-489f-bc51-ac13d0735edd\",\"sort\":17392,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.4\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$21\",\"label\":\"i.11\",\"sort\":115,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"b6ba7304-430a-4c35-9135-0e4c69fa862a\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-60\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":496,\"uuid\":\"4034bf31-9104-489f-bc51-ac13d0735edd\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(1) \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":4}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Root Manual of the Rites of Mañjuśrī \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":4,\"end\":45},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c4fb3172-1e57-46ea-90da-be0db0a27d6a\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":45,\"end\":46}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Mañjuśrī­mūla­kalpa,\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":46,\"end\":66},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d0b357f0-ff50-48a9-a152-4a9c921f7a2d\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Toh 543), \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":66,\"end\":77}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"2.129;\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":77,\"end\":83},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"376bde15-9337-4678-93c3-ff61840360d9\",\"href\":\"/entity/passage/c815be70-573b-483f-b99a-bf6ef2fdbb3f\",\"entity\":\"c815be70-573b-483f-b99a-bf6ef2fdbb3f\",\"type\":\"passage\",\"toh\":null,\"subtype\":\"translation\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (2) \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":83,\"end\":88}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ral pa gyen brdzes kyi rtog pa chen po byang chub sems dpa’ chen po’i rnam par ’phrul pa le’u rab ’byams las bcom ldan ’das ma ’phags ma sgrol ma’i rtsa ba’i rtog pa \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":88,\"end\":254},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"eca8229f-6457-423e-a08c-ae91538bcccf\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":254,\"end\":255}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ūrdhvajaṭā-mahā­kalpa­mahā­bodhi­sattva­vikurvaṇapaṭalavisarā bhagavatī āryatārā­mūla­kalpa)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":255,\"end\":347},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9caac0ec-23da-4fdc-8c7f-c1a2e83a4922\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 724, folio 238.a; (3) \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":347,\"end\":375}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"dkyil ’khor thams cad kyi spyi’i cho ga gsang ba’i rgyud \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":375,\"end\":432},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"57a8b1ae-b5a4-44d9-ab7a-891375b33f1b\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":432,\"end\":433}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sarva­maṇḍala­sāmānyavidhi­guhya­tantra)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":433,\"end\":473},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bc8de693-af0b-4297-9704-e86571b142e5\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 806, folio 152.b.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":473,\"end\":496}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c7c26a57-a38b-4921-ac3b-1dbdf95d913a\",\"sort\":17412,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.5\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$22\",\"label\":\"i.11\",\"sort\":115,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"b6ba7304-430a-4c35-9135-0e4c69fa862a\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-60\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1924,\"uuid\":\"c7c26a57-a38b-4921-ac3b-1dbdf95d913a\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(1) Vinayadatta, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":17}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sgyu ’phrul chen mo’i dkyil ’khor gyi cho ga bla ma’i zhal snga’i man ngag \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":17,\"end\":92},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"09b406f8-8db2-4607-b9e4-1c263bd27de5\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":92,\"end\":93}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Gurūpadeśa­nāma­mahā­māyā­maṇḍalopāyikā)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":93,\"end\":133},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4efad102-c9c3-4ebc-ac15-21b75c527841\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 1645, folio 209.a; (2) Bhavyakīrti, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":133,\"end\":175}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sgron ma gsal bar byed pa dgongs pa rab gsal zhes bya ba bshad pa’i ti ka \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":175,\"end\":249},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c9cd5310-3eb7-498f-b468-dd0df79a631c\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":249,\"end\":250}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Pradīpoddyotanābhisaṃdhi­prakāśikā­nāma­vyākhyā­ṭīkā)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":250,\"end\":303},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"784d19f7-8702-4544-ae73-cdd79aac7442\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 1793, folio 201.a; (3) Pramuditākaravarman, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":303,\"end\":353}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"gsang ba ’dus pa rgyud kyi rgyal po’i bshad pa zla ba’i ’od zer \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":353,\"end\":417},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"de09f3e3-4ae5-42a7-80df-1eee4f18884f\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":417,\"end\":418}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Guhya­samāja­tantra­rāja­ṭīkā­candra­prabhā)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":418,\"end\":462},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"690c84a1-481a-4ebe-93ee-06be6c1d2972\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 1852, folio 169.b; (4) Vitapāda, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":462,\"end\":501}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"gsang ba ’dus pa’i dkyil ’khor gyi sgrub pa’i thabs rnam par bshad pa \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":501,\"end\":571},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"27fccbc8-1dcc-4ea1-ba72-1a68b7fd0f7d\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":571,\"end\":572}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Guhya­samāja­maṇḍalopāyikā­ṭīkā)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":572,\"end\":604},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"8c66e189-4cbd-46d6-bb15-be814e515a4e\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 1873, folio 209.a; (5) Ānandagarbha, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":604,\"end\":647}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"rdo rje dbyings kyi dkyil ’khor chen po’i cho ga rdo rje thams cad ’byung ba \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":647,\"end\":724},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4e4c51f9-4abe-41c2-af1c-e57c3c8bba90\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":724,\"end\":725}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Vajra­dhātu­mahā­maṇḍalopāyikā­sarva­vajrodaya)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":725,\"end\":772},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c1b76901-7f35-41ff-86ec-5b496e6f0f8f\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 2516, folio 50.a; (6) Anonymous,\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":772,\"end\":810}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’jam pa’i rdo rje ’byung ba’i dkyil ’khor gyi cho ga sems can thams cad kyi bde ba bskyed pa \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":810,\"end\":903},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7d205d43-180e-4a24-b720-46126d2f4e04\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":903,\"end\":904}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Mañju­vajrodaya­maṇḍalopāyikā­sarva­sattva­hitāvahā)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":904,\"end\":956},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"46b43cb9-6ea7-4cb2-9f1c-56bf4f0e81fe\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Toh 2590; (7) Kāmadhenu, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":956,\"end\":983}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ngan song thams cad yongs su sbyong ba gzi brjid kyi rgyal po zhes bya ba cho ga zhib mo’i rgyal po chen po’i rgya cher ’grel pa \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":983,\"end\":1112},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b1e9c3ea-7835-4916-84f5-d083e93d960e\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1112,\"end\":1113}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sarva­durgati­pariśodhana­tejorāja­nāma­mahā­kalpa­rāja­ṭīkā)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1113,\"end\":1174},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"05745e17-cb8d-46d0-bdd9-09e8e0540812\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 2625; (8) Ānandagarbha, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1174,\"end\":1204}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"de bzhin gshegs pa dgra bcom pa yang dag par rdzogs pa’i sangs rgyas ngan song thams cad yongs su sbyong ba gzi brjid kyi rgyal po zhes bya ba’i bshad pa \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1204,\"end\":1358},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5d7b4aa9-0dbf-4fbd-b78b-9cd9816536d0\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1358,\"end\":1359}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sarva­durgati­pariśodhana­tejorāja­tathāgatārhat­samyak­saṃbuddha­nāma­kalpa­ṭīkā)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1359,\"end\":1441},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5959f11a-5573-4199-8c2b-69b7463df504\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 2628, folio 73.a; (9) Sthiramati, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1441,\"end\":1481}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"rgyan dam pa sna tshogs rim par phye ba bkod pa \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1481,\"end\":1529},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"59fd1a2c-4889-4c00-8efa-e1746540a4e8\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1529,\"end\":1530}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Paramālaṃkāra­viśva­paṭala­vyūha)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1530,\"end\":1563},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b019e287-0eb1-4b44-88b7-b1e658e4992c\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 2661, folio 322.b; (10) Sahajalalita, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1563,\"end\":1607}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"kun nas sgor ’jug pa’i ’od zer gtsug tor dri ma med par snang ba de bzhin gshegs pa thams cad kyi snying po dang dam tshig la rnam par blta ba zhes bya ba’i gzungs kyi rnam par bshad pa \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1607,\"end\":1793},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0525e9dc-3b66-419a-bfc6-463198423587\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1793,\"end\":1794}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Samanta­mukha­praveśa­raśmi­vimaloṣṇīṣa­prabhāsa­sarva­tathāgata­hṛdaya­samayavilokita­nāma­dhāraṇī­vṛtti)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1794,\"end\":1900},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e80956a7-fa2d-4709-b144-ee3f2e0f9898\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 2688, folio 292.b.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1900,\"end\":1924}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f9402630-1b4f-4b29-9618-e998e6e9883e\",\"sort\":17474,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.6\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$23\",\"label\":\"i.11\",\"sort\":115,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"b6ba7304-430a-4c35-9135-0e4c69fa862a\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-60\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":843,\"uuid\":\"f9402630-1b4f-4b29-9618-e998e6e9883e\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(1) Bodhisattva, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":17}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"kun nas sgor ’jug pa’i ’od zer gtsug tor dri ma med par snang ba’i gzungs bklag cing chod rten brgya rtsa brgyad dam mchod rten lnga gdab pa’i cho ga mdo sde las btus pa \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":17,\"end\":187},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"8c61d1f2-6082-4c03-8b24-ecd4e6c6a960\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":187,\"end\":188}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Samanta­mukha­praveśa­raśmi­vimaloṣṇīṣa­prabhāsa­dhāraṇī­vacana­sūtrāntoddhṛtāṣṭottara­śata­caityāntara­pañca­caitya­nirvapaṇa­vidhi)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":188,\"end\":321},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f3099c36-adc3-455f-86cd-eb299ecf5c6e\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 3068, folios 145.a, 151.b, 153.b; (2) Dīpaṁkaraśrījñāna, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":321,\"end\":384}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"dbu ma’i man ngag rin po che’i za ma tog kha phye ba zhes bya ba \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":384,\"end\":449},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9167c0b9-113c-493e-9ef2-685f18652d7f\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":449,\"end\":450}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ratna­karaṇḍodghāṭa­nāma­madhyamakopadeśa)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":450,\"end\":492},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"3ebdae07-9ffd-4938-b12c-75044cc6de8b\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 3930, folios 99.a, 115.a; (3) Śāntideva, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":492,\"end\":539}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bslab pa kun las btus pa \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":539,\"end\":564},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"51c0d67c-4874-4ef7-90f5-6b127b5f78c4\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":564,\"end\":565}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śikṣāsamuccaya)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":565,\"end\":580},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a6115cc6-d73f-4a50-b9c7-c1efb7e7dd5a\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 3940, folios 3.a–194.b, 90.a–91.b, 122.a–123.b; (4) Vairocanarakṣita, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":580,\"end\":656}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bslab pa me tog snye ma \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":656,\"end\":680},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"47aa600b-f119-4f12-9bb5-39cc14662051\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":680,\"end\":681}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śikṣā­kusuma­mañjarī)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":681,\"end\":702},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0f4f335a-0194-4fbf-994a-eaa60b76c174\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 3943, folio 200.a; (5) Dīpaṁkaraśrījñāna, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":702,\"end\":750}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"byang chub lam gyi sgron ma’i dka’ ’grel \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":750,\"end\":791},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"2ee722a2-557b-4a07-afe0-1764e5ff6869\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":791,\"end\":792}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Bodhi­mārga­pradīpa­pañjikā)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":792,\"end\":820},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1ae57c85-2da8-44d8-b4c0-fc9661db30d8\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 3948, folio 20.b.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":820,\"end\":843}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"8865b0c8-44cb-4caa-a84c-c247077d4c5c\",\"sort\":17506,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.7\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$24\",\"label\":\"i.11\",\"sort\":115,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"b6ba7304-430a-4c35-9135-0e4c69fa862a\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-60\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":208,\"uuid\":\"8865b0c8-44cb-4caa-a84c-c247077d4c5c\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(1) Anonymous, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":15}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"gser ’od dam pa mdo sde dbang po’i smon lam \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":15,\"end\":59},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"05e0def6-737e-4689-ada5-c256101a1c73\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":59,\"end\":60}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Suvarṇa­prabhāsottama­sūtrendra­praṇidhāna)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":60,\"end\":103},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bb632a76-34a2-421d-88e1-568303bc71ab\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 4379; (2) Anonymous, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":103,\"end\":130}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"rgyal po gser gyi lag pa’i smon lam \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":130,\"end\":166},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"17e32e1d-a51f-41af-849b-868047a6af74\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":166,\"end\":167}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Rāja­suvarṇa­bhuja­praṇidhāna)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":167,\"end\":197},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bb744158-83ba-4436-8346-1e3a41bd850f\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 4380.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":197,\"end\":208}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"537d23cc-f237-45cf-9738-52c2b0e3c26c\",\"sort\":17520,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.8\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"In addition to its importance for rites and recitations, the text is quoted on doctrinal points in Indian commentaries. Passages indicating that the Buddha never dies, leaves no relics, and that the Dharma never ceases are quoted in six texts, two of which cite the delightful verse that describes the impossibility of there being buddha relics, stating that there will be a buddha relic only when a ladder to the moon is built from rabbit horns.\",\"label\":\"i.12\",\"sort\":139,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"33651175-baef-4552-9ead-3eab1dbe9e17\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-67\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1087,\"uuid\":\"537d23cc-f237-45cf-9738-52c2b0e3c26c\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(1) Dīpaṁkaraśrījñāna, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":23}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mngon par rtogs pa rnam par ’byed pa \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":23,\"end\":60},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"056334b7-a260-4972-bff2-1182960297e3\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":60,\"end\":61}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Abhisamaya­vibhaṅga­nāma)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":61,\"end\":86},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"17a0dcbe-eda2-48f1-a27a-9c74abf270a2\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 1490, folio 201.a; (2) Āryadeva, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":86,\"end\":125}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"spyod pa bsdud pa’i sgron ma \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":125,\"end\":154},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"25752a03-84a6-470c-aefa-274961509a2a\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":154,\"end\":155}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Caryāmelāpaka­pradīpa)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":155,\"end\":177},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d6e28057-9a50-41be-ad25-eafd3ae9718c\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 1803, folio 106.a; (3) Mañjuśrīkīrti,\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":177,\"end\":220}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’jam dpal gyi mtshan yang dag par brjod pa’i rgya cher bshad pa \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":220,\"end\":284},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a29dd3e4-37bf-4a8b-8b00-6b30487d70a0\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":284,\"end\":285}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Mañjuśri­nāma­saṃgīti­ṭīkā)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":285,\"end\":312},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"176403b2-c40d-4a59-b2e2-60bd03144efa\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 2534, folio 217.b; (4) Haribhadra, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":312,\"end\":353}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"shes rab kyi pha tol tu phyin pa brgyad stong pa’i bshad pa mngon par rtogs pa’i rgyan gyi snang ba \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":353,\"end\":453},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4130ff63-0034-4364-86ba-a5849dec7030\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":453,\"end\":454}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Aṣṭa­sāhasrikā­prajñā­pāramitā­vyākhyānābhisamayālaṃkārāloka)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":454,\"end\":515},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"594283e7-fd6f-4acd-afe9-a7ed02183f02\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 3791, folio 84.b; (5) Dharmakīrtiśrī, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":515,\"end\":559}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"shes rab kyi pha rol tu phyin pa’i man ngag gi bstan bcos mngon par rtogs pa’i rgyan zhes bya ba’i ’grel pa rtogs par dka’ ba’i snang ba zhes bya ba’i ’grel bshad \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":559,\"end\":722},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"cc2037d8-c7e4-41fd-bb08-1b7ff42190ec\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":722,\"end\":723}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Abhisamayālaṃkāra­nāma­prajñā­pāramitopadeśa­śāstra­vṛtti­durbodhāloka­nāma­ṭīkā)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":723,\"end\":804},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"cd96eaec-07c3-4762-a9cf-19f4a8252905\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 3794, folio 152.b; (6) Dharmamitra, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":804,\"end\":846}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"shes rab kyi pha rol tu phyin pa’i man ngag gi bstan bcos mngon par rtogs pa’i rgyan gyi tshig le’ur byas pa’i ’grel bshad tshig rab tu gsal ba \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":846,\"end\":990},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"902ed163-d94c-4644-87c3-40613219f391\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":990,\"end\":991}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Abhisamayālaṃkāra­kārikā­prajñā­pāramitopadeśa­śāstra­ṭīkāprasphuṭapadā)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":991,\"end\":1063},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ca96a017-8c67-453b-ab70-4ef5851a32aa\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 3796, folio 104.a.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1063,\"end\":1087}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"baeb732f-1fa0-49cf-9cda-d67b81f8242e\",\"sort\":17558,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.9\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"In addition to its importance for rites and recitations, the text is quoted on doctrinal points in Indian commentaries. Passages indicating that the Buddha never dies, leaves no relics, and that the Dharma never ceases are quoted in six texts, two of which cite the delightful verse that describes the impossibility of there being buddha relics, stating that there will be a buddha relic only when a ladder to the moon is built from rabbit horns.\",\"label\":\"i.12\",\"sort\":139,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"33651175-baef-4552-9ead-3eab1dbe9e17\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-67\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":74,\"uuid\":\"baeb732f-1fa0-49cf-9cda-d67b81f8242e\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(1) Āryadeva, Toh 1803, folio 217.b; (2) Haribhadra, Toh 3791, folio 84.b.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":74}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d500af8a-bb6d-4980-b338-b5e094d869e6\",\"sort\":17564,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.10\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The descriptions of buddha nature and the nature of the bodies of a buddha, which are only in Toh 555 and Toh 556, are quoted in two texts in the Tengyur, one written in Tibetan and one translated from Sanskrit by Rinchen Sangpo, although nothing is known about the author.\",\"label\":\"i.13\",\"sort\":145,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"d447dcb7-ab2f-4af8-bfcb-df1608769529\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-70\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":394,\"uuid\":\"d500af8a-bb6d-4980-b338-b5e094d869e6\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(1) Ekādaśanirghoṣa, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":21}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"rdo rje ’chang chen po’i lam gyir rim pa’i man ngag bdud rtsi gsang ba \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":21,\"end\":92},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c52c20c7-583f-4209-a255-53f4b66ada70\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":92,\"end\":93}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Mahā­vajra­dhara­patha­kramopadeśāmṛta­guhya)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":93,\"end\":138},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f6e3ce31-7f4b-42ef-b15f-f20da4e3f688\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 1823, folio 274.a; (2) Yeshé Dé, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":138,\"end\":177}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"lang kar gshegs pa zhes bya ba theg pa chen po’i mdo’i ’grel pa de bzhin gshegs pa’i snying po’i rgyan \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":177,\"end\":280},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c1675ba6-0a61-4e14-b289-30f32029bc23\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":280,\"end\":281}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Laṅkāvatāra­nāma­mahāyāna­sūtra­vṛtti­tathāgata­hṛdayālaṃkāra)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":281,\"end\":343},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4bb9d1a3-3e97-4914-8bb5-379de6c25bef\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 4019, folios 29.a, 29.b, 152.b, 279.b, 302.a.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":343,\"end\":394}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"262f5d19-288c-489f-843f-c97ecc9348e1\",\"sort\":17578,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.11\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"In Newar Buddhism, this sūtra became and remains one of the nine principal sūtras called “the nine Dharmas,” which are considered to be the most important lengthy sūtras to be recited and offered to.\",\"label\":\"i.14\",\"sort\":149,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"2bfd30cc-8563-4b69-953b-e2a8a465df6c\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-72\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":289,\"uuid\":\"262f5d19-288c-489f-843f-c97ecc9348e1\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Termed the Navadharma (“Nine Dharmas”) or Navagrantha (“Nine Texts”), these works are (1) \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":90}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Prajñāpāramitā,\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":90,\"end\":105},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ab1d024a-ef85-40ab-8548-e4f693d90a33\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (2) \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":105,\"end\":110}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Gaṇḍavyūha\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":110,\"end\":120},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"185c97d3-3a62-4f95-bc54-61d431cd31ab\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\",\"start\":110,\"end\":0}},{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bda379c0-070c-4b85-bd4e-f9d0b78932f8\",\"href\":\"/entity/work/e9e0d769-0708-4b0b-990b-5b2da82d5155\",\"entity\":\"e9e0d769-0708-4b0b-990b-5b2da82d5155\",\"type\":\"work\",\"toh\":null,\"linkToh\":\"toh44-45\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\",\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":120,\"end\":121},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"185c97d3-3a62-4f95-bc54-61d431cd31ab\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\",\"start\":120,\"end\":0}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (3) \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":121,\"end\":126}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Daśabhūmi\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":126,\"end\":135},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6e262352-b443-4085-ac88-9f5c6df1a5c1\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\",\"start\":126,\"end\":0}},{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"95a32346-605a-46f8-9702-4b036012be61\",\"href\":\"/entity/work/a685ab48-5089-47ea-965f-7c0915643fe0\",\"entity\":\"a685ab48-5089-47ea-965f-7c0915643fe0\",\"type\":\"work\",\"toh\":null,\"linkToh\":\"toh44-31\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\",\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":135,\"end\":136},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6e262352-b443-4085-ac88-9f5c6df1a5c1\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\",\"start\":135,\"end\":0}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (4) \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":136,\"end\":141}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Samādhirāja\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":141,\"end\":152},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"57b0c143-2101-4d54-ad80-ed112068c21e\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\",\"start\":141,\"end\":0}},{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"49dd7a6c-8d1e-4eef-a363-4eba3d4e6ad9\",\"href\":\"/entity/work/125c3bee-621a-4c25-82bd-f8fb35093d3c\",\"entity\":\"125c3bee-621a-4c25-82bd-f8fb35093d3c\",\"type\":\"work\",\"toh\":null,\"linkToh\":\"toh127\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\",\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":152,\"end\":153},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"57b0c143-2101-4d54-ad80-ed112068c21e\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\",\"start\":152,\"end\":0}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (5) \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":153,\"end\":158}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Laṅkāvatāra,\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":158,\"end\":170},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4e15de9a-f7dc-456b-981d-c61807c4dac8\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (6) \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":170,\"end\":175}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Saddharmapuṇḍarīka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":175,\"end\":193},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"645d3437-10cb-478e-865e-5d293ad19cf3\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\",\"start\":175,\"end\":0}},{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"49f712c2-7ffa-49eb-b57c-af8ddacdf946\",\"href\":\"/entity/work/7711a098-9c12-4bf6-aecf-0cae08f05026\",\"entity\":\"7711a098-9c12-4bf6-aecf-0cae08f05026\",\"type\":\"work\",\"toh\":null,\"linkToh\":\"toh113\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\",\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":193,\"end\":194},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"645d3437-10cb-478e-865e-5d293ad19cf3\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\",\"start\":193,\"end\":0}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (7) \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":194,\"end\":199}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Lalitavistara\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":199,\"end\":212},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"3a3b1a9b-24d4-4c92-8fa9-9387bca039aa\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\",\"start\":199,\"end\":0}},{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"20ad26db-e6aa-490b-b90a-8ecfa41f9e6b\",\"href\":\"/entity/work/b8138146-9ff5-4bf6-800f-78413afc4bf8\",\"entity\":\"b8138146-9ff5-4bf6-800f-78413afc4bf8\",\"type\":\"work\",\"toh\":null,\"linkToh\":\"toh95\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\",\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":212,\"end\":213},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"3a3b1a9b-24d4-4c92-8fa9-9387bca039aa\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\",\"start\":212,\"end\":0}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (8) \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":213,\"end\":218}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Suvarṇaprabhāsa,\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":218,\"end\":234},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9b857bcb-384f-4fcc-8d50-357cb41247ba\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and (9) \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":234,\"end\":243}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Tathāgatagūhya.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":243,\"end\":258},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"8ca743e5-242c-41a7-a67d-ee7527893fbd\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" See Lewis 1993, p. 327, n. 15.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":258,\"end\":289}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b06b66ff-e9ec-4272-a358-2509d924fa32\",\"sort\":17598,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.12\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"There are three surviving translations of The Sūtra of the Sublime Golden Light in Chinese. The earliest of these was translated by Dharmakṣema (385–433). He was an Indian who came to China in 414, living first in Dunhuang. Then in 420 he went to Guzang, the capital of Northern Liang, one of the sixteen independent states of that time, situated in what is now the Gansu region in China’s northwest. There he studied Chinese and engaged in translation under the patronage of Juqu Mengxun (368–433), the ruler of Northern Liang. He also had the reputation of being “a master of spells.” As a result of that reputation, Juqu Mengxun, toward the end of his reign, became afraid that Dharmakṣema might be used against him by his adversaries and so he had him assassinated. Nobel believed that the Sanskrit in its present form is not earlier than the mid-fifth century and that Dharmakṣema translated from an earlier version. This opinion appears to be supported by the Sanskrit manuscript fragments discovered in Khotan.\",\"label\":\"i.18\",\"sort\":166,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"124828eb-15d5-4bc6-89fb-22e125380297\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-77\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":45,\"uuid\":\"b06b66ff-e9ec-4272-a358-2509d924fa32\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Princeton Dictionary of Buddhism,\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":37},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e2b67ab8-e303-46e5-af1a-7b4f3fb55612\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" p. 248.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":37,\"end\":45}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a9b5e8b4-9e14-4f48-98ed-16822d1703c4\",\"sort\":17601,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.13\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"There are three surviving translations of The Sūtra of the Sublime Golden Light in Chinese. The earliest of these was translated by Dharmakṣema (385–433). He was an Indian who came to China in 414, living first in Dunhuang. Then in 420 he went to Guzang, the capital of Northern Liang, one of the sixteen independent states of that time, situated in what is now the Gansu region in China’s northwest. There he studied Chinese and engaged in translation under the patronage of Juqu Mengxun (368–433), the ruler of Northern Liang. He also had the reputation of being “a master of spells.” As a result of that reputation, Juqu Mengxun, toward the end of his reign, became afraid that Dharmakṣema might be used against him by his adversaries and so he had him assassinated. Nobel believed that the Sanskrit in its present form is not earlier than the mid-fifth century and that Dharmakṣema translated from an earlier version. This opinion appears to be supported by the Sanskrit manuscript fragments discovered in Khotan.\",\"label\":\"i.18\",\"sort\":166,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"124828eb-15d5-4bc6-89fb-22e125380297\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-77\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":22,\"uuid\":\"a9b5e8b4-9e14-4f48-98ed-16822d1703c4\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Emmerick 2004, p. xxi.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":22}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"db61cb28-ccd5-4ac8-939e-b38494ce46e1\",\"sort\":17603,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.14\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The third translation was by Yijing (635–713), which was published in 703. Because of its clarity and writing style, this version became popular in China and was itself translated into Tibetan in the early ninth century. Yijing’s translation, compared to the Sanskrit and the Tibetan translation from Sanskrit, is freer, to the extent that Emmerick has stated it could not be used to reconstruct the original Sanskrit. Yijing spent thirty years in India and Sumatra and returned to China in 695. He brought with him four hundred Sanskrit texts, including The Sūtra of the Sublime Golden Light, and spent the first decade of the seventh century translating them.\",\"label\":\"i.20\",\"sort\":175,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"6e0659e3-5124-4082-8aea-859cc2cbc049\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-81\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":22,\"uuid\":\"db61cb28-ccd5-4ac8-939e-b38494ce46e1\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Emmerick 2004, p. xii.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":22}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e697d551-82ab-4c5a-a58b-1c11cec5d2dc\",\"sort\":17605,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.15\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The third translation was by Yijing (635–713), which was published in 703. Because of its clarity and writing style, this version became popular in China and was itself translated into Tibetan in the early ninth century. Yijing’s translation, compared to the Sanskrit and the Tibetan translation from Sanskrit, is freer, to the extent that Emmerick has stated it could not be used to reconstruct the original Sanskrit. Yijing spent thirty years in India and Sumatra and returned to China in 695. He brought with him four hundred Sanskrit texts, including The Sūtra of the Sublime Golden Light, and spent the first decade of the seventh century translating them.\",\"label\":\"i.20\",\"sort\":175,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"6e0659e3-5124-4082-8aea-859cc2cbc049\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-81\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":46,\"uuid\":\"e697d551-82ab-4c5a-a58b-1c11cec5d2dc\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Princeton Dictionary of Buddhism,\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":37},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a14cef3c-7dfd-49e6-a389-8b60aa4f8ac8\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" p. 1028.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":37,\"end\":46}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"3ae9cbde-692b-484a-a289-110e4e1a4092\",\"sort\":17608,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.16\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The Mogao caves of Dunhuang, which were sealed in the eleventh century, contained a great number of manuscripts of the sūtra, particularly those of Yijing’s translation into Chinese. The sūtra became popular for its teachings on freeing oneself from the effects of bad karma. For example, Yijing’s Chinese translation (and the Uighur and Tangut versions derived from it) has a preface that states how the sūtra saved Zhang Judao, ruler of Tangut, from going to hell because he had slaughtered cattle for a big feast. This narrative is illustrated in a twelfth-century Tangut woodcut that is preserved in St. Petersburg.\",\"label\":\"i.21\",\"sort\":182,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"a52c3980-2af5-4459-b1a4-db2f36296a14\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-84\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":20,\"uuid\":\"3ae9cbde-692b-484a-a289-110e4e1a4092\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Tyomkin 1995, p. 30.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":20}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b85dcbd2-859d-43a9-85fb-f17db8455a26\",\"sort\":17610,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.17\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"There are some Tibetan texts included in the Tengyur that were authored by Tibetan translators active in the early ninth century. The translator Kawa Paltsek quotes from the passages describing the Dharma body and the Buddha not leaving any relics because he has no body with bones and blood. Yeshé Dé wrote a text that has a number of references to this sūtra’s teaching on the three bodies of a buddha, buddha nature, and the description of the bhūmis.\",\"label\":\"i.25\",\"sort\":194,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"eb2acf92-b2e0-49b7-8b81-fde62f33a896\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-89\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":101,\"uuid\":\"b85dcbd2-859d-43a9-85fb-f17db8455a26\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Paltsek, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":9}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"gsung rab rin po che’i gtam rgyud dang śākya’i rabs rgyud,\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":9,\"end\":67},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c908e5ab-fad7-48c0-9dbb-3ff657b42575\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Toh 4357, folios 273.a and 331.b.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":67,\"end\":101}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bc801eef-22be-4632-9b52-2a724a93f5c0\",\"sort\":17616,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.18\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"There are some Tibetan texts included in the Tengyur that were authored by Tibetan translators active in the early ninth century. The translator Kawa Paltsek quotes from the passages describing the Dharma body and the Buddha not leaving any relics because he has no body with bones and blood. Yeshé Dé wrote a text that has a number of references to this sūtra’s teaching on the three bodies of a buddha, buddha nature, and the description of the bhūmis.\",\"label\":\"i.25\",\"sort\":194,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"eb2acf92-b2e0-49b7-8b81-fde62f33a896\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-89\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":227,\"uuid\":\"bc801eef-22be-4632-9b52-2a724a93f5c0\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Yeshe Dé, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":10}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"lang kar gshegs pa zhes bya ba theg pa chen po’i mdo’i ’grel pa de bzhin gshegs pa’i snying po’i rgyan \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":10,\"end\":113},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"aa33411d-24ff-40fb-9150-71ae2c182420\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":113,\"end\":114}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Laṅkāvatāra­nāma­mahāyāna­sūtra­vṛtti­tathāgata­hṛdayālaṃkāra)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":114,\"end\":176},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"460b8c2d-599f-46b2-8193-8ea73273ba3b\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 4019, folios 29.a, 29.b, 152.b, 279.b, 302.a.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":176,\"end\":227}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"131f5605-1a6a-4e88-8dbf-cce9b5c6186d\",\"sort\":17624,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.19\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The commentary in the Tengyur that quotes from the sūtra more than any other‍—twenty times in all‍—is the translation by Gö Chödrup of An Extensive Commentary on the Sūtra that Elucidates the Profound Intention by the Korean monk Wŏnch’ŭk (613–96), who had migrated to China. This commentary by Wŏnch’ŭk in Tibetan translation became a particular influence on the thought of Tsongkhapa, the founder of the Gelukpa school. The sūtra has been quoted by great masters in all the schools of Tibetan Buddhism and extracts from it were published in Tibet as numerous standalone texts‍—not only the confession prayer but also other chapters, such as the treatise on kingship. Its continuing significance is indicated by Pema Karpo (1527–92), the hierarch of the Drukpa Kagyü school, composing a confession prayer extracted from The Sūtra of the Sublime Golden Light at the request of Döndrup Dorjé, the ruler of Shigatsé.\",\"label\":\"i.27\",\"sort\":209,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"da12800c-45d0-46e1-8015-03efb2775a15\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-93\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":207,\"uuid\":\"131f5605-1a6a-4e88-8dbf-cce9b5c6186d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This is his name as given in \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":29}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Princeton Dictionary of Buddhism \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":66},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"2194c5c9-5c1c-4ee6-8f8e-ec5a799277bf\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(p. 996). His name is variously given elsewhere as Wonchuk, Wen Tsheg, Yuance, Yuan Tso, and in Tibetan translation as Dzoksal (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":66,\"end\":194}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"rdzogs gsal\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":194,\"end\":205},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":194,\"end\":205,\"uuid\":\"416b0049-cb65-4de4-ae63-15ee24f7a902\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\").\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":205,\"end\":207}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d244b45e-0410-490a-84fe-86e1bb0dbb50\",\"sort\":17630,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.20\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The commentary in the Tengyur that quotes from the sūtra more than any other‍—twenty times in all‍—is the translation by Gö Chödrup of An Extensive Commentary on the Sūtra that Elucidates the Profound Intention by the Korean monk Wŏnch’ŭk (613–96), who had migrated to China. This commentary by Wŏnch’ŭk in Tibetan translation became a particular influence on the thought of Tsongkhapa, the founder of the Gelukpa school. The sūtra has been quoted by great masters in all the schools of Tibetan Buddhism and extracts from it were published in Tibet as numerous standalone texts‍—not only the confession prayer but also other chapters, such as the treatise on kingship. Its continuing significance is indicated by Pema Karpo (1527–92), the hierarch of the Drukpa Kagyü school, composing a confession prayer extracted from The Sūtra of the Sublime Golden Light at the request of Döndrup Dorjé, the ruler of Shigatsé.\",\"label\":\"i.27\",\"sort\":209,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"da12800c-45d0-46e1-8015-03efb2775a15\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-93\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":45,\"uuid\":\"d244b45e-0410-490a-84fe-86e1bb0dbb50\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Princeton Dictionary of Buddhism,\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":37},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"96550593-ee67-4b72-a756-5544bf612a5f\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" p. 189.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":37,\"end\":45}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bcc2523c-aac1-483c-bbbb-9d74a38c7d8d\",\"sort\":17633,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.21\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Toh 555 was translated into Tibetan from Chinese. The source text was Yijing’s seventh-century translation from Sanskrit into Chinese, and therefore the translation differs throughout, even though the content is essentially the same. There are many passages that are actually shorter versions of those in the translations from Sanskrit. Its greater length compared to Toh 556 is primarily due to the addition of chapters 29 and 30.\",\"label\":\"i.33\",\"sort\":250,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"9bdd390a-1016-430b-b5f9-b872bdd5048a\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-102\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1092,\"uuid\":\"bcc2523c-aac1-483c-bbbb-9d74a38c7d8d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"No Sanskrit title is given since this version was translated from the Chinese. The rendering of the Chinese title varies in different editions of the Kangyur. The Degé has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":172}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tā shin kyin kwang myutsa’i shin wang kyin.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":172,\"end\":215},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"61ed5ed9-ca9d-41b8-b154-a28668fea42c\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" The Yongle has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":215,\"end\":231}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ta’i ching gim gom mang dza’i shing wang gyi.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":231,\"end\":276},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"282cd07c-e61a-471b-99b1-7b52365be65a\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" The Kangxi has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":276,\"end\":292}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ta’i ching gin grom ming dza’i shing wang gying.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":292,\"end\":340},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"723b612a-21ac-4fd6-8a7a-467d4d66510a\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" The Narthang reads \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":340,\"end\":360}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"de’i shing ki ma kwang med dzwa’i shing wang kyang.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":360,\"end\":411},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"58022b8a-3661-4125-aaa8-1e76e7b291d3\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" The Lhasa version has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":411,\"end\":434}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tā shin kyin kwang mya ru tsa’i shin wa da kyin.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":434,\"end\":482},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"fb58876a-df15-4080-b761-ed32a097ce43\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" These appear to be variants as a result of differing regional pronunciations and scribal corruptions of what would now be written as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":482,\"end\":616}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Da cheng jin guang ming zui sheng wang jing \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":616,\"end\":660},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e34b77da-7640-4695-b41f-7c6d5585b190\",\"lang\":\"Zh-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"大乘金光明最勝王經. Zhiyi 智顗 (538–97), a.k.a. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":660,\"end\":697}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Tiantai zhizhe dashi\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":697,\"end\":717},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":697,\"end\":717,\"uuid\":\"3d16c8aa-7cbe-45d2-9652-080713d1cd74\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Zh-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" 天台智者大師, writing in his commentary on this sūtra titled \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":717,\"end\":773}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Jin guang ming jing xuan yi \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":773,\"end\":801},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"393539b0-dfb7-49a0-8635-490c61caefaa\",\"lang\":\"Zh-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"金光明經玄義, cited Paramārtha (a.k.a. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":801,\"end\":834}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Zhendi\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":834,\"end\":840},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":834,\"end\":840,\"uuid\":\"16d48215-b5e1-48dd-b1d7-7c77235f6750\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Zh-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" 真諦) in giving the Sanskrit pronunciation of the title of the sūtra as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":840,\"end\":911}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Xiu ba na po po po yu do mo yin tuo luo zhe yue na xiu duo luo \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":911,\"end\":974},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f1ad7b66-c209-4f6b-bce5-cee36c209245\",\"lang\":\"Zh-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"修跋拏婆頗婆欝多摩因陀羅遮閱那修多羅, presumably transcribing \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":974,\"end\":1018}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Suvarṇa­prabhāsottama­rāja­sūtraṃ.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1018,\"end\":1052},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"88549450-3523-4ff1-8aaa-a85c973d2e0e\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" The CBETA collection appears to concur.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1052,\"end\":1092}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e6ead452-ba4c-44fc-815b-40960d5d35e1\",\"sort\":17669,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.22\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"[B1] I pay homage to all the buddhas, bodhisattvas, pratyekabuddhas, and noble śrāvakas of the past, future, and present. Thus did I hear at one time. The Bhagavat was within the profound, completely pure Dharma realm that is the sublime field of activity of the tathāgatas, dwelling at Vulture Peak Mountain at Rājagṛha, together with a saṅgha of ninety-eight thousand great bhikṣus. All of them were great arhats, perfectly tamed like the king of elephants. Their defilements had ceased, they were devoid of kleśas, their minds were completely liberated, their wisdom was completely liberated, they had done what had to be done, they had put down their burdens, they had attained their goals, they had cut through engagement with existence, they had attained supreme and sublime power, they had perfectly maintained pure conduct, they were arrayed with methods and wisdom, they had manifested the eight liberations, and they had reached the farther shore.\",\"label\":\"1.1\",\"sort\":916,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"1fdf707e-dc17-4874-8443-4634f4ee88e3\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-166\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":434,\"uuid\":\"e6ead452-ba4c-44fc-815b-40960d5d35e1\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"There have been two ways to interpret this traditional beginning of a sūtra, with such Indian masters as Kamalaśīla claiming that both are equally correct. The alternative interpretation is “Thus did I hear: at one time the Bhagavān …” and so on. The various arguments, both traditional and modern, for either side are given by Brian Galloway in “Thus Have I Heard: At one time…” \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":380}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Indo-Iranian Journal \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":380,\"end\":401},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"038c0e7b-989e-457f-b3c0-fb51d4a58912\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"34, Issue 2 (April 1991): 87–104.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":401,\"end\":434}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"28d92c9f-59b9-4e8e-95a4-c1eb50e9771d\",\"sort\":17673,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.23\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"[B1] I pay homage to all the buddhas, bodhisattvas, pratyekabuddhas, and noble śrāvakas of the past, future, and present. Thus did I hear at one time. The Bhagavat was within the profound, completely pure Dharma realm that is the sublime field of activity of the tathāgatas, dwelling at Vulture Peak Mountain at Rājagṛha, together with a saṅgha of ninety-eight thousand great bhikṣus. All of them were great arhats, perfectly tamed like the king of elephants. Their defilements had ceased, they were devoid of kleśas, their minds were completely liberated, their wisdom was completely liberated, they had done what had to be done, they had put down their burdens, they had attained their goals, they had cut through engagement with existence, they had attained supreme and sublime power, they had perfectly maintained pure conduct, they were arrayed with methods and wisdom, they had manifested the eight liberations, and they had reached the farther shore.\",\"label\":\"1.1\",\"sort\":916,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"1fdf707e-dc17-4874-8443-4634f4ee88e3\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-166\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":54,\"uuid\":\"28d92c9f-59b9-4e8e-95a4-c1eb50e9771d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 555 has “ten million times ninety-eight thousand.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":54}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"209d87c4-f78c-44fb-aaac-a2ee8d6a433e\",\"sort\":17675,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.24\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$25\",\"label\":\"1.3\",\"sort\":1007,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"d1168543-98bf-4a26-8a3e-50c3af6289ba\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-172\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":28,\"uuid\":\"209d87c4-f78c-44fb-aaac-a2ee8d6a433e\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 555 has “a quintillion.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":28}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"25c79e27-11ee-442f-bcb9-77c0db443b9e\",\"sort\":17677,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.25\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$26\",\"label\":\"1.4\",\"sort\":1037,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"3daf33d4-d723-43ee-9876-e21c99bbbb1b\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-174\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":23,\"uuid\":\"25c79e27-11ee-442f-bcb9-77c0db443b9e\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 555 has Dharmabala.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":23}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5a072995-b989-44b6-90de-51f4d21443c3\",\"sort\":17679,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.26\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$27\",\"label\":\"1.4\",\"sort\":1037,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"3daf33d4-d723-43ee-9876-e21c99bbbb1b\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-174\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":27,\"uuid\":\"5a072995-b989-44b6-90de-51f4d21443c3\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 555 has Viśuddhaprajña.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":27}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"990b3631-e5bf-489c-940d-d795a136e49c\",\"sort\":17681,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.27\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$28\",\"label\":\"1.4\",\"sort\":1037,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"3daf33d4-d723-43ee-9876-e21c99bbbb1b\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-174\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":27,\"uuid\":\"990b3631-e5bf-489c-940d-d795a136e49c\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 555 has Ascetic Effort.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":27}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"54a16683-b8bc-4279-8008-2a85463bc05f\",\"sort\":17683,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.28\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$29\",\"label\":\"1.4\",\"sort\":1037,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"3daf33d4-d723-43ee-9876-e21c99bbbb1b\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-174\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":22,\"uuid\":\"54a16683-b8bc-4279-8008-2a85463bc05f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 555 has Noble Joy.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":22}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"41e127d9-7337-4332-acad-f3871bdc57c9\",\"sort\":17685,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.29\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$2a\",\"label\":\"1.4\",\"sort\":1037,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"3daf33d4-d723-43ee-9876-e21c99bbbb1b\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-174\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":41,\"uuid\":\"41e127d9-7337-4332-acad-f3871bdc57c9\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 555 has Great Cloud Dharma Protector.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":41}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1eaacd77-9d71-45dc-847e-ef29a9c0de7e\",\"sort\":17687,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.30\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$2b\",\"label\":\"1.4\",\"sort\":1037,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"3daf33d4-d723-43ee-9876-e21c99bbbb1b\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-174\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":41,\"uuid\":\"1eaacd77-9d71-45dc-847e-ef29a9c0de7e\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 555 has Great Cloud Limitless Renown.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":41}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c930a3f9-656e-4cb6-99db-08ca56023f9f\",\"sort\":17689,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.31\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$2c\",\"label\":\"1.4\",\"sort\":1037,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"3daf33d4-d723-43ee-9876-e21c99bbbb1b\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-174\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":43,\"uuid\":\"c930a3f9-656e-4cb6-99db-08ca56023f9f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 555 has Great Cloud Precious Qualities.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":43}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"15cbf3ed-5c2f-4181-a183-4af8d0d89a5d\",\"sort\":17691,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.32\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$2d\",\"label\":\"1.4\",\"sort\":1037,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"3daf33d4-d723-43ee-9876-e21c99bbbb1b\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-174\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":53,\"uuid\":\"15cbf3ed-5c2f-4181-a183-4af8d0d89a5d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 555 has Great Cloud Wisdom Rain Thoroughly Equal.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":53}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a11f8b4a-ef4d-4b4b-8617-321386919bd0\",\"sort\":17693,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.33\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"There were also 580,000 Licchavī youths. Among them were Kumāra Lion’s Light, Kumāra Siṃhamati, Kumāra Dharmadatta, Kumāra Powerful Bestower, Kumāra Mahāprabha, Kumāra Great Glory, Kumāra Buddhapālita, Kumāra Dharmapāla, Kumāra Sustaining the Saṅgha, Kumāra Vajra Guard, Kumāra Ākāśapāla, Kumāra Ākāśaghoṣa, Kumāra Ratnagarbha, Kumāra Supreme Auspicious Essence, and so on. They were pleasantly established in the highest, most complete enlightenment and had perfect aspiration for the Mahāyāna. During that afternoon they had come into the presence of the Bhagavat, bowed down their heads to the feet of the Bhagavat, circumambulated him three times, keeping him to their right, and sat to one side.\",\"label\":\"1.5\",\"sort\":1171,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"9ec9e373-a16c-4474-9a5e-e04f70ef5412\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-183\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":81,\"uuid\":\"a11f8b4a-ef4d-4b4b-8617-321386919bd0\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 555 states that there were “eight hundred thousand times a hundred thousand.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":81}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7b5f3a81-1b92-4543-8f08-5073fb7c9f9d\",\"sort\":17695,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.34\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"There were also 42,000 devas. Among them were Deva Beautiful to See, Deva Pramudita, Deva Sūryaprabha, Deva Moon Crest, Deva Clear Insight, Deva Ākāśa­viśuddha­prajña, Deva Remover of Affliction, Deva Maṅgala, and so on. They had made the vast prayer to guard the Mahāyāna Dharma, to hold the true Dharma, and to prevent its discontinuation. During that afternoon they had come into the presence of the Bhagavat, bowed down their heads to the feet of the Bhagavat, circumambulated him three times, keeping him to their right, and then sat to one side.\",\"label\":\"1.6\",\"sort\":1240,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"5d9db405-9e91-4911-9bfe-09fe8e152cc9\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-185\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":71,\"uuid\":\"7b5f3a81-1b92-4543-8f08-5073fb7c9f9d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to the Narthang and Lhasa versions of Toh 556 and to Toh 555.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":71}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"580a49db-5074-4891-a63f-9243bc378251\",\"sort\":17697,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.35\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"There were also gandharvas, asuras, kinnaras, kumbhāṇḍas, and mahoragas; divine ṛṣis of mountains, forests, rivers, and seas; great kings and their retinues, queens, attendants, sons, noblemen, and noblewomen; and devas, humans, and so on. They had all prayed to read, recite, possess and hold, question, spread, guard, and protect this unsurpassable Mahāyāna Dharma. During that afternoon all of them had come into the presence of the Bhagavat, bowed down their heads to the feet of the Bhagavat, circumambulated him three times, keeping him to their right, and sat to one side.\",\"label\":\"1.10\",\"sort\":1384,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"36b6f668-1ddd-440e-b6ef-d7d4e74baf5e\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-190\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":31,\"uuid\":\"580a49db-5074-4891-a63f-9243bc378251\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"dri\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":3},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":3,\"uuid\":\"1a5c24cd-0d53-4475-a822-636fe141d1e5\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Toh 555 has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":3,\"end\":17}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bri\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":17,\"end\":20},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":17,\"end\":20,\"uuid\":\"87358014-11f6-4c94-957b-1ad69434c59c\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“write”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":20,\"end\":31}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f63c0dae-68de-4a19-b134-fc88058d15b0\",\"sort\":17702,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.36\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“I will teach this Sublime Golden Light, Which is the lord of the kings of sūtras.\",\"label\":\"1.13\",\"sort\":1426,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"50a8236b-ac0e-4183-b41d-1cf2f7bc4578\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-194\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":73,\"uuid\":\"f63c0dae-68de-4a19-b134-fc88058d15b0\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 557 has “To the supreme bodhisattvas, / Who are pure and immaculate.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":73}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"76fe7b49-f8f4-4168-ad19-5764c866fcb6\",\"sort\":17704,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.37\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“This auspicious, sublime teaching Is in order to eliminate all bad actions. It causes all bad karma to cease.\",\"label\":\"1.17\",\"sort\":1458,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"bc93f63d-909a-486e-975b-408ee16d9d14\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-199\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":330,\"uuid\":\"76fe7b49-f8f4-4168-ad19-5764c866fcb6\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Sanskrit has four lines of verse: “I will teach that which is blessed, / Which is the supreme domain of good fortune, / Which has the purpose of annihilating all evil / And which brings to an end all evil.” Because of Tibetan syntax, the first line of this verse in English occurs at the end of the following verse in Tibetan.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":330}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"08c5f979-7450-4bb6-9035-7548a89e61fd\",\"sort\":17706,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.38\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“The lords of Brahmā devas, lords of the devas; The greatly powerful lords of the nāgas; And the lords of the kinnaras, the lords of the asuras, And similarly the lords of the garuḍas\",\"label\":\"1.27\",\"sort\":1547,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"df582b5d-184a-4ab8-aa48-ab8c49180593\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-209\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":394,\"uuid\":\"08c5f979-7450-4bb6-9035-7548a89e61fd\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Sanskrit has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":17}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tridaśendra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":17,\"end\":28},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":17,\"end\":28,\"uuid\":\"75af78bf-b1a1-479c-b3af-cb0661117a21\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“Lords of the Thirty”), referring to the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":28,\"end\":71}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Trāyastriṃśa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":71,\"end\":83},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"fb356f46-3c64-4256-8c64-7d0c8d24f7ba\",\"uuid\":\"20e2afda-9881-448b-8d5b-7bff338dda3a\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" paradise on the summit of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":83,\"end\":110}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Meru\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":110,\"end\":114},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"834dc5dc-8d4e-47b5-9e05-fa96dd153ea8\",\"uuid\":\"1004e16f-3789-42d0-b38b-b537f8614677\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". It is ruled by \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":114,\"end\":131}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Indra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":131,\"end\":136},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"7045ba28-23a7-4e65-ac32-3d872bad82dc\",\"uuid\":\"65452422-061e-4fd7-a544-2be58b345aaf\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", who is often referred to as “Devendra, lord of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":136,\"end\":185}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"devas\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":185,\"end\":190},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"a09787ca-2952-4bf6-a04c-bde6f4cf3e40\",\"uuid\":\"1dfad27c-39e0-470e-b23d-4221fd95892c\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".” The Sanskrit is in the plural, which is not evident in the Tibetan. This line refers to \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":190,\"end\":281}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Brahmā\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":281,\"end\":287},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"0ea2394f-1cfc-4258-a798-9a6eb4c60b62\",\"uuid\":\"dda4040e-2be5-47eb-84c2-fbdc6df99e73\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":287,\"end\":292}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Indra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":292,\"end\":297},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"7045ba28-23a7-4e65-ac32-3d872bad82dc\",\"uuid\":\"4a97c9b6-1011-4efb-baba-830d6f68c305\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", but in the plural it apparently refers to a number of such principal deities from other worlds.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":297,\"end\":394}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5e94e764-485b-4d4e-8e80-f74f1909fd5f\",\"sort\":17722,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.39\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“The lords of Brahmā devas, lords of the devas; The greatly powerful lords of the nāgas; And the lords of the kinnaras, the lords of the asuras, And similarly the lords of the garuḍas\",\"label\":\"1.27\",\"sort\":1547,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"df582b5d-184a-4ab8-aa48-ab8c49180593\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-209\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":305,\"uuid\":\"5e94e764-485b-4d4e-8e80-f74f1909fd5f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"In the Sanskrit, the last three lines of this verse read: “With the greatly powerful lords of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":98}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"kinnaras\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":98,\"end\":106},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"6efa6098-a749-48c8-ba73-e629967e1352\",\"uuid\":\"03d3c478-80db-4bda-8dd0-84d47b2edfe0\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", / And similarly with the lords of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":106,\"end\":146}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"garuḍas\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":146,\"end\":153},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"63a551d2-800b-4bc7-802d-cecec8515ad2\",\"uuid\":\"445731bd-bb4b-4e9d-8aad-7fba0ff132d1\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" / And the hosts of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":153,\"end\":173}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"yakṣas\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":173,\"end\":179},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"b4640039-6b60-4eb6-8695-1c0153d43a37\",\"uuid\":\"296724e9-0e28-4c8f-9eaa-f415cec91f75\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":179,\"end\":181}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"gandharvas\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":181,\"end\":191},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"e5ecdd12-cdf7-40f9-8159-f2a466a8563e\",\"uuid\":\"2e561f83-3857-4cf2-8f84-f29fc6b1878d\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":191,\"end\":197}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"pannas\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":197,\"end\":203},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":197,\"end\":203,\"uuid\":\"68c4bee7-b532-4140-a0d0-cca689edfb2b\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (serpents, i.e., \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":203,\"end\":221}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"nāgas\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":221,\"end\":226},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"5a08fb0f-b8eb-4159-8018-bfd9bd66d5d9\",\"uuid\":\"000c5b83-b28c-4f2d-9165-834e46b414f8\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\").” According to the Tibetan \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":226,\"end\":255}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"gnod byin\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":255,\"end\":264},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":255,\"end\":264,\"uuid\":\"f2ee7126-8e84-4630-910a-93c533ab3897\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The Sanskrit has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":264,\"end\":283}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"guhya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":283,\"end\":288},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":283,\"end\":288,\"uuid\":\"b5d44db0-361e-4a25-bd34-9bc9b7afdcdb\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“secret ones”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":288,\"end\":305}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9c3d74ec-8447-424a-a12b-675181cff196\",\"sort\":17740,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.40\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Throughout millions of eons Will themselves receive offerings From devas, nāgas, and humans, And from kinnaras, asuras, and yakṣas.\",\"label\":\"1.31\",\"sort\":1595,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"ec8c5fea-31a2-4247-91a1-7cd0896ab4fd\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-214\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":75,\"uuid\":\"9c3d74ec-8447-424a-a12b-675181cff196\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to the Tibetan \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":25}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"gnod byin\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":25,\"end\":34},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":25,\"end\":34,\"uuid\":\"2a05e81b-edfe-437c-bfa3-2d4086b0dc8b\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The Sanskrit has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":34,\"end\":53}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"guhya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":53,\"end\":58},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":53,\"end\":58,\"uuid\":\"6c898f26-8f0e-49c8-82a3-ffaae1aaaf79\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“secret ones”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":58,\"end\":75}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"fdb887bf-aa5b-4bdb-b1ae-a794f636e3d2\",\"sort\":17746,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.41\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“They will be taken into the care Of the perfect buddhas in the ten directions, And similarly by the bodhisattvas Who have profound activity.\",\"label\":\"1.33\",\"sort\":1623,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"889d138d-ae37-4ad2-8e66-8846e625eff0\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-217\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":57,\"uuid\":\"fdb887bf-aa5b-4bdb-b1ae-a794f636e3d2\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to the Tibetan. The Sanskrit has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":43}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sarva\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":43,\"end\":48},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":43,\"end\":48,\"uuid\":\"c197ae86-b78d-4012-ad9f-a1076f40eb7f\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“all”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":48,\"end\":57}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e3ea51d3-abb4-45f4-a771-d0f435c87837\",\"sort\":17750,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.42\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Having put on clean clothes, Wearing perfumed clothing, And having a loving mind, They should offer without distraction.\",\"label\":\"1.34\",\"sort\":1633,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"6de1c3ce-9a0a-4939-a3c1-3c52a640ec40\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-3207\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":77,\"uuid\":\"e3ea51d3-abb4-45f4-a771-d0f435c87837\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to the Tibetan. The Sanskrit for Toh 557 has “purified by perfume.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":77}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"37595199-9f8b-427c-82f6-f58dc0cec79b\",\"sort\":17752,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.43\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Having put on clean clothes, Wearing perfumed clothing, And having a loving mind, They should offer without distraction.\",\"label\":\"1.34\",\"sort\":1633,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"6de1c3ce-9a0a-4939-a3c1-3c52a640ec40\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-3207\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":88,\"uuid\":\"37595199-9f8b-427c-82f6-f58dc0cec79b\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to the Tibetan. The Sanskrit has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":43}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"atandrita\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":43,\"end\":52},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":43,\"end\":52,\"uuid\":\"2953e238-96f7-4fb3-a011-25080b0a53b4\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“without sleepiness or lethargy”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":52,\"end\":88}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a16d3d09-4c28-42b6-bb59-24ed41ea60be\",\"sort\":17756,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.44\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Those who listen to this sūtra Will be welcomed among humans, Will attain an excellent human existence, And will live happy lives.\",\"label\":\"1.36\",\"sort\":1651,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"9e00f126-6083-4d32-a298-2e4bd32cbc5f\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-3208\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":232,\"uuid\":\"a16d3d09-4c28-42b6-bb59-24ed41ea60be\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to the Sanskrit \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":26}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"svāgatam\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":26,\"end\":34},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":26,\"end\":34,\"uuid\":\"5935d3b0-432a-4f89-95e9-753e30e41562\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (literally, “well come”), which was translated into Tibetan as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":34,\"end\":98}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"legs par ’ongs\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":98,\"end\":112},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":98,\"end\":112,\"uuid\":\"d67bf2e5-6917-497e-b56d-26dfd5ce41cc\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". This could be interpreted as “come well among humans.” Toh 555 interprets this as meaning a good rebirth among humans.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":112,\"end\":232}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a5990b6a-991c-47dc-8658-c29d1e5f3db1\",\"sort\":17762,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.45\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Those who listen to this sūtra Will be welcomed among humans, Will attain an excellent human existence, And will live happy lives.\",\"label\":\"1.36\",\"sort\":1651,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"9e00f126-6083-4d32-a298-2e4bd32cbc5f\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-3208\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":132,\"uuid\":\"a5990b6a-991c-47dc-8658-c29d1e5f3db1\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to the Tibetan. The Sanskrit has “will easily attain a human result,” which presumably means the result of becoming human.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":132}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"21c2fc6a-94b4-4b36-8288-1ba5c406e9f3\",\"sort\":17764,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.46\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Those in whose ears This teaching sounds Will plant good roots And be praised by many buddhas.”\",\"label\":\"1.37\",\"sort\":1661,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"962ec0cc-9993-46bf-a764-e0fb98761734\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-3209\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":62,\"uuid\":\"21c2fc6a-94b4-4b36-8288-1ba5c406e9f3\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to the Tibetan. The Sanskrit translates as “enters.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":62}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1c3e154c-83d4-4082-9d6a-2945a2703ca1\",\"sort\":17766,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.47\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Also, at that time, there dwelled in the great city of Rājagṛha a bodhisattva mahāsattva by the name of Ruciraketu. He had served past jinas, had developed roots of merit, and had attended upon many hundreds of thousands of quintillions of buddhas. He thought, “Through what causes and what conditions does the Bhagavat Śākyamuni have such a short lifespan of eighty years?”\",\"label\":\"2.1\",\"sort\":1676,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"ad00ada5-c487-4c44-b767-638fc927dc46\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-226\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":58,\"uuid\":\"1c3e154c-83d4-4082-9d6a-2945a2703ca1\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"lhag par bya bar byas pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":24},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":24,\"uuid\":\"e8ae957e-b458-48bd-9c15-fc8f29999096\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Toh 557 has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":24,\"end\":38}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bsnyen bkur byas pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":38,\"end\":57},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":38,\"end\":57,\"uuid\":\"1f882339-0010-41ff-8dac-d8f2180d517b\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":57,\"end\":58}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9c6bc1ed-da03-409d-947f-30e798f1d95a\",\"sort\":17771,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.48\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Then he thought, “The Bhagavat has said, ‘There are two causes and two conditions for a long life. What are those two? Forsaking killing and giving food.’ The Bhagavat Śākyamuni has forsaken killing and has correctly adopted the path of the ten good actions for countless hundreds of thousands of quintillions of eons. He has given external and internal substances as food to beings, even to the extent of satisfying hungry beings with his own body, blood, bones, and limbs, to say nothing of every other kind of food.”\",\"label\":\"2.2\",\"sort\":1692,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"60a07274-550a-4ac1-9457-151a20a6351e\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-228\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":79,\"uuid\":\"9c6bc1ed-da03-409d-947f-30e798f1d95a\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"yang dag par blangs te gnas par gyur\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":36},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":36,\"uuid\":\"fb54293a-b93b-4a2f-9515-48110ab7d7c0\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Toh 557 has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":36,\"end\":50}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"yang dag par blangs par gyur\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":50,\"end\":78},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":50,\"end\":78,\"uuid\":\"ef5bab53-e2c7-4040-86e9-d7f2dce6b813\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":78,\"end\":79}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"89f1956a-18d5-4d5f-b2a7-8488a3ae805b\",\"sort\":17776,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.49\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Then he thought, “The Bhagavat has said, ‘There are two causes and two conditions for a long life. What are those two? Forsaking killing and giving food.’ The Bhagavat Śākyamuni has forsaken killing and has correctly adopted the path of the ten good actions for countless hundreds of thousands of quintillions of eons. He has given external and internal substances as food to beings, even to the extent of satisfying hungry beings with his own body, blood, bones, and limbs, to say nothing of every other kind of food.”\",\"label\":\"2.2\",\"sort\":1692,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"60a07274-550a-4ac1-9457-151a20a6351e\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-228\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":28,\"uuid\":\"89f1956a-18d5-4d5f-b2a7-8488a3ae805b\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"cher na\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":7},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":7,\"uuid\":\"2a8d8d6c-e63d-421a-8240-391edbb43442\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Toh 557 has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":7,\"end\":21}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tha na\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":21,\"end\":27},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":21,\"end\":27,\"uuid\":\"ac063b2f-82e8-44ee-90cb-9efd4c7b11de\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":27,\"end\":28}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b24d76d7-c8fe-49d8-8abe-95da655fe136\",\"sort\":17781,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.50\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"When that sublime being’s mind had thought that, with his attention focused upon the Buddha, his house became immense, vast, and made of blue beryl. It was adorned with many divine jewels, its color transformed by the Tathāgata, and it was pervaded by a perfume that transcended the divine.\",\"label\":\"2.3\",\"sort\":1708,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"2228856a-579f-4774-a774-62cd50864647\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-231\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":611,\"uuid\":\"b24d76d7-c8fe-49d8-8abe-95da655fe136\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This obscure compound, in Sanskrit \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":35}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tathāgatavigrahaṃ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":35,\"end\":52},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":35,\"end\":52,\"uuid\":\"8d410fcf-f84f-4bb9-8e66-535d918808fe\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":52,\"end\":55}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tathāgata\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":55,\"end\":64},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"e73562d6-15c5-4706-82c3-8f843ccfec58\",\"uuid\":\"390498b8-f0f0-41f7-9679-7b2faef94442\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" form” or “\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":64,\"end\":75}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tathāgata\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":75,\"end\":84},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"e73562d6-15c5-4706-82c3-8f843ccfec58\",\"uuid\":\"61168acc-4a6e-4931-bd22-3edc15bcdb60\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" beauty”), with no indication as to whether \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":84,\"end\":128}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tathāgata\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":128,\"end\":137},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"e73562d6-15c5-4706-82c3-8f843ccfec58\",\"uuid\":\"b70ee209-b764-40b8-97f5-7da2c90d5050\",\"toh\":null,\"start\":128,\"end\":0}},{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":128,\"end\":137,\"uuid\":\"72b1c29e-9946-472f-b09b-639d59d4b46c\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is singular or plural, was translated into Tibetan here with interpolation as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":137,\"end\":216}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"de bzhin gshegs pas kha dog bsgyur ba\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":216,\"end\":253},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":216,\"end\":253,\"uuid\":\"034012d2-724d-4035-a365-a8742d72cfd7\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“color transformed by the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":253,\"end\":281}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Tathāgata\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":281,\"end\":290},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"e73562d6-15c5-4706-82c3-8f843ccfec58\",\"uuid\":\"cf80a9cc-94f5-4ea7-bcca-70722e94825c\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"”). In Sanskrit, it is evident that this is an adjective for the house. The Tibetan does at times use \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":290,\"end\":392}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"kha dog\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":392,\"end\":399},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":392,\"end\":399,\"uuid\":\"a94f9ca0-4721-4cd1-96d9-fda8c3bd7d9b\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" to translate \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":399,\"end\":413}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"varṇa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":413,\"end\":418},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":413,\"end\":418,\"uuid\":\"46729002-30ab-49a2-8b78-a877deef5cad\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" when it does not mean color specifically but form and shape. In Toh 555, it has been interpreted to mean that the house has the appearance of a buddha realm through the blessing of the Buddha.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":418,\"end\":611}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ae718c49-d51c-4b80-8251-e8c4c0349c76\",\"sort\":17799,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.51\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"In the four directions of that house there appeared four thrones made of divine jewels. The thrones were overspread with layers of precious, divine cloth decorated with divine jewels.\",\"label\":\"2.4\",\"sort\":1714,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"fc7850e7-4135-487a-89d9-3252b8f3859e\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-233\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":81,\"uuid\":\"ae718c49-d51c-4b80-8251-e8c4c0349c76\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"From the Tibetan \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":17}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"phrugs\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":17,\"end\":23},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":17,\"end\":23,\"uuid\":\"ae33438d-6c87-4907-9715-4ee5c901a13a\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The Sanskrit \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":23,\"end\":38}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"paryaṅgka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":38,\"end\":47},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":38,\"end\":47,\"uuid\":\"996c8185-1244-4787-8ca3-08b735992fe8\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" could mean a “seat” or “cushion.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":47,\"end\":81}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d813d6c6-ce33-43d7-bafa-f227875ad0d8\",\"sort\":17805,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.52\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"In the four directions of that house there appeared four thrones made of divine jewels. The thrones were overspread with layers of precious, divine cloth decorated with divine jewels.\",\"label\":\"2.4\",\"sort\":1714,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"fc7850e7-4135-487a-89d9-3252b8f3859e\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-233\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":108,\"uuid\":\"d813d6c6-ce33-43d7-bafa-f227875ad0d8\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"From the Sanskrit \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":18}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"divyaratna­puṣpa­patraiḥ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":18,\"end\":42},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":18,\"end\":42,\"uuid\":\"533cad08-76f3-4c45-ac27-f72bf9edd427\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The Tibetan has the less specific \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":42,\"end\":78}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bcos bu’i rin po che’i phrugs\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":78,\"end\":107},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":78,\"end\":107,\"uuid\":\"05b67ace-aaa5-46f0-8f3d-cf09a74b6e1f\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":107,\"end\":108}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"659fdbf8-be3b-4a3a-8d00-a84f2485883b\",\"sort\":17811,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.53\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$2e\",\"label\":\"2.5\",\"sort\":1719,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"12e5fa1f-174a-4fff-8c40-3aa0b5e1c257\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-236\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":89,\"uuid\":\"659fdbf8-be3b-4a3a-8d00-a84f2485883b\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to the Sanskrit \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":26}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"teṣu\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":26,\"end\":30},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":26,\"end\":30,\"uuid\":\"9cfa5397-a1e9-432f-b61c-a3e2d7ed8cce\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The Tibetan has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":30,\"end\":48}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"las\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":48,\"end\":51},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":48,\"end\":51,\"uuid\":\"a74517be-dfc6-4e22-afe2-64dee909274c\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“from”), apparently in error for \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":51,\"end\":86}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"la\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":86,\"end\":88},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":86,\"end\":88,\"uuid\":\"60971884-4784-44c5-be38-a1cb2bc214ff\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":88,\"end\":89}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d9e04992-a786-445d-b1d3-832c7efb6334\",\"sort\":17819,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.54\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$2f\",\"label\":\"2.5\",\"sort\":1719,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"12e5fa1f-174a-4fff-8c40-3aa0b5e1c257\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-236\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":319,\"uuid\":\"d9e04992-a786-445d-b1d3-832c7efb6334\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This obscure compound‍—in Sanskrit \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":35}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tathāgatavigraha\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":35,\"end\":51},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":35,\"end\":51,\"uuid\":\"0923f387-7c57-443f-a3aa-fde3b113692d\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":51,\"end\":54}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tathāgata\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":54,\"end\":63},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"e73562d6-15c5-4706-82c3-8f843ccfec58\",\"uuid\":\"a21b49f3-c8a2-40ec-9b63-fa8dc7199bfe\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" form” or “\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":63,\"end\":74}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tathāgata\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":74,\"end\":83},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"e73562d6-15c5-4706-82c3-8f843ccfec58\",\"uuid\":\"fa495a75-48cb-42cb-a380-4512c3662295\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" beauty”)‍—was translated into Tibetan with interpolation as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":83,\"end\":144}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"de bzhin gshegs pas kha dog [bsgyur ba]\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":144,\"end\":183},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":144,\"end\":183,\"uuid\":\"239dff78-6bcb-4cb9-8752-5862748824f1\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“colors [transformed by] the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":183,\"end\":214}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Tathāgata\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":214,\"end\":223},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"e73562d6-15c5-4706-82c3-8f843ccfec58\",\"uuid\":\"c7e304e5-756b-4d4a-b56c-5788670b2224\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"”). Toh 555 interprets this to mean “their sizes were in proportion to those of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":223,\"end\":307}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tathāgatas\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":307,\"end\":317},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"e73562d6-15c5-4706-82c3-8f843ccfec58\",\"uuid\":\"67eeb8d7-5b26-4c23-ac67-a8a1101a0ce8\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":317,\"end\":319}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"80d61e93-794e-4614-a023-a0307209ebde\",\"sort\":17833,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.55\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$30\",\"label\":\"2.5\",\"sort\":1719,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"12e5fa1f-174a-4fff-8c40-3aa0b5e1c257\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-236\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":44,\"uuid\":\"80d61e93-794e-4614-a023-a0307209ebde\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"rnam par g.yengs pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":19},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":19,\"uuid\":\"4b9e5076-5f67-41e9-952e-07e614df7dd2\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Toh 557 has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":19,\"end\":33}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"g.yengs ba\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":33,\"end\":43},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":33,\"end\":43,\"uuid\":\"272b373d-3dfe-427f-af9d-95a44ab361b5\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":43,\"end\":44}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"35fafcb1-bffa-49ad-8a92-8008f7bc5160\",\"sort\":17838,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.56\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$31\",\"label\":\"2.5\",\"sort\":1719,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"12e5fa1f-174a-4fff-8c40-3aa0b5e1c257\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-236\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":132,\"uuid\":\"35fafcb1-bffa-49ad-8a92-8008f7bc5160\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"skom pa rnams ni skom dang phrad par gyur\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":41},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":41,\"uuid\":\"c4f79b69-d39c-4032-a658-05582434a3b9\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Toh 557 has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":41,\"end\":55}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"skom pa dag ni skom ngoms par gyur\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":55,\"end\":89},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":55,\"end\":89,\"uuid\":\"cbc8a9aa-00d9-4410-8240-4f40a085b4ed\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“the thirsty had their thirst quenched”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":89,\"end\":132}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"044cf6df-a11f-4249-b1ed-3056252c12e2\",\"sort\":17843,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.57\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The bodhisattva Ruciraketu was amazed to see those buddha bhagavats, and, filled with joy, delighted, elated, pleased, and happy, with his palms together in homage, he bowed toward those buddha bhagavats. Mindful of those buddha bhagavats and mindful of the qualities of the Buddha Bhagavat Śākyamuni, he had doubts concerning the lifespan of the Bhagavat Śākyamuni. In his mind was the thought, “Why is it that the Bhagavat Śākyamuni has this short lifespan of eighty years?”\",\"label\":\"2.6\",\"sort\":1761,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"cb9db483-a68d-404f-88dc-b36304ac3c8a\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-241\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":47,\"uuid\":\"044cf6df-a11f-4249-b1ed-3056252c12e2\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Sanskrit here has “bodhisattva \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":35}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mahāsattva\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":35,\"end\":45},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"d1c7dfac-7376-48af-bc36-07491c77e7ac\",\"uuid\":\"1abb0637-6d3e-4123-9621-e026092619ff\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":45,\"end\":47}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b4cfb97f-a252-4e34-95da-21b150ba657d\",\"sort\":17847,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.58\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“If all Sumerus were reduced to atoms, Their number could be calculated, But no one can calculate The lifespan of Śākyamuni.\",\"label\":\"2.11\",\"sort\":1863,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"39d68a1c-c8e9-4e62-b0ae-a81eaa08474e\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-247\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":81,\"uuid\":\"b4cfb97f-a252-4e34-95da-21b150ba657d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The plural is according to the Tibetan. It is singular in the available Sanskrit.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":81}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f29a09cc-a73a-4dcf-b348-4f23cc77a74f\",\"sort\":17849,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.59\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“If all Sumerus were reduced to atoms, Their number could be calculated, But no one can calculate The lifespan of Śākyamuni.\",\"label\":\"2.11\",\"sort\":1863,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"39d68a1c-c8e9-4e62-b0ae-a81eaa08474e\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-247\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":69,\"uuid\":\"f29a09cc-a73a-4dcf-b348-4f23cc77a74f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 557 has “The number of atoms in all / \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":42}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sumerus\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":42,\"end\":49},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"834dc5dc-8d4e-47b5-9e05-fa96dd153ea8\",\"uuid\":\"40ea0354-3e6a-400d-9d4a-7a0454588cd8\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" can be calculated…”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":49,\"end\":69}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"3d79671b-af6b-4b7f-bfdf-89be8de231ad\",\"sort\":17853,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.60\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“This is because of two causes And because of two conditions: He has forsaken violence toward others, And he has given food numerous times.\",\"label\":\"2.15\",\"sort\":1909,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"cca73634-4a7f-4540-abf1-3fd5f7f8e7fc\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-253\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":64,\"uuid\":\"3d79671b-af6b-4b7f-bfdf-89be8de231ad\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to Toh 557 and the Sanskrit. Here “cause” is repeated.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":64}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"8795cd0e-d815-4c18-b8db-093e3b494eb7\",\"sort\":17855,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.61\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Therefore, the length of the great being’s Lifespan cannot be calculated By saying it is a certain number of eons, Or likewise by saying it is countless eons.\",\"label\":\"2.16\",\"sort\":1919,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"d3de72c7-10d4-49a0-abe8-9853776f6d53\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-255\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":97,\"uuid\":\"8795cd0e-d815-4c18-b8db-093e3b494eb7\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to the Tibetan. The Sanskrit has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":43}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"saṃkhya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":43,\"end\":50},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":43,\"end\":50,\"uuid\":\"486e90e8-a648-4440-969a-ed3bb2fb8b1b\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“numbers”) instead of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":50,\"end\":74}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"asaṃkhya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":74,\"end\":82},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":74,\"end\":82,\"uuid\":\"d41f09d6-07d3-4393-b2b7-65187228451a\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“countless”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":82,\"end\":97}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"057ea50b-b405-4a23-acca-3f4c41d4db64\",\"sort\":17861,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.62\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"At that time, in that assembly, there was the Kauṇḍinya brahmin, the Dharma master Vyākaraṇa, who, together with countless thousands of brahmins, had made offerings to the Bhagavat. On hearing these words concerning the great nirvāṇa of the Tathāgata, he immediately wept, bowed down to the feet of the Bhagavat, and said to the Bhagavat, “If you have love for all beings, if you have great compassion, if you wish to benefit them, if you are a mother and father for all beings, if you are unequaled, if you are like the moon radiating light, if you are like a risen sun of great wisdom and knowledge, and if you look upon all beings as you do upon Rāhula, then I pray that you grant me something sacred.”\",\"label\":\"2.33\",\"sort\":2115,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"1456b522-89bd-41a9-b55e-95ee48c9f47b\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-273\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1353,\"uuid\":\"057ea50b-b405-4a23-acca-3f4c41d4db64\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This line shows significant variation across sources and is difficult to interpret precisely. Toh 556 and 557 render this figure’s name as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":139}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"slob dpon lung ston pa bram ze kauN+Di n+ya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":139,\"end\":182},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":139,\"end\":182,\"uuid\":\"23840302-e678-4ac4-8eec-e046b2ecb5f1\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", which can be interpreted to mean “the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":182,\"end\":222}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Kauṇḍinya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":222,\"end\":231},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"aa2c2a31-ffdb-4887-a677-972a8ec87ca3\",\"uuid\":\"530fe098-6d4f-426b-98e3-58ae5054e0c3\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":231,\"end\":232}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"brahmin\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":232,\"end\":239},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"41a01c6c-e7cf-4689-b3bb-4cdb181c88b6\",\"uuid\":\"69b016fa-5fd2-462a-b290-09c3ab9ed10c\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", the Dharma master \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":239,\"end\":259}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Vyākaraṇa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":259,\"end\":268},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"4ab87917-09a8-4fc8-86f0-bcf3470b170a\",\"uuid\":\"ffd6546f-0bd3-4baf-a705-d92fd45a6904\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".” The extant Sanskrit reads \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":268,\"end\":297}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ācāryavyākaraṇaprāptaḥ kauṇḍinyo nāma brāhmaṇaḥ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":297,\"end\":344},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":297,\"end\":344,\"uuid\":\"81cd36f2-942e-4dc2-b637-c6933c78cfb4\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", which could be taken to mean “the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":344,\"end\":380}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"brahmin\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":380,\"end\":387},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"41a01c6c-e7cf-4689-b3bb-4cdb181c88b6\",\"uuid\":\"0ed65776-b0ea-44f1-8bc5-db0b0ba81637\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" named \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":387,\"end\":394}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Kauṇḍinya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":394,\"end\":403},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"aa2c2a31-ffdb-4887-a677-972a8ec87ca3\",\"uuid\":\"6ebbff7d-ee19-4fa0-b828-b90a7f1c51bc\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" who had obtained a prophecy from a/the Dharma master.” The Sanskrit line includes the term “obtained” (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":403,\"end\":507}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"prāpta\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":507,\"end\":513},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":507,\"end\":513,\"uuid\":\"f48e1a47-1428-46f1-b411-da321db6b28a\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), which is not attested in the Chinese or Tibetan sources. The translation here follows the Chinese text that is the basis of Toh 555 in regarding \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":513,\"end\":661}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"kauṇḍinya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":661,\"end\":670},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":661,\"end\":670,\"uuid\":\"e332d958-a89e-448f-94f8-ca56ed57a158\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}},{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"aa2c2a31-ffdb-4887-a677-972a8ec87ca3\",\"uuid\":\"2d55dc06-93f8-4b71-ab2a-2848f3163cc3\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" as the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":670,\"end\":678}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"brahmin\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":678,\"end\":685},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"41a01c6c-e7cf-4689-b3bb-4cdb181c88b6\",\"uuid\":\"9dbe25af-0a15-4fba-bb98-101c06de31f2\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s family name (姓). This \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":685,\"end\":710}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"brahmin\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":710,\"end\":717},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"41a01c6c-e7cf-4689-b3bb-4cdb181c88b6\",\"uuid\":\"d76c1269-a48d-49f8-b81a-e255f3abf368\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is then “named (名曰) the Dharma master \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":717,\"end\":756}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Vyākaraṇa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":756,\"end\":765},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"4ab87917-09a8-4fc8-86f0-bcf3470b170a\",\"uuid\":\"85cb3796-3ac1-4486-8096-96f70cdf4b86\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (法師授記).” The Tibetan sources for Toh 555 appear to take \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":765,\"end\":822}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"kauṇḍinya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":822,\"end\":831},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":822,\"end\":831,\"uuid\":\"73856250-a19a-42ce-b16a-06ffbfc347f8\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}},{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"aa2c2a31-ffdb-4887-a677-972a8ec87ca3\",\"uuid\":\"3aabe8b8-eb77-435a-87ce-e9e58def9624\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" as the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":831,\"end\":839}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"brahmin\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":839,\"end\":846},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"41a01c6c-e7cf-4689-b3bb-4cdb181c88b6\",\"uuid\":\"8f60b3f7-d8ec-4252-9105-54975f4c8df2\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s proper name and treat the rest of the phrase as descriptive, reading “The \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":846,\"end\":923}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"brahmin\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":923,\"end\":930},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"41a01c6c-e7cf-4689-b3bb-4cdb181c88b6\",\"uuid\":\"7b184123-c055-4922-a789-53625336073f\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" named \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":930,\"end\":937}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Kauṇḍinya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":937,\"end\":946},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"aa2c2a31-ffdb-4887-a677-972a8ec87ca3\",\"uuid\":\"e7708721-54b0-4233-b3fa-1c061458bcd1\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" who was prophesied by a/the Dharma master (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":946,\"end\":990}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bram ze kauN+Di n+ya chos kyi slob dpon gyis lung bstan pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":990,\"end\":1048},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":990,\"end\":1048,\"uuid\":\"a69a9de6-0f83-40ea-ac75-8e76eaf30b91\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"). To further complicate matters, the Degé version of Toh 555 also declines \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1048,\"end\":1124}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"kauṇḍinya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1124,\"end\":1133},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1124,\"end\":1133,\"uuid\":\"3608d592-63ed-4871-b38a-61daed99f2ce\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}},{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"aa2c2a31-ffdb-4887-a677-972a8ec87ca3\",\"uuid\":\"3924d48f-e93a-4709-8595-8ef06af63aa6\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" in the instrumental, which would result in the reading “the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1133,\"end\":1194}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"brahmin\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1194,\"end\":1201},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"41a01c6c-e7cf-4689-b3bb-4cdb181c88b6\",\"uuid\":\"b872587b-c76f-4dc2-ad29-baba8c62c879\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" prophesied by the Dharma master \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1201,\"end\":1234}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Kauṇḍinya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1234,\"end\":1243},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"aa2c2a31-ffdb-4887-a677-972a8ec87ca3\",\"uuid\":\"e9a989d1-4be4-493e-8c01-2051c2be80b5\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".” The Kangxi, Lhasa, Narthang, Stok Palace, and Yongle versions of Toh 555 lack this instrumental declension.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1243,\"end\":1353}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9d3624c5-6c66-4867-94d6-57a9a892abac\",\"sort\":17909,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.63\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Licchavī youth,” said the brahmin, “I wish for a relic of the Bhagavat the size of a mustard seed in order to make offerings to the Bhagavat. It is known that if one makes offerings to a relic the size of a mustard seed that one has received as a share of the ashes that are the relics of the Bhagavat, one will become the sole lord of the devas of Trāyastriṃśa.\",\"label\":\"2.36\",\"sort\":2160,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"81c10481-2b95-4365-8c64-33f95cc151dc\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-277\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":111,\"uuid\":\"9d3624c5-6c66-4867-94d6-57a9a892abac\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"In this instance, the Sanskrit version of that paradise’s name is \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":66}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tridaśa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":66,\"end\":73},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":66,\"end\":73,\"uuid\":\"1c7d8fd0-26f7-46b8-8ce5-d8af2eb40b63\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“thirty” instead of “thirty-three”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":73,\"end\":111}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7c6a8035-72f3-40d5-8635-b0ed74ae8d0b\",\"sort\":17913,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.64\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“O Licchavī youth, it is difficult for śrāvakas and pratyekabuddhas to know The Sūtra of the Sublime Golden Light. It is difficult for them to comprehend it. The Sūtra of the Sublime Golden Light, which has those characteristics and qualities, is going to be spoken, so listen!\",\"label\":\"2.37\",\"sort\":2181,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"10725106-9a88-4b4d-903d-3266797ce05a\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-279\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1002,\"uuid\":\"7c6a8035-72f3-40d5-8635-b0ed74ae8d0b\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This paragraph may be a remnant of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":39}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Licchavī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":39,\"end\":47},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"83cef396-e5d4-4358-9bd2-076af1d9b37c\",\"uuid\":\"f564bcce-c9cc-4832-bbf4-31c99f1b90cd\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" youth’s response to the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":47,\"end\":72}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"brahmin\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":72,\"end\":79},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"41a01c6c-e7cf-4689-b3bb-4cdb181c88b6\",\"uuid\":\"8d65f1b2-25d5-4879-b69a-4d88666b71ae\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", which is here assigned to the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":79,\"end\":111}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"brahmin\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":111,\"end\":118},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"41a01c6c-e7cf-4689-b3bb-4cdb181c88b6\",\"uuid\":\"96ad3166-8215-44a0-85af-7b41a9ce07f1\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" instead. Although missing in both Toh 556 and Toh 557, the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":118,\"end\":178}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Licchavī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":178,\"end\":186},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"83cef396-e5d4-4358-9bd2-076af1d9b37c\",\"uuid\":\"02840ebb-a534-4898-b2a2-60cfedee22f3\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s response was evidently once present as can be seen from the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":186,\"end\":249}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"brahmin\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":249,\"end\":256},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"41a01c6c-e7cf-4689-b3bb-4cdb181c88b6\",\"uuid\":\"acf9389e-821f-4ad9-ac04-75b7ca037188\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s response to it, where he refers to “such characteristics and qualities.” This paragraph is present in Toh 555: “The youth then said to the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":256,\"end\":398}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"brahmin\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":398,\"end\":405},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"41a01c6c-e7cf-4689-b3bb-4cdb181c88b6\",\"uuid\":\"ac088ac9-ef9f-42c1-a1da-4e98b833bcb4\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", ‘If you wish to be reborn in the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":405,\"end\":440}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Trāyastriṃśa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":440,\"end\":452},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"fb356f46-3c64-4256-8c64-7d0c8d24f7ba\",\"uuid\":\"eedf9633-de42-4553-a6e4-764702342a55\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" paradise and enjoy the perfect ripening of karma, then you should listen, with single-pointed mind, to \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":452,\"end\":556}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Supremely Victorious King of Sūtras, the Sublime Golden Light.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":556,\"end\":622},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b96256bf-97b9-4e4c-9d7b-ed7de388de93\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" This sūtra is supreme among all sūtras, and therefore it is difficult to know and to penetrate. Therefore, the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":622,\"end\":734}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"śrāvakas\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":734,\"end\":742},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"df2147ef-e586-4828-a111-730705966794\",\"uuid\":\"b6918ad7-2c47-4edd-9eb7-509268832ec8\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":742,\"end\":747}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"pratyekabuddhas\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":747,\"end\":762},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"dd537b63-172f-4115-ac04-ef342e1774b7\",\"uuid\":\"aca140b6-5be3-4aea-bf74-edd2c2fc9ddb\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" are unable to comprehend it. This sūtra gives rise to the limitless ripening of the results of merit and accomplishes that until the attainment of the highest enlightenment. Today I have taught you just a little portion of that subject.’ ”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":762,\"end\":1002}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ff3dc6d3-867d-4295-9790-0c5fe458158d\",\"sort\":17935,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.65\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“The scope of the buddhas is inconceivable. The tathāgatas are without any equal. All buddhas are always in peace. All buddhas appear perfectly.\",\"label\":\"2.58\",\"sort\":2379,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"65da9a6d-8d80-46ae-82c5-ff8d226e3ee6\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-301\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":72,\"uuid\":\"ff3dc6d3-867d-4295-9790-0c5fe458158d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to the Tibetan. The Sanskrit has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":43}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"samācāra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":43,\"end\":51},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":43,\"end\":51,\"uuid\":\"7a012577-6bb5-4d77-b684-51cf6d9e249f\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“perfect conduct”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":51,\"end\":72}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a7dfa60a-490c-470f-a0a1-fbd5959c7236\",\"sort\":17939,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.66\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“All buddhas have the same color; That is the intrinsic nature of the buddhas. The Bhagavat is not fabricated, And the Tathāgata is not produced.\",\"label\":\"2.59\",\"sort\":2390,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"15eaecf5-3dca-42ff-95da-92a917ef4785\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-303\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":58,\"uuid\":\"a7dfa60a-490c-470f-a0a1-fbd5959c7236\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Vaidya’s Sanskrit has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":22}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"vaṇa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":22,\"end\":26},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":22,\"end\":26,\"uuid\":\"d7824f3d-ddd3-48c3-a32c-7fed0a871ada\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", apparently in error for \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":26,\"end\":52}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"varṇa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":52,\"end\":57},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":52,\"end\":57,\"uuid\":\"09fb2e50-e945-43b4-8cdb-9e7f97574c92\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":57,\"end\":58}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"84e98923-2cbc-469d-8733-5325180adab6\",\"sort\":17945,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.67\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“All buddhas have the same color; That is the intrinsic nature of the buddhas. The Bhagavat is not fabricated, And the Tathāgata is not produced.\",\"label\":\"2.59\",\"sort\":2390,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"15eaecf5-3dca-42ff-95da-92a917ef4785\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-303\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":56,\"uuid\":\"84e98923-2cbc-469d-8733-5325180adab6\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to the Sanskrit and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":30}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bcom ldan ’das\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":30,\"end\":44},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":30,\"end\":44,\"uuid\":\"de48174c-d2f5-475f-8361-d4f7e905603f\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" in Toh 557.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":44,\"end\":56}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a9389082-a082-4dc1-aacd-558994a4c8a7\",\"sort\":17949,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.68\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“He has a body like a vajra. He manifests an illusory body. The great Ṛṣi does not have relics, Not even of the size of a mustard seed.\",\"label\":\"2.60\",\"sort\":2404,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"dd336ec5-5749-4670-9b24-5cd52193b32d\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-306\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":117,\"uuid\":\"a9389082-a082-4dc1-aacd-558994a4c8a7\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Sanskrit has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":17}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"nirmitakāya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":17,\"end\":28},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":17,\"end\":28,\"uuid\":\"b977e399-e119-4a63-acdf-ca80f8a58bd3\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", which is synonymous with \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":28,\"end\":55}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"nirmāṇakāya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":55,\"end\":66},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":55,\"end\":66,\"uuid\":\"411142fe-7490-4424-b52c-de174d3d0f08\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Both are translated in Tibetan as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":66,\"end\":102}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sprul pa’i sku\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":102,\"end\":116},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":102,\"end\":116,\"uuid\":\"e24974e3-3773-44d9-990a-e46bc336ae05\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":116,\"end\":117}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e7026e47-e19d-4a39-aa5c-e8edba6a6c3d\",\"sort\":17957,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.69\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“I made that request for the sacred object Having already heard and understood that. I spoke in that way In order to reveal the truth.”\",\"label\":\"2.63\",\"sort\":2443,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"6373f08c-501f-4a19-a45c-1bc1dd6c58b0\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-310\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":137,\"uuid\":\"e7026e47-e19d-4a39-aa5c-e8edba6a6c3d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to the Tibetan \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":25}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bdag gis\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":25,\"end\":33},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":25,\"end\":33,\"uuid\":\"43bc35bb-78b2-43ca-b47e-350d10807779\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", presumably from the Sanskrit \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":33,\"end\":64}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mayā\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":64,\"end\":68},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":64,\"end\":68,\"uuid\":\"f6011711-8633-484d-ba2f-7fcb334ac972\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The available Sanskrit has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":68,\"end\":97}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mune\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":97,\"end\":101},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":97,\"end\":101,\"uuid\":\"186b3314-bbfa-473b-8263-95c2e4491f86\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“from the Muni” or “of the Muni”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":101,\"end\":137}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"12eed377-b0c3-4950-a374-e4de2816165b\",\"sort\":17965,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.70\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“I made that request for the sacred object Having already heard and understood that. I spoke in that way In order to reveal the truth.”\",\"label\":\"2.63\",\"sort\":2443,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"6373f08c-501f-4a19-a45c-1bc1dd6c58b0\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-310\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":32,\"uuid\":\"12eed377-b0c3-4950-a374-e4de2816165b\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This verse is absent in Toh 555.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":32}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b322957a-b7e6-42f1-99e4-0353314caf79\",\"sort\":17967,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.71\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Then thirty-two thousand devas, having heard that profound teaching on the lifespan of the Tathāgata, all developed the aspiration for the highest, most complete enlightenment. With joyful mental thoughts and with one voice, they recited these verses:\",\"label\":\"2.64\",\"sort\":2454,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"91ad31f5-91bd-4eec-a036-440b86938c76\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-313\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":66,\"uuid\":\"b322957a-b7e6-42f1-99e4-0353314caf79\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 556 has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":12}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sgra skad mthun par\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":12,\"end\":31},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":12,\"end\":31,\"uuid\":\"474cd37d-93ed-45c5-89df-ce3d1a57f633\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Toh 557 has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":31,\"end\":45}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sgra dbyangs gcig tu\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":45,\"end\":65},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":45,\"end\":65,\"uuid\":\"ec10ab67-c543-46d1-8717-ffdf4b4b2b42\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":65,\"end\":66}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"8cfdc4e1-da72-402d-bbce-0b828478f41b\",\"sort\":17973,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.72\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Then the bodhisattva Ruciraketu, having heard the teaching on the lifespan of the Bhagavat Śākyamuni from both those buddha bhagavats and those excellent individuals, arose from his seat, and with his palms together in homage, bowed and said, “Bhagavat, if in that way the buddha bhagavats do not pass into nirvāṇa and do not leave relics in the world, why is it that in the sūtras it is taught that the buddhas pass into nirvāṇa and leave their relics in the world so that if devas and humans have veneration and respect toward the relics of past buddhas that have been left in the world, and if the world with its devas and humans makes offerings to them, they will attain immeasurable benefit? And why is it said here that there are no relics, Bhagavat? I pray that with compassion you will explain and teach this.”\",\"label\":\"2.67\",\"sort\":2484,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"acb582ff-add7-4336-b36f-e541b1b02ade\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-317\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":121,\"uuid\":\"8cfdc4e1-da72-402d-bbce-0b828478f41b\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"From the meaning of the BHS \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":28}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"vibhajati\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":28,\"end\":37},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":28,\"end\":37,\"uuid\":\"427701b3-8705-4e72-9345-4cb690752dc6\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", translated into Tibetan literally as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":37,\"end\":76}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"rnam par dbye ba\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":76,\"end\":92},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":76,\"end\":92,\"uuid\":\"5dfe2b40-3b55-4b5a-86a4-b3bc5247e046\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“divide,” “differentiate”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":92,\"end\":121}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bf850fa8-b169-4eba-ab76-a24a15810c91\",\"sort\":17979,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.73\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Eighth, the tathāgatas know that someone whose nature is characterized by craving is engaged in seeking. Through the power of being engaged in seeking there will be the experience of various sufferings. The tathāgatas have eliminated fixation on ‘me’ and ‘mine’ and have no seeking; therefore, this is called nirvāṇa.\",\"label\":\"2.102\",\"sort\":2732,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"885a81f9-dd5d-4ab2-8543-958f3e8c105d\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-353\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":149,\"uuid\":\"bf850fa8-b169-4eba-ab76-a24a15810c91\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":13}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tshol ba\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":13,\"end\":21},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":13,\"end\":21,\"uuid\":\"7073793c-9740-4aaf-90ac-8a59be918278\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" in the Yongle, Narthang, and Choné versions of Toh 556, and in Toh 555. The Degé version of Toh 556 has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":21,\"end\":126}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tshor ba\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":126,\"end\":134},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":126,\"end\":134,\"uuid\":\"21b4e245-0bed-44b0-b654-ddf0aaec0611\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":134,\"end\":137}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sensation\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":137,\"end\":146},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"8c2e38c1-2d4a-406f-8c9d-169cc9a9ce9c\",\"uuid\":\"53e0bffa-ddf5-46fc-92bb-96879c7231b1\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":146,\"end\":149}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"03a968d8-a663-433f-a025-8b8d12ad55ad\",\"sort\":17987,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.74\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Eighth, the tathāgatas know that someone whose nature is characterized by craving is engaged in seeking. Through the power of being engaged in seeking there will be the experience of various sufferings. The tathāgatas have eliminated fixation on ‘me’ and ‘mine’ and have no seeking; therefore, this is called nirvāṇa.\",\"label\":\"2.102\",\"sort\":2732,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"885a81f9-dd5d-4ab2-8543-958f3e8c105d\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-353\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":89,\"uuid\":\"03a968d8-a663-433f-a025-8b8d12ad55ad\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":13}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tshol ba\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":13,\"end\":21},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":13,\"end\":21,\"uuid\":\"9a7a94d4-8580-4074-aa59-501ab6ac6f5e\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" in Toh 555. The Degé version of Toh 556 has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":21,\"end\":66}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tshor ba\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":66,\"end\":74},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":66,\"end\":74,\"uuid\":\"5bf390de-6148-43da-b518-0268acb40606\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":74,\"end\":77}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sensation\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":77,\"end\":86},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"8c2e38c1-2d4a-406f-8c9d-169cc9a9ce9c\",\"uuid\":\"f1b8c31a-26de-4e41-90c4-8beb459dcf6d\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":86,\"end\":89}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d4e088c9-af1f-490f-8209-9b6741ae3b37\",\"sort\":17995,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.75\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The bodhisattva Ruciraketu, having heard from the Bhagavat the meaning of the Bhagavat’s not passing into nirvāṇa and his teaching of profound deeds, placed his palms together in homage and bowed down to him. He said, “Having on this day been taught that the Tathāgata, the Great Teacher, does not pass into nirvāṇa and that he creates great benefit for beings through leaving relics in the world, I am joyful, delighted, and amazed in body and mind.”\",\"label\":\"2.120\",\"sort\":2891,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"ca049c77-ce01-48c3-adf6-00117186f94b\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-373\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":75,\"uuid\":\"d4e088c9-af1f-490f-8209-9b6741ae3b37\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to Toh 555, which has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":32}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mdzad pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":32,\"end\":40},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":32,\"end\":40,\"uuid\":\"48fbc5ff-da95-4a5e-8019-70d77052ecda\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Toh 556 has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":40,\"end\":54}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bzod pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":54,\"end\":61},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":54,\"end\":61,\"uuid\":\"67be3ca9-9e3a-406e-b889-767367e200c6\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“patience”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":61,\"end\":75}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b4411db5-49f6-46ec-9d4c-0a83a84fd4dd\",\"sort\":18001,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.76\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Noble one, how should bodhisattvas understand the enjoyment body? All the tathāgatas, in order to enable bodhisattvas to have unimpeded attainment, in order to teach the ultimate truth so that they would know the one taste of saṃsāra and nirvāṇa, in order to dispel the view of belief in a self, and in order to make terrified beings become happy, in accord with truth and with the wisdom of the true nature‍—which are the cause of the infinite qualities of the buddhas‍—and through the power of past prayers, they manifest bodies that are beautified by the thirty-two signs and eighty features of a great being, with auras of light around their bodies. Those are called the enjoyment bodies.\",\"label\":\"3.4\",\"sort\":2965,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"c03d1d6c-0f9c-4500-ab74-333f0d3fcc6c\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-381\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":65,\"uuid\":\"b4411db5-49f6-46ec-9d4c-0a83a84fd4dd\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 555 has “in order that bodhisattvas will attain realization.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":65}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e825baa0-7837-4c99-931e-8ffe61248c13\",\"sort\":18003,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.77\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Also, noble one, there is the analogy of countless, innumerable waters and mirrors, in which appear the different characteristics of empty reflections because of light, even though empty means ‘devoid of characteristics.’\",\"label\":\"3.14\",\"sort\":3034,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"78e8151c-a660-4238-b17b-35d20d8d0eb9\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-392\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":20,\"uuid\":\"e825baa0-7837-4c99-931e-8ffe61248c13\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 555 has “space.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":20}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0a787624-5493-4d06-a6f4-f69076d7f66b\",\"sort\":18005,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.78\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Also, noble one, there is the analogy of countless, innumerable waters and mirrors, in which appear the different characteristics of empty reflections because of light, even though empty means ‘devoid of characteristics.’\",\"label\":\"3.14\",\"sort\":3034,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"78e8151c-a660-4238-b17b-35d20d8d0eb9\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-392\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":20,\"uuid\":\"0a787624-5493-4d06-a6f4-f69076d7f66b\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 555 has “space.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":20}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"986f207e-fd30-43bb-8e34-8d3a1bee456f\",\"sort\":18007,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.79\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Therefore, those two bodies are not nirvāṇa. The Dharma body is also not located within nirvāṇa because the Dharma body and those two bodies are not dual. Therefore, because of these three bodies it is taught that there is nirvāṇa without location.\",\"label\":\"3.19\",\"sort\":3081,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"ce4b129f-8fac-46e0-9331-c3ec4250ff99\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-399\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":132,\"uuid\":\"986f207e-fd30-43bb-8e34-8d3a1bee456f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to Toh 555 and the Yongle, Lithang, Kangxi, and Choné versions. The Degé of Toh 556 has “\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":99}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"nirvāṇa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":99,\"end\":106},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"bebe04fd-2b22-4637-89db-ae1cd69dffe1\",\"uuid\":\"832223f2-ff11-4935-aeb1-066ac0617323\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" because of not dwelling.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":106,\"end\":132}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4d2118f2-5043-4158-beef-b2e191b6c2fe\",\"sort\":18011,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.80\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“What is the enjoyment body and not the emanation body? That is a body that is seen on the bhūmis.\",\"label\":\"3.32\",\"sort\":3216,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"7af3bb42-b020-468f-8e25-bdf2babfc2bb\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-413\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":150,\"uuid\":\"4d2118f2-5043-4158-beef-b2e191b6c2fe\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to Toh 555 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":21}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mdun rol\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":21,\"end\":29},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":21,\"end\":29,\"uuid\":\"087eaba0-2f35-4f89-81a2-edafe08333cc\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (literally “in front of”), while Toh 556 has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":75}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"snga rol\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":75,\"end\":83},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":75,\"end\":83,\"uuid\":\"98d1a67e-cf50-4c19-8bbf-b0870d1802b2\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“before” in the sense of time), which would not fit this context.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":83,\"end\":150}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"90863494-70e4-4769-a55d-5a0aeef81832\",\"sort\":18017,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.81\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Noble one, the Dharma body is the direct perception of the nonduality of phenomena. What is nonduality? In the Dharma body, there are no characteristics, nor any basis for characteristics; there is no existence and there is no nonexistence; there is no singularity and no differences; there is no number and there is nothing to be enumerated; and there is no light and there is no darkness.\",\"label\":\"3.35\",\"sort\":3245,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"0744967d-535d-44ad-be8c-a864d4cbecc9\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-417\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":94,\"uuid\":\"90863494-70e4-4769-a55d-5a0aeef81832\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to Toh 555 and the Chinese 二無所有 (“What is nonduality?”). Toh 556 has only “duality.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":94}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9bd4279c-84a0-4a02-8b4f-5bbc995eb5cc\",\"sort\":18021,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.82\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Noble one, the one who knows and sees the true nature of phenomena has no birth, aging, sickness, and death, and therefore lives for a long time, does not sleep, has no hunger, has no thirst, and has a mind that remains always in samādhi without distraction or conceptual elaboration. Whoever develops an aspiration to have conceptual discourse with the Tathāgata will not see the Tathāgata. Whatever is taught by the tathāgatas is beneficial. Whoever hears this sūtra will never encounter wild beasts, malevolent spirits, or vicious people. There is no end to the ripening of results from listening to this Dharma.\",\"label\":\"3.59\",\"sort\":3519,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"27424f15-7185-4938-9f50-61a861e03a9a\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-442\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":96,\"uuid\":\"9bd4279c-84a0-4a02-8b4f-5bbc995eb5cc\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"From the Tibetan \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":17}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"spros pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":17,\"end\":25},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":17,\"end\":25,\"uuid\":\"6e849529-eeb3-487e-a9f9-21143c1b3b7f\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Toh 555 has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":25,\"end\":39}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"rtso pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":39,\"end\":46},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":39,\"end\":46,\"uuid\":\"81842f64-88a9-4c51-aad4-f1c10ceabdcb\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“dispute with,” “argue with,” or “debate with”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":46,\"end\":96}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"791696d6-5586-4530-8d90-cf8ed4738e97\",\"sort\":18027,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.83\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Noble one, the one who knows and sees the true nature of phenomena has no birth, aging, sickness, and death, and therefore lives for a long time, does not sleep, has no hunger, has no thirst, and has a mind that remains always in samādhi without distraction or conceptual elaboration. Whoever develops an aspiration to have conceptual discourse with the Tathāgata will not see the Tathāgata. Whatever is taught by the tathāgatas is beneficial. Whoever hears this sūtra will never encounter wild beasts, malevolent spirits, or vicious people. There is no end to the ripening of results from listening to this Dharma.\",\"label\":\"3.59\",\"sort\":3519,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"27424f15-7185-4938-9f50-61a861e03a9a\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-442\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":74,\"uuid\":\"791696d6-5586-4530-8d90-cf8ed4738e97\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 555 has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":12}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’dre srin\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":12,\"end\":21},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":12,\"end\":21,\"uuid\":\"2d9a7bb8-ad17-4cc1-9cfa-fea04d50cbac\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The Degé version of Toh 556 has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":21,\"end\":55}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"yi dwags\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":55,\"end\":63},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":55,\"end\":63,\"uuid\":\"7835676a-16fa-4fee-a56f-e8d6dd09a5ea\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":63,\"end\":66}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"preta\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":66,\"end\":71},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"7eb37dc1-ba1f-4f18-ac93-39b3b807c51d\",\"uuid\":\"ed8a18b1-f455-4b8b-9644-7ffbee13b954\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":71,\"end\":74}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"342ff992-946e-44a0-9c56-c51b3f547530\",\"sort\":18035,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.84\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The bodhisattva Ruciraketu then went to sleep and in a dream saw a golden drum that was shining like the disk of the sun. In all directions there were countless, innumerable buddha bhagavats seated upon precious beryl thrones at the foot of precious wish-fulfilling trees, encircled by assemblies of many hundreds of thousands. Looking straight ahead, they were teaching the Dharma.\",\"label\":\"4.1\",\"sort\":3618,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"45f5d34a-816d-4621-950c-89d3c4aa29a8\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-458\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":62,\"uuid\":\"342ff992-946e-44a0-9c56-c51b3f547530\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Sanskrit translates as “he saw a \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":37}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bherī drum\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":37,\"end\":47},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"2df871fe-c65d-44dc-b97a-47039046f128\",\"uuid\":\"a8e6467d-8e60-4b75-9f27-f082cf9065d8\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" made of gold.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":47,\"end\":62}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"12ab849a-7f5a-45fb-ad20-6fae4f555e76\",\"sort\":18039,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.85\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“One night, though I was not Sleepy, I entered a dream. I saw a large, beautiful drum Entirely of golden light.\",\"label\":\"4.5\",\"sort\":3650,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"a6ab6e80-2d56-4a3c-9495-6f3f68cfc82b\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-463\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":174,\"uuid\":\"12ab849a-7f5a-45fb-ad20-6fae4f555e76\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to the Sanskrit \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":26}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"atandrena\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":26,\"end\":35},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":26,\"end\":35,\"uuid\":\"38b33d76-d011-4afc-832e-d6a3a4e9ed5e\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The Tibetan translates this as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":35,\"end\":68}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"g.yel ba med pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":68,\"end\":83},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":68,\"end\":83,\"uuid\":\"4443ce89-ddb5-4879-b1b8-d04b04d4a383\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", which usually means “undistracted,” although that does not appear to be the meaning here.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":83,\"end\":174}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a4b6a311-6693-4d7b-804b-27aab24a0ace\",\"sort\":18045,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.86\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“ ‘Through the sound of the great drum of sublime golden light, May all the suffering of the lower existences, The suffering in Yama’s realm, and the suffering of poverty Cease in the three realms within this trichiliocosm.\",\"label\":\"4.9\",\"sort\":3686,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"a85ed487-7eca-4255-ba41-4c2d225f1dc7\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-468\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":265,\"uuid\":\"a4b6a311-6693-4d7b-804b-27aab24a0ace\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to the Sanskrit \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":26}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"yāmaloka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":26,\"end\":34},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":26,\"end\":34,\"uuid\":\"7d31158c-837e-4c89-86cd-fe83053e3e4e\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", which denotes the realm of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":34,\"end\":67}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"pretas\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":67,\"end\":73},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"7eb37dc1-ba1f-4f18-ac93-39b3b807c51d\",\"uuid\":\"2ca44ede-aae7-4da3-bb9c-4aff8a4c179b\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". This is normally translated into Tibetan as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":73,\"end\":119}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"gshin rje’i ’jig rten\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":119,\"end\":140},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":119,\"end\":140,\"uuid\":\"6718d800-0102-4914-b32c-cae8f8796dbb\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“the world of the lord of death”). Apparently due to a lack of space in the verse, the Tibetan omitted \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":140,\"end\":245}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’jig rten\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":245,\"end\":254},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":245,\"end\":254,\"uuid\":\"034d1b4e-7080-4f7e-9167-1c572a399f10\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“world”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":254,\"end\":265}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"be160f40-f180-44cf-8a37-ed009b948259\",\"sort\":18055,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.87\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“ ‘Through the sound and words of the great drum, May all beings possess the voice of Brahmā And reach the supreme enlightenment of Sublime buddhahood and turn the good Dharma wheel.\",\"label\":\"4.12\",\"sort\":3725,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"dac500dc-23fe-4d08-bd0c-61532a742f40\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-472\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":26,\"uuid\":\"be160f40-f180-44cf-8a37-ed009b948259\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sgra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":4},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":4,\"uuid\":\"296e6814-26f5-49b9-84a9-5b91d0243ac9\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Toh 557 has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":4,\"end\":18}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"dbyangs\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":18,\"end\":25},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":18,\"end\":25,\"uuid\":\"f6cfa91b-158e-49f9-9460-bba00a9128e7\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":25,\"end\":26}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1b64af3e-9491-4038-a22c-1363d009d4f5\",\"sort\":18060,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.88\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“ ‘Those beings who are in the lower realms, Whose skeleton bodies are burning in fire, May they hear the sound of the great drum. May all their suffering cease completely And may they hear the words, “Homage to the buddhas!”\",\"label\":\"4.14\",\"sort\":3748,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"c6a586a5-018d-4f88-bc80-c8d5d0c49805\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-475\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":116,\"uuid\":\"1b64af3e-9491-4038-a22c-1363d009d4f5\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This line is not in the Sanskrit or Toh 557, nor is it in the Yongle, Lithang, Kangxi, or Choné versions of Toh 556.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":116}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9130b6d2-0a6c-4e98-847c-fa543b32ea45\",\"sort\":18062,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.89\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“ ‘May all beings remember hundreds of lifetimes‍— Thousands of millions of lifetimes. May they always remember the Munīndra, And may they hear his vast teaching.\",\"label\":\"4.15\",\"sort\":3759,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"7788c7f2-1907-4d08-8c02-3f57b5eee0a3\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-477\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":38,\"uuid\":\"9130b6d2-0a6c-4e98-847c-fa543b32ea45\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Literally “thousands of ten millions.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":38}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"205254d0-6b32-47ed-9570-ed4dfc4888e8\",\"sort\":18064,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.90\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“ ‘May all beings remember hundreds of lifetimes‍— Thousands of millions of lifetimes. May they always remember the Munīndra, And may they hear his vast teaching.\",\"label\":\"4.15\",\"sort\":3759,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"7788c7f2-1907-4d08-8c02-3f57b5eee0a3\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-477\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":31,\"uuid\":\"205254d0-6b32-47ed-9570-ed4dfc4888e8\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tshe rabs\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":9},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":9,\"uuid\":\"3bb80ac1-0a3e-4e84-881f-2a8ddf52003d\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Toh 557 has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":9,\"end\":23}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"skye ba\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":23,\"end\":30},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":23,\"end\":30,\"uuid\":\"82b041f4-0dc8-48a3-b277-76ade4c3940a\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":30,\"end\":31}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"64ecd06d-42b2-45ca-a52c-5b88930b88c2\",\"sort\":18069,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.91\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“ ‘Whatever bad actions I have done, Such as being arrogant with pride in my wealth, Andr arrogant with pride in my family, My possessions, or my youth;\",\"label\":\"4.24\",\"sort\":3843,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"8ce33422-62d8-40b9-b888-a1d3a024444c\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-488\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":183,\"uuid\":\"64ecd06d-42b2-45ca-a52c-5b88930b88c2\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to the Sanskrit \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":26}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tāruṇya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":26,\"end\":33},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":26,\"end\":33,\"uuid\":\"db9af2b5-9dc2-45f2-8227-2c8c1a9a9644\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", which matches the Yongle, Lithang, Kangxi, and Choné versions of Toh 556, which have \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":33,\"end\":120}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"gzhon pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":120,\"end\":128},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":120,\"end\":128,\"uuid\":\"a20da346-4c9f-421f-af9b-69295cbd71ab\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The Degé version has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":128,\"end\":151}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bzhon pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":151,\"end\":159},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":151,\"end\":159,\"uuid\":\"6149f4ed-c742-48af-a988-201f8dae5bd5\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“steed” or “vehicle”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":159,\"end\":183}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1725d565-022d-46f2-9228-eb6136c3fcfe\",\"sort\":18077,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.92\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“ ‘I make a confession of all Disrespect I have shown To teachers of the Dharma and Disrespect I have shown to the Dharma itself.\",\"label\":\"4.35\",\"sort\":3940,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"92cccf83-5c52-42d1-a67a-f5e735edc930\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-500\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":154,\"uuid\":\"1725d565-022d-46f2-9228-eb6136c3fcfe\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This verse is absent in the Sanskrit and Chinese, but it is present in the Tibetan and quoted as being from this sūtra by Śāntideva in his \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":139}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śikṣāsamuccaya.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":139,\"end\":154},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f861a12f-22e6-44d3-a78e-24aa9f57873f\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"20eae98d-15f3-43b8-bada-cc363f52bf6f\",\"sort\":18081,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.93\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“ ‘May I make offerings to those with the ten strengths In the worlds in the ten directions. I will save from all suffering Those worlds in the ten directions.\",\"label\":\"4.38\",\"sort\":3965,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"3457a427-a3af-4fa5-8400-21867c547100\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-504\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":69,\"uuid\":\"20eae98d-15f3-43b8-bada-cc363f52bf6f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mchod par shog\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":14},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":14,\"uuid\":\"a98fc5ba-44dc-4a9c-83c8-1e3707f6bfcb\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Toh 557 has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":14,\"end\":28}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mchod par bgyi\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":28,\"end\":42},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":28,\"end\":42,\"uuid\":\"2286bdad-434a-409a-ac00-ff36888c0280\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“I will make offerings”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":42,\"end\":69}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"577947e7-b4a5-4956-a7d8-e9f3a028b41b\",\"sort\":18086,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.94\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“ ‘May I make offerings to those with the ten strengths In the worlds in the ten directions. I will save from all suffering Those worlds in the ten directions.\",\"label\":\"4.38\",\"sort\":3965,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"3457a427-a3af-4fa5-8400-21867c547100\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-504\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":43,\"uuid\":\"577947e7-b4a5-4956-a7d8-e9f3a028b41b\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’jig rten\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":9},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":9,\"uuid\":\"1f47ac4f-0601-4888-9d0b-4abca962eff9\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Toh 557 has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":9,\"end\":23}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sems can\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":23,\"end\":31},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":23,\"end\":31,\"uuid\":\"311579e7-4830-41a6-a67c-b7db8eb12be0\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“beings”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":31,\"end\":43}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e3a6ed9d-0ec7-43ac-a684-72826657a78c\",\"sort\":18091,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.95\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“ ‘May I bring all the Countless beings onto the ten bhūmis. When they have reached the ten bhūmis May they all become tathāgatas.\",\"label\":\"4.39\",\"sort\":3978,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"cd0a4b8e-b8d3-474b-98d0-b76b6377581e\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-507\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":58,\"uuid\":\"e3a6ed9d-0ec7-43ac-a684-72826657a78c\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’god par shog\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":13},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":13,\"uuid\":\"d86336bc-318a-44c8-a2b4-2b50909bae7c\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Toh 557 has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":13,\"end\":27}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’god par bgyi\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":27,\"end\":40},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":27,\"end\":40,\"uuid\":\"229bd6a4-307e-4461-a3e4-5e242b06d66f\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“I will bring”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":40,\"end\":58}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ff7577cd-783d-4188-ae04-1d84b6d4f325\",\"sort\":18096,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.96\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“ ‘Until I can free them all From the ocean of suffering, For millions of eons may I be active For the sake of every single being.\",\"label\":\"4.40\",\"sort\":3993,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"9b2948e0-e2f8-4b58-bd37-36c55a168b2a\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-509\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":64,\"uuid\":\"ff7577cd-783d-4188-ae04-1d84b6d4f325\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"spyod par shog\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":14},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":14,\"uuid\":\"9290a930-447c-4dfd-a33a-a160d823d9d4\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Toh 557 has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":14,\"end\":28}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"spyad par bgyi\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":28,\"end\":42},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":28,\"end\":42,\"uuid\":\"03cc5afb-94fc-4dae-8bf7-fceb51aff273\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“I will be active”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":42,\"end\":64}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e0909865-bf25-49ce-9e59-2aa4596af21b\",\"sort\":18101,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.97\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“ ‘May I teach those beings This profound teaching That is called The Sublime Golden Light And purifies one of all karma.\",\"label\":\"4.41\",\"sort\":4004,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"0e3bc61e-6493-4181-ad36-11da91038542\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-511\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":59,\"uuid\":\"e0909865-bf25-49ce-9e59-2aa4596af21b\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ston gyur cig\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":13},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":13,\"uuid\":\"a9a31169-7148-44f6-a407-277eb7790dcf\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Toh 557 has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":13,\"end\":27}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bstan par bgyi\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":27,\"end\":41},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":27,\"end\":41,\"uuid\":\"74671d5d-8aad-4522-ad6a-505d92a28f7d\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“I will teach”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":41,\"end\":59}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"06ad809e-cc0f-422c-ac54-8f5b7b9895c7\",\"sort\":18106,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.98\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“ ‘May I teach those beings This profound teaching That is called The Sublime Golden Light And purifies one of all karma.\",\"label\":\"4.41\",\"sort\":4004,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"0e3bc61e-6493-4181-ad36-11da91038542\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-511\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":105,\"uuid\":\"06ad809e-cc0f-422c-ac54-8f5b7b9895c7\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to the Tibetan \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":25}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"byang byed pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":25,\"end\":38},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":25,\"end\":38,\"uuid\":\"5cbc9628-38e9-434c-92b4-cbf307065c54\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Toh 557 has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":38,\"end\":52}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"byang bgyid pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":52,\"end\":66},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":52,\"end\":66,\"uuid\":\"df13d5d1-0a01-4e91-80f0-a401ea6b6d18\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The Sanskrit has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":66,\"end\":85}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"kṣaya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":85,\"end\":90},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":85,\"end\":90,\"uuid\":\"2290428e-1809-4071-b745-721d555b77df\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“eliminate”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":90,\"end\":105}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c11241b2-0772-4019-a86a-9eff73010f80\",\"sort\":18114,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.99\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“ ‘Those who have committed dreadful evil acts Throughout a thousand eons Will purify themselves of them Through one single confession.\",\"label\":\"4.42\",\"sort\":4018,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"202ee9f5-f49a-4691-be49-916e61b7abd1\",\"workUuid\":\"41800df0-55ae-491a-8a46-1c9f36e1ca14\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-089-013-514\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":73,\"uuid\":\"c11241b2-0772-4019-a86a-9eff73010f80\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to the Tibetan \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":25}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"byang ba\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":25,\"end\":33},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":25,\"end\":33,\"uuid\":\"7fb2444c-d4ea-4e4f-a6c6-0aa3497b0b4a\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The Sanskrit has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":33,\"end\":52}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"vrajantu\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":52,\"end\":60},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":52,\"end\":60,\"uuid\":\"44085211-74e1-41bf-b59b-af8f362accaa\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“destroy”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":60,\"end\":73}}]}]}],\"glossary\":[{\"uuid\":\"805eaba9-4065-4743-b490-a04ef51d4e9d\",\"authority\":\"3509bec3-2cbe-4518-ad2b-6c1e8b684e58\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e“Clear Light.” The highest of the three paradises that correspond to the second \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2564\\\"\u003edhyāna\u003c/span\u003e in the form realm.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Ābhāsvara\",\"tibetan\":\"འོད་གསལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ābhāsvara\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’od gsal\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2bb91118-86fe-4939-981b-b4a6dc4e4de1\",\"authority\":\"4dfd66c2-1368-4410-bd1e-2e4c0cd8f0fc\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA buddha.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003ebsnyengs pa mi mnga’ ba’i grags pa\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Abhayakīrti\",\"tibetan\":\"འཇིགས་མེད་གྲགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"abhayakīrti\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’jigs med grags pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a6149485-1e33-43a4-96ba-655d24a56467\",\"authority\":\"a017cc45-7e3f-460d-8577-a093c7543a2e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eIn the Sarvāstivāda tradition, this is the lowest of the five \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2938\\\"\u003eŚuddhāvāsa\u003c/span\u003e paradises, the highest paradises in the form realm, and is said to be the most common rebirth for the “\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2505\\\"\u003enon-returners\u003c/span\u003e” of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-3215\\\"\u003eŚrāvakayāna\u003c/span\u003e. In this sūtra it is the third highest. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Abṛha, Avṛha\",\"tibetan\":\"མི་ཆེ་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"avṛha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mi che ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2f80c642-ecba-46cd-a8b2-9c0b1ed671e5\",\"authority\":\"c493dc30-b94e-491c-a45d-e8f3807d2768\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eAlbizia lebbeck\u003c/em\u003e. A tall tree that can grow to 100 feet. Other common names include Indian walnut, lebbeck, lebbeck tree, flea tree, frywood, koko, and “woman’s tongue tree.” The bark is used medicinally.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"acacia\",\"tibetan\":\"ཤཱི་རི་ཤཱ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śirīṣa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"shI ri shA\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d756627e-57de-4181-8afd-d6dedb75bc11\",\"authority\":\"9d8db80f-f44c-432a-bfe6-abaecfaaf457\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA spiritual teacher, meaning one who knows the conduct or practice (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eācāra\u003c/em\u003e) to be performed. It can also be a title for a scholar, though that is not the context in this sūtra. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"ācārya\",\"tibetan\":\"སློབ་དཔོན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ācārya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"slob dpon\"}},{\"uuid\":\"789befb5-6df7-4ed5-8102-20f2e5e3db83\",\"authority\":\"38d24d16-01af-41d2-bbf2-2326cde56918\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThese palaces served as both vehicles and residences for deities.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"aerial palace\",\"tibetan\":\"གཞལ་མེད་ཁང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vimāna\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gzhal med khang\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f8b603ad-07d1-4b0b-8c9a-e94d5caa865e\",\"authority\":\"c87671dd-3ffd-410d-a94d-fca04ee8ccc2\",\"definition\":\"$32\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"affliction, kleśa\",\"tibetan\":\"ཉོན་མོངས།, ཉོན་མོངས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kleśa, kleśa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nyon mongs, nyon mongs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"45a48b06-14a4-4a11-beac-df1118f20976\",\"authority\":\"c87671dd-3ffd-410d-a94d-fca04ee8ccc2\",\"definition\":\"$33\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"affliction, kleśa\",\"tibetan\":\"ཉོན་མོངས།, ཉོན་མོངས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kleśa, kleśa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nyon mongs, nyon mongs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"58e74b39-bca4-4800-a114-059795feb2fe\",\"authority\":\"23274b58-cb87-46d4-8c53-7d180068255a\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eAmyris agallocha\u003c/em\u003e. Also called agallochum and aloeswood. This is a resinous heartwood that has been infected by the fungus \u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003ePhialophora parasitica\u003c/em\u003e. In India, agarwood is primarily derived from the fifteen Aquilaria (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eAquilaria malaccensis\u003c/em\u003e) and nine \u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eGyrinops\u003c/em\u003e species of lign-aloe trees. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"agarwood\",\"tibetan\":\"ཨ་ག་རུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"agaru\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"a ga ru\"}},{\"uuid\":\"547d441f-ee55-43d1-bf8d-712745f3a103\",\"authority\":\"f5713afd-744f-4ee1-b0d7-5cfeccde56fd\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA god who is the king of lightning in the eastern direction.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Āgata\",\"tibetan\":\"འོང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"āgata\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’ong ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"569c7928-b769-4d02-abf6-9f93a71c3804\",\"authority\":\"e00c06d4-270e-464e-a57b-1a020464ad34\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe eighth and highest level of the Realm of Form (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003erūpadhātu\u003c/em\u003e), the last of the five pure abodes (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eśuddhāvāsa\u003c/em\u003e); it is only accessible as the result of specific states of \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003edhyāna\u003c/em\u003e. According to some texts this is where non-returners (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eanāgāmin\u003c/em\u003e) dwell in their last lives. In other texts it is the realm of the enjoyment body (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003esaṃbhoga­kāya\u003c/em\u003e) and is a buddhafield associated with the Buddha Vairocana; it is accessible only to bodhisattvas on the tenth level.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Akaniṣṭha\",\"tibetan\":\"འོག་མིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"akaniṣṭha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’og min\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b78f2e81-fa8d-4312-a7a1-86949f89ddfd\",\"authority\":\"2e7ae358-eb53-4f85-a660-9f667a73c36e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bodhisattva.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Ākāśagarbha\",\"tibetan\":\"ནམ་མཁའི་སྙིང་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ākāśagarbha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nam mkha’i snying po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"25f9b88e-7fb3-4d68-a52b-49e7a1e4da3c\",\"authority\":\"413399d1-6f0f-4469-b08b-fd5a3bc6ca1a\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2496\\\"\u003eLicchavī\u003c/span\u003e youth.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Ākāśaghoṣa\",\"tibetan\":\"ནམ་མཁའ་སྒྲོགས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ākāśaghoṣa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nam mkha’ sgrogs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ba5e7fb9-e30f-44bf-b7a9-76971f797abf\",\"authority\":\"f63d1a5d-76a0-46b8-b5e0-d4a895db870e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2496\\\"\u003eLicchavī\u003c/span\u003e youth.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003enam mkha’ skyabs\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Ākāśapāla\",\"tibetan\":\"ནམ་མཁའ་སྐྱོང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ākāśapāla\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nam mkha’ skyong\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5eaaf65c-6293-45b2-aca5-96506aa7e494\",\"authority\":\"c26470e4-f9a9-4cb1-8ab3-c6b24796b6d6\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bodhisattva.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003ebsam pa nam mkha’ ci bzhin\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Ākāśavat\",\"tibetan\":\"ནམ་མཁའ་བཞིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ākāśavat\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nam mkha’ bzhin\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b38c05f5-9f1a-4b06-8cc2-d5ff8067e463\",\"authority\":\"342a107e-23b0-4e95-98b8-eac1821223f5\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2471\\\"\u003edeva\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003enam mkha’i blo gros rnam par dag pa\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Ākāśa­viśuddha­prajña\",\"tibetan\":\"ནམ་མཁའ་རྣམ་དག་ཤེས་རབ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ākāśa­viśuddha­prajña\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nam mkha’ rnam dag shes rab\"}},{\"uuid\":\"497e05ef-9c9d-4cee-bb86-157997d6046f\",\"authority\":\"7b13af11-a4ff-4496-9927-272636112225\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bodhisattva.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003eseng ge’i mtshan thogs pa med pa’i ’od zer ’bar ba\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Akṣayamati\",\"tibetan\":\"བློ་གྲོས་མི་ཟད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"akṣayamati\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"blo gros mi zad\"}},{\"uuid\":\"15b53e78-cf61-4aec-86bd-5380bbcb3129\",\"authority\":\"cad43a0c-a53f-4f2e-8341-2a76e07dcb4a\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eLit. “Not Disturbed” or “Immovable One.” The buddha in the eastern realm of Abhirati. A well-known buddha in Mahāyāna, regarded in the higher tantras as the head of one of the five buddha families, the vajra family in the east.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Akṣobhya\",\"tibetan\":\"མི་འཁྲུགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"akṣobhya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mi ’khrugs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"4d5fe580-1bb8-49ce-86e9-39f960262383\",\"authority\":\"9cb5c538-16c1-484b-a9cf-49066347ee14\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe kingdom of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2555\\\"\u003eyakṣas\u003c/span\u003e located on Mount \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2940\\\"\u003eSumeru\u003c/span\u003e and ruled over by Kubera, also known as \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2847\\\"\u003eVaiśravaṇa\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003enor ldan\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Alakāvati\",\"tibetan\":\"ལྕང་ལོ་ཅན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"alakāvati\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lcang lo can\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a205f712-edf6-4633-a433-08e3bab530ce\",\"authority\":\"42e48cc9-6522-4cb3-9b3e-9a808c84d812\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2503\\\"\u003enāga\u003c/span\u003e king.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003edba’ rlabs chung ngu\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Alpormika\",\"tibetan\":\"དབའ་རླབས་ཆུང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"alpormika\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dba’ rlabs chung\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a91c8877-6a20-4d23-9475-e5bc915e2bc9\",\"authority\":\"510ec4e4-97ae-4928-8fb5-5bd950480604\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bodhisattva.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Always Concentrated\",\"tibetan\":\"རྟག་ཏུ་ཏིང་ངེ་འཛིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rtag tu ting nge ’dzin\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b4043124-016c-46e7-b162-8a823ecbce68\",\"authority\":\"52456ea4-51a5-46fa-8f83-56abbc67c5c4\",\"definition\":\"$34\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Amitābha\",\"tibetan\":\"འོད་དཔག་མེད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"amitābha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’od dpag med\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0e4a8c27-a163-43ca-a541-e5906937a273\",\"authority\":\"d309704a-4473-4b44-b15e-2bfa45fe2283\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2555\\\"\u003eyakṣa\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Amra\",\"tibetan\":\"ཨ་མྲ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"amra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"a mra\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ef4011fb-3baf-438a-9660-959e688818ad\",\"authority\":\"2add846b-7852-4d0b-83d2-53fddda0874a\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2555\\\"\u003eyakṣa\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003ea mra thogs pa\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Amradhara\",\"tibetan\":\"ཨ་མྲ་འཆང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"amradhara\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"a mra ’chang\"}},{\"uuid\":\"e0d96fcc-e6d7-49bb-ad3e-fc50b223d78e\",\"authority\":\"27fb6065-f0a2-4b6f-8c5b-ad8b1a123bd2\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe nectar of immortality possessed by the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2471\\\"\u003edevas\u003c/span\u003e, it is used as a metaphor for the teaching that brings liberation.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"amṛta\",\"tibetan\":\"བདུད་རྩི།\",\"sanskrit\":\"amṛta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bdud rtsi\"}},{\"uuid\":\"6c853461-7d86-47a4-9476-d994ab38a8d8\",\"authority\":\"c844f23a-aa98-4f2a-9328-640c26842784\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA buddha.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003esnang ba’i rgyal po\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Aṃśurāja\",\"tibetan\":\"འོད་སྣང་རྒྱལ་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"aṃśurāja\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’od snang rgyal po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"759b69fd-3945-476f-9464-efc71731b2c5\",\"authority\":\"a9a90c0c-0173-431f-b38a-2cb97de433e4\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e“Cloudless.” In the Sarvāstivāda tradition, the lowest of the three paradises that correspond to the fourth \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2564\\\"\u003edhyāna\u003c/span\u003e in the form realm. Translated in other texts as \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003esprin dang bral ba\u003c/em\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Anabhraka\",\"tibetan\":\"སྤྲིན་མེད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"anabhraka\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sprin med\"}},{\"uuid\":\"25d30c62-21d4-45f4-aa28-a30a59ba2248\",\"authority\":\"2c02baf4-0ece-4579-8f66-c49bcc21f21f\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA major śrāvaka disciple and personal attendant of the Buddha Śākyamuni during the last twenty-five years of his life. He was a cousin of the Buddha (according to the \u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eMahāvastu\u003c/cite\u003e, he was a son of Śuklodana, one of the brothers of King Śuddhodana, which means he was a brother of Devadatta; other sources say he was a son of Amṛtodana, another brother of King Śuddhodana, which means he would have been a brother of Aniruddha).\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eĀnanda, having always been in the Buddha’s presence, is said to have memorized all the teachings he heard and is celebrated for having recited all the Buddha’s teachings by memory at the first council of the Buddhist saṅgha, thus preserving the teachings after the Buddha’s parinirvāṇa. The phrase “Thus did I hear at one time,” found at the beginning of the sūtras, usually stands for his recitation of the teachings. He became a patriarch after the passing of Mahākāśyapa.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Ānanda\",\"tibetan\":\"ཀུན་དགའ་བོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ānanda\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"kun dga’ bo\"}},{\"uuid\":\"cb7577e3-d76f-4598-93c0-76a3991799cb\",\"authority\":\"a6ab2bdd-635c-4ab6-b350-4220754def50\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bodhisattva.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Anāvaraṇa­dharma­cakra­varta\",\"tibetan\":\"ཐོགས་པ་མེད་པར་ཆོས་ཀྱི་འཁོར་ལོ་བསྐོར་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"anāvaraṇa­dharma­cakra­varta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"thogs pa med par chos kyi ’khor lo bskor ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"156530bf-0e66-4b03-807b-ea48f2f06480\",\"authority\":\"9df57ea3-24de-49af-aac2-2258f71120e6\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eA nāga king whose domain is Lake Anavatapta. According to Buddhist cosmology, this lake is located near Mount Sumeru and is the source of the four great rivers of Jambudvīpa. It is often identified with Lake Manasarovar at the foot of Mount Kailash in Tibet.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Anavatapta\",\"tibetan\":\"མ་དྲོས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"anavatapta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ma dros pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a84fe0e5-56a1-484f-829f-6fbeb6575eca\",\"authority\":\"7f5c1186-ed32-4b9c-b588-467f1b504255\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bodhisattva.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Anikṣiptadhura\",\"tibetan\":\"མི་གཏོང་བརྩོན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"anikṣiptadhura\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mi gtong brtson pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"81d7585a-71d0-4c49-9e96-d6c53d49c14d\",\"authority\":\"949c27d4-245d-4db7-bf5d-b6b72d4ccccd\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bodhisattva.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003esmon lam chen po yongs su mi gcod pa\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Anikṣipta­mahā­praṇidhāna\",\"tibetan\":\"སྨོན་ལམ་ཆེན་པོ་མི་གཏོང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"anikṣipta­mahā­praṇidhāna\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"smon lam chen po mi gtong ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"80eb280d-22b5-48d5-85d5-94f83d5dddf5\",\"authority\":\"7221c3d4-af4a-4307-ac69-3032f3260048\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2555\\\"\u003eyakṣa\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003ezas kyi ril ming\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Annaharaṇa\",\"tibetan\":\"ཟས་འཕྲོག\",\"sanskrit\":\"annaharaṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"zas ’phrog\"}},{\"uuid\":\"52a06769-8761-4294-8f5f-896f2ffa5871\",\"authority\":\"2b52f5bf-301a-4324-a183-5ca961bd8b1b\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e“Immeasurable Light.” The second highest of the three paradises that correspond to the second \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2564\\\"\u003edhyāna\u003c/span\u003e in the form realm. Translated in other texts as \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003etshad med snang ba\u003c/em\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Apramāṇābha\",\"tibetan\":\"ཚད་མེད་འོད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"apramāṇābha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tshad med ’od\"}},{\"uuid\":\"26379e1f-3aa1-4b5e-b164-30105102abdf\",\"authority\":\"147f742b-de9f-4851-ae1b-10fcfb730119\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e“Immeasurable Goodness.” The second highest of the three paradises that correspond to the third \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2564\\\"\u003edhyāna\u003c/span\u003e in the form realm. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Apramāṇaśubha\",\"tibetan\":\"ཚད་མེད་དགེ\",\"sanskrit\":\"apramāṇaśubha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tshad med dge\"}},{\"uuid\":\"9a49890c-94f8-4129-9740-fac8887e030b\",\"authority\":\"d95e6f28-87de-429e-b185-d12873ac760c\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAccording to Buddhist tradition, one who is worthy of worship (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003epūjām arhati\u003c/em\u003e), or one who has conquered the enemies, the mental afflictions (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003ekleśa-ari-hata-vat\u003c/em\u003e), and reached liberation from the cycle of rebirth and suffering. It is the fourth and highest of the four fruits attainable by śrāvakas. Also used as an epithet of the Buddha.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"arhat\",\"tibetan\":\"དགྲ་བཅོམ་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"arhat\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dgra bcom pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"8bbd9642-1f8b-40bd-89dc-31b2f53eacfd\",\"authority\":\"47372486-8059-40c0-846e-d19b16eaf837\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eCareva arborea\u003c/em\u003e. Also known as mugwort and wormwood.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Degé 557: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003esha myang\u003c/em\u003e. Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003esha ma ka\u003c/em\u003e. Bagchi edition: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eśyābhyaka\u003c/em\u003e.)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"artemisia\",\"tibetan\":\"ཤ་མྱ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śāmyaka\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sha mya\"}},{\"uuid\":\"40dce0ff-b273-4107-acb0-3cc7cddc52c8\",\"authority\":\"207f5f53-fc1e-434b-8151-bc7b63581fd5\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe Sanskrit \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eārya\u003c/em\u003e has the general meaning of a noble person, one of a higher class or caste. In Buddhist literature, depending on the context, it often means specifically one who has gained the realization of the path and is superior for that reason. In particular, it applies to stream enterers, once-returners, non-returners, and worthy ones (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003earhats\u003c/em\u003e) and is also used as an epithet of bodhisattvas. In the five-path system, it refers to someone who has achieved at least the path of seeing (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003edarśanamārga\u003c/em\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"ārya\",\"tibetan\":\"འཕགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ārya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’phags pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"60f077ca-e1d4-476c-9ef2-79952daef92b\",\"authority\":\"6d74dfd0-53d8-493e-911f-04831c0dd16b\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e“Beings without Perception.” A heavenly realm listed in this text between the twelfth heaven of the form realm, \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2913\\\"\u003eBṛhatphala\u003c/span\u003e, and the five Pure Abodes of the form realm, known collectively as \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2938\\\"\u003eŚuddhāvāsa\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Asaṃjñasattva\",\"tibetan\":\"སེམས་ཅན་འདུ་ཤེས་མེད་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"asaṃjñasattva\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sems can ’du shes med pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"136b1de2-9916-46f4-9d24-101eca1d61f3\",\"authority\":\"71848c67-27ef-43a4-a60c-8b00ca05db1c\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe name of a certain kind of kalpa, literally meaning “incalculable.” The number of years in this kalpa differs in various sūtras that give a number. Also, twenty intermediate kalpas are said to be one \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003easaṃkhyeya\u003c/em\u003e (incalculable) kalpa, and four incalculable kalpas are one great kalpa. In that case, those four incalculable kalpas represent the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2480\\\"\u003eeons\u003c/span\u003e of the creation, presence, destruction, and absence of a world. Buddhas are often described as appearing in a second incalculable kalpa.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"asaṃkhyeya eon\",\"tibetan\":\"བསྐལ་པ་གྲངས་མེད་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"asaṃkhyeyakalpa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bskal pa grangs med pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d1696558-a54d-4453-a65b-c8dc56343522\",\"authority\":\"d446af6c-b807-4c2d-ae67-641d4f0de5f9\",\"definition\":\"$35\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"aspects of enlightenment, bodhipakṣadharma\",\"tibetan\":\"བྱང་ཆུབ་ཀྱི་ཕྱོགས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bodhipakṣa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"byang chub kyi phyogs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"cd64ca4d-45fd-4ab3-9701-125845e35df4\",\"authority\":\"7a2edc31-86b9-40e6-9158-5eb126810dd2\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bodhisattva.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eDharma­cakra­pravarta­cittotpada\u003c/em\u003e; \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003echos kyi ’khor lo yongs su bskor bar sems bskyed\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Aspiring to Always Turn the Dharma Wheel\",\"tibetan\":\"རྟག་པར་ཆོས་ཀྱི་འཁོར་ལོ་བསྐོར་བར་སེམས་བསྐྱེད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"satata­dharma­cakra­pravarta­cittotpada\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rtag par chos kyi ’khor lo bskor bar sems bskyed\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b0f25636-a93c-40c2-824c-aeb9d1aa263a\",\"authority\":\"32837dd6-edd0-49d4-b729-9e3e243c4fa1\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA type of nonhuman being whose precise status is subject to different views, but is included as one of the six classes of beings in the sixfold classification of realms of rebirth. In the Buddhist context, asuras are powerful beings said to be dominated by envy, ambition, and hostility. They are also known in the pre-Buddhist and pre-Vedic mythologies of India and Iran, and feature prominently in Vedic and post-Vedic Brahmanical mythology, as well as in the Buddhist tradition. In these traditions, asuras are often described as being engaged in interminable conflict with the devas (gods).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"asura\",\"tibetan\":\"ལྷ་མ་ཡིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"asura\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lha ma yin\"}},{\"uuid\":\"e402ebc0-1717-4674-83d1-8e2ba3924cd3\",\"authority\":\"ebc5372a-3bb2-4b4c-82ea-645a69b0703e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne of the five companions with whom Siddhārtha Gautama practiced asceticism near the Nairañjanā River and who later heard the Buddha first teach the four noble truths at the Deer Park in Sarnath. He was renowned for his pure conduct and holy demeanor, so the Buddha sent him to attract \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2807\\\"\u003eŚāriputra\u003c/span\u003e and \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2694\\\"\u003eMaudgalyāyana\u003c/span\u003e to the order.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Aśvajit\",\"tibetan\":\"རྟ་ཐུལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"aśvajit\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rta thul\"}},{\"uuid\":\"52a2dde9-c02f-46be-acb9-16ac92edb4f5\",\"authority\":\"d70bf5fd-41a7-4582-bc7b-b3abe624cb99\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThis is the fourth highest of the five \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2938\\\"\u003eŚuddhāvāsa\u003c/span\u003e paradises, the highest paradises in the form realm. In this sūtra it is the second highest. Here translated as meaning “Not Pained.” In other texts translated as \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003ema dros pa\u003c/em\u003e (“Not Warm”). \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Atapa, Atapas\",\"tibetan\":\"མི་གདུང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"atapa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mi gdung ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b17621cd-27ac-4814-80ad-3051f765f3a6\",\"authority\":\"883fab0d-5aaa-441f-9d46-7e59d454552a\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2555\\\"\u003eyakṣa\u003c/span\u003e king.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Aṭavika\",\"tibetan\":\"འབྲོག་གནས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"aṭavika\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’brog gnas\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ad802bad-24c7-4602-97a2-38342cedf1d0\",\"authority\":\"d635d8f5-134a-49c9-8655-03325aed625a\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA lake in a wilderness.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 557: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003edgon pa na yod pa\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Aṭavīsaṃbhavā\",\"tibetan\":\"འབྲོག་ཁོང་ཁོང་ན་ཡོད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"aṭavīsaṃbhavā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’brog khong khong na yod\"}},{\"uuid\":\"81980d17-eb3d-491a-8297-35881384bb0d\",\"authority\":\"0ecba1e9-f6bc-4e30-823b-34a3dc139974\",\"definition\":\"$36\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Avalokiteśvara\",\"tibetan\":\"ཀུན་ཏུ་སྤྱན་རས་གཟིགས་དབང་ཕྱུག\",\"sanskrit\":\"avalokiteśvara\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"kun tu spyan ras gzigs dbang phyug\"}},{\"uuid\":\"930f3b45-48ca-4dec-8331-b2328ed8afcf\",\"authority\":\"e52f9ccd-a654-4ff0-b1bc-054ec34639ca\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA buddha.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003ertog pa ’jigs med dbang phyug\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Avalokiteśvarābhaya\",\"tibetan\":\"སྤྱན་རས་གཟིགས་དབང་མི་འཇིགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"avalokiteśvarābhaya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"spyan ras gzigs dbang mi ’jigs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"de6e8d0d-5083-4cbe-9fd1-01273dfb56e3\",\"authority\":\"ede82432-9c8a-46a3-a71c-18020da917ec\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe classical system of Indian medicine.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003eshes pa\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Āyurveda\",\"tibetan\":\"ཚེའི་རིག་བྱེད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"āyurveda\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tshe’i rig byed\"}},{\"uuid\":\"517c0c22-1b23-4872-84b1-a79c9a77450a\",\"authority\":\"e160e4b5-7694-4ac6-9a8d-a698f1b409e3\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe five actions that lead to going instantly to hell upon death: killing one’s father; killing one’s mother; killing an \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2437\\\"\u003earhat\u003c/span\u003e; splitting the sangha; and wounding a buddha so that he bleeds.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"bad karma with immediate result, five actions with immediate result upon death\",\"tibetan\":\"མཚམས་མེད་པ་ལྔ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"pañcānantarya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mtshams med pa lnga\"}},{\"uuid\":\"92e4b294-545f-4787-9f48-96c5abd3b932\",\"authority\":\"e8d04ec0-77da-4598-b25e-a2b9f90a846f\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA king in the distant past.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Balendraketu\",\"tibetan\":\"སྟོབས་ཀྱི་དབང་པོའི་ཏོག\",\"sanskrit\":\"balendraketu\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"stobs kyi dbang po’i tog\"}},{\"uuid\":\"424d07fe-e805-4e2a-96bd-a925f6e5195d\",\"authority\":\"2618b8e7-6641-4405-956f-eab21c68db0b\",\"definition\":\"$37\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Bali\",\"tibetan\":\"སྟོབས་ཆེན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bali\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"stobs chen\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b35e3086-7f46-4af9-9250-b231fe0e92c5\",\"authority\":\"db4bf23a-9763-4819-bd3b-4175c6b68867\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eCommiphora wighti\u003c/em\u003e, or \u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eCommiphora mukul\u003c/em\u003e. The resin, also known as guggul gum, is obtained from the bark of the tree. When burned, the smoke is said to drive away evil spirits\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Nobel edition: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eguggulu\u003c/em\u003e. Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003egu gul\u003c/em\u003e.)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"bdellium\",\"tibetan\":\"གུ་གུལ་ར་ས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"guggulurasa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gu gul ra sa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"11a27248-f816-4d5c-b4b3-5337a66680be\",\"authority\":\"2e135f90-296b-48e1-8e27-aa8acfc420d6\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2471\\\"\u003edeva\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003emthong na dga’ ba\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Beautiful to See\",\"tibetan\":\"དགའ་བ་མཐོང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dga’ ba mthong ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"e62b8fa4-3316-40ef-bfbb-4e0bc985ce76\",\"authority\":\"fa9bbbcf-ac8b-4aa0-b025-156c27bf155f\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eUsed in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2445\\\"\u003eĀyurveda\u003c/span\u003e for both external and oral application in treating worm infestation, pruritus (itching), psychiatric disorders, low digestion strength, and more.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Bagchi: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003esamocaka\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"bezoar, cow bezoar\",\"tibetan\":\"གི་ཝང་།, གིའུ་ཝང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"gorocanā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gi wang, gi’u wang\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a923b9d8-34d7-4119-83ae-131b7f92aa46\",\"authority\":\"9f2be30a-6837-4cda-a22c-035a3e3643a8\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne of Siddhārtha’s five ascetic companions, who abandoned him when he renounced asceticism. When those five later became the Buddha’s first disciples, Bhadrika was the second of them to convert.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Bhadrika\",\"tibetan\":\"བཟང་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bhadrika\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bzang po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7317e301-9d9a-41ce-9424-338eceefcc6b\",\"authority\":\"2b190410-5ef2-4a3a-a428-89d999d14336\",\"definition\":\"$38\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Bhagavat\",\"tibetan\":\"བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bhagavat\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bcom ldan ’das\"}},{\"uuid\":\"997183d3-1ea8-4e8b-bef3-c1c37f789035\",\"authority\":\"c50be940-0bff-4971-9e11-268697045713\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bodhisattva.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003esman gtong\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Bhaiṣajyadatta\",\"tibetan\":\"སྨན་སྦྱིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bhaiṣajyadatta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sman sbyin\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ee90db88-34b8-483b-bd56-b0758dbe6bc2\",\"authority\":\"02efcf76-ca7a-4352-99da-c4d1b79a289c\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bodhisattva.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003esman gyi rgyal po\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Bhaiṣajyarāja\",\"tibetan\":\"སྨན་པའི་རྒྱལ་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bhaiṣajyarāja\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sman pa’i rgyal po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2df871fe-c65d-44dc-b97a-47039046f128\",\"authority\":\"887a29fe-4d05-4d32-b1b1-49efd27e45bd\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAs specified in the Sanskrit, a conical or bowl-shaped kettledrum, with an upper surface that is beaten with sticks. The Tibetan and Chinese are not specific about the kind of drum it is.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"bherī drum\",\"tibetan\":\"རྔ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bherī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rnga\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5365d0e6-91d5-4ce8-8796-a14339d6e504\",\"authority\":\"3f54b15a-ac9f-4ecb-82cf-bce1c48f4a11\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe term \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003ebhikṣu\u003c/em\u003e, often translated as “monk,” refers to the highest among the eight types of prātimokṣa vows that make one part of the Buddhist assembly. The Sanskrit term literally means “beggar” or “mendicant,” referring to the fact that Buddhist monks and nuns‍—like other ascetics of the time‍—subsisted on alms (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003ebhikṣā\u003c/em\u003e) begged from the laity. \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eIn the Tibetan tradition, which follows the Mūlasarvāstivāda Vinaya, a monk follows 253 rules as part of his moral discipline. A nun (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003ebhikṣuṇī\u003c/em\u003e; \u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003edge slong ma\u003c/em\u003e) follows 364 rules. A novice monk (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eśrāmaṇera\u003c/em\u003e; \u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003edge tshul\u003c/em\u003e) or nun (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eśrāmaṇerikā\u003c/em\u003e; \u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003edge tshul ma\u003c/em\u003e) follows thirty-six rules of moral discipline (although in other vinaya traditions novices typically follow only ten).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"bhikṣu\",\"tibetan\":\"དགེ་སློང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bhikṣu\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dge slong\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5eb1d3c8-b031-4dfa-99a2-a469f6a9f835\",\"authority\":\"53a05132-fe6f-436a-83e1-f06adbcb30ca\",\"definition\":\"$39\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"bhikṣuṇī\",\"tibetan\":\"དགེ་སློང་མ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bhikṣuṇī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dge slong ma\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b699c0ca-caa4-48ce-abf0-acb0ff7f4361\",\"authority\":\"f68247f2-bbfd-42a9-ab23-c2572a2d7221\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2555\\\"\u003eyakṣa\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003ekhro gnyer\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Bhṛkuṭi\",\"tibetan\":\"ཁྲོ་གཉེར་ཅན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bhṛkuṭi\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"khro gnyer can\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ff1e1864-2411-4b97-a56d-bfd1b395dc48\",\"authority\":\"c52879aa-5872-4ca4-935a-dfb2ee0305c7\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eLiterally the “grounds” in which qualities grow, and also meaning “levels.” Here it refers specifically to levels of enlightenment, especially the ten levels of the bodhisattvas.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"bhūmi\",\"tibetan\":\"ས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bhūmi\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c3880ffb-0adb-41fa-82e1-09cee7cf6931\",\"authority\":\"0832ddc3-0c90-4dd0-a39e-b1286a11a022\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2555\\\"\u003eyakṣa\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003esa kun g.yo ba\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Bhūmikampa\",\"tibetan\":\"ས་གཡོ་བྱེད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bhūmikampa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sa g.yo byed\"}},{\"uuid\":\"1eef92ba-9f79-4834-8bda-da998d34f1f6\",\"authority\":\"c03438fc-3749-41a2-bf82-c0e2031eac9e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eMomordica monadelpha\u003c/em\u003e. A perennial climbing plant, the fruit of which is a bright red gourd. Because of its color it is frequently used in poetry as a simile for lips. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"bimba\",\"tibetan\":\"བིམ་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bimba, bimbā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bim pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7b3f5ea0-4ec8-45e4-9122-240166249a66\",\"authority\":\"5596745f-b209-4bae-bf2c-38133abe1743\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eParmelia perlata\u003c/em\u003e. A lichen used as a spice and in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2445\\\"\u003eĀyurveda\u003c/span\u003e for the treatment of skin diseases, cough, asthma, kidney stones, painful urination, and localized swelling. Commonly called \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eśaileya\u003c/em\u003e in Sanskrit.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eEmmerick, based on the Nobel edition, separates the compound into two: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003epatra\u003c/em\u003e (leaf) and \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eśaileya\u003c/em\u003e. Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003espra ba\u003c/em\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"black stone flower\",\"tibetan\":\"རྡོ་དྲེག་ལོ་མ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"patraśaileya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rdo dreg lo ma\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2a349391-f527-4ccd-b584-fcc7ec612dc6\",\"authority\":\"5194ec43-131c-4add-9bdd-11a73347b3fb\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eMore commonly known as the Indian roller (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eCoracias benghalensis\u003c/em\u003e). \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"blue jaybird\",\"tibetan\":\"ཙ་ཤ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"cāṣa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tsa sha\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2b1b14a2-798d-412c-91f2-0acb6ed6485b\",\"authority\":\"b0b39e62-0912-43af-a32e-dd7cd05a2b7b\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe place where the Buddha Śākyamuni achieved awakening and where every buddha will manifest the attainment of buddhahood. In our world this is understood to be located under the Bodhi tree, the Vajrāsana, in present-day Bodhgaya, India. It can also refer to the state of awakening itself.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Bodhimaṇḍa\",\"tibetan\":\"བྱང་ཆུབ་ཀྱི་སྙིང་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bodhimaṇḍa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"byang chub kyi snying po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"9e6bac79-d0f2-420a-a6d3-d452e261ba6b\",\"authority\":\"bd78861b-2633-413b-8ca4-b595b3b46f17\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA goddess. In Toh 555 called “goddess of the Bodhi tree.”\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Bodhisattvasamuccayā\",\"tibetan\":\"བྱང་ཆུབ་ཡང་དག་པར་བསྡུས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"Bodhi­sattva­samuccayā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"byang chub yang dag par bsdus pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ef9c1ac5-e9a9-4aad-886d-0b0ddf8d8dde\",\"authority\":\"db36127a-581c-4efe-9ebf-172706c136f8\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eIn addition to being the name of the great deity, “\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2896\\\"\u003eBrahmā\u003c/span\u003e” (sometimes “\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-3270\\\"\u003eMahābrahmā\u003c/span\u003e”) can mean all the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2471\\\"\u003edevas\u003c/span\u003e that live in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2896\\\"\u003eBrahmā\u003c/span\u003e’s paradise. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Brahmā, Brahmā devas\",\"tibetan\":\"ཚངས་པ།, ཚངས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"brahmā, brahmā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tshangs pa, tshangs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0ea2394f-1cfc-4258-a798-9a6eb4c60b62\",\"authority\":\"db36127a-581c-4efe-9ebf-172706c136f8\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eA high-ranking deity presiding over a divine world; he is also considered to be the lord of the Sahā world (our universe). Though not considered a creator god in Buddhism, Brahmā occupies an important place as one of two gods (the other being Indra/Śakra) said to have first exhorted the Buddha Śākyamuni to teach the Dharma. The particular heavens found in the form realm over which Brahmā rules are often some of the most sought-after realms of higher rebirth in Buddhist literature. Since there are many universes or world systems, there are also multiple Brahmās presiding over them. His most frequent epithets are “Lord of the Sahā World” (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003esahāṃpati\u003c/em\u003e) and Great Brahmā (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003emahābrahman\u003c/em\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Brahmā, Brahmā devas\",\"tibetan\":\"ཚངས་པ།, ཚངས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"brahmā, brahmā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tshangs pa, tshangs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"39c0206c-a427-41a4-ba6d-22b392e81be5\",\"authority\":\"55a600c9-c2f9-48a7-9b19-39a5ff3282f4\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e“\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2896\\\"\u003eBrahmā\u003c/span\u003e’s Multitude.” The lowest of the three paradises that form the paradises of the first \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2564\\\"\u003edhyāna\u003c/span\u003e in the form realm. \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003etshangs ris\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Brahmakāyika\",\"tibetan\":\"ཚངས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"brahmakāyika\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tshangs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"85498276-32f9-4681-8f01-aff944c61f89\",\"authority\":\"68c5b143-54b4-4c0d-b64d-a9b30967e69d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e“\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2896\\\"\u003eBrahmā\u003c/span\u003e’s entourage.” In this sūtra the highest of the three paradises that correspond to the first \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2564\\\"\u003edhyāna\u003c/span\u003e in the form realm. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Brahma­pariṣadya\",\"tibetan\":\"ཚངས་པའི་རྒྱལ་འཁོར།\",\"sanskrit\":\"brahma­pariṣadya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tshangs pa’i rgyal ’khor\"}},{\"uuid\":\"1d7673b8-0bc8-4a28-95cd-7a8af20615f1\",\"authority\":\"15013434-829b-4924-b806-195c6192a240\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e“\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2896\\\"\u003eBrahmā\u003c/span\u003e’s Principals.” In the generally established cosmology, the second highest of the three paradises that correspond to the first \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2564\\\"\u003edhyāna\u003c/span\u003e in the form realm. Here it is the third highest with the addition of another \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2896\\\"\u003eBrahmā\u003c/span\u003e paradise.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003etshangs pa’i mdun na ’don pa\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Brahmapurohita\",\"tibetan\":\"ཚངས་ཆེན་མདུན་འདོན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"brahmapurohita\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tshangs chen mdun ’don\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ff2493de-380b-4b95-af5d-fae406385fdc\",\"authority\":\"3e542b86-9372-408e-82b4-5002057f290b\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eSee “\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2896\\\"\u003eBrahmā\u003c/span\u003e.”\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Brahmarāja\",\"tibetan\":\"ཚངས་པའི་རྒྱལ་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"brahmarāja\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tshangs pa’i rgyal po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"41a01c6c-e7cf-4689-b3bb-4cdb181c88b6\",\"authority\":\"47bce8c5-ec29-4bea-8b8a-a459224f0ba6\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA member of the highest of the four castes in Indian society, which is closely associated with religious vocations.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"brahmin\",\"tibetan\":\"བྲམ་ཟེ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"brāhmaṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bram ze\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f6e28c1e-ca63-417e-b2ed-0ca5a353c7e5\",\"authority\":\"ca63bb7f-ceba-45f1-b520-ac2199b60741\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe seven branches of enlightenment are mindfulness, analysis of phenomena, diligence, joy, tranquility, \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2593\\\"\u003esamādhi\u003c/span\u003e, and equanimity.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"branches of enlightenment\",\"tibetan\":\"བྱང་ཆུབ་ཡན་ལག\",\"sanskrit\":\"bodhyaṅga\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"byang chub yan lag\"}},{\"uuid\":\"6998a02f-d349-4a81-94ca-0848aebce803\",\"authority\":\"6a9bbb29-903d-467f-b8d9-e31a19d63481\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eIn the Sarvāstivāda tradition, the highest of the three paradises that correspond to the fourth \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2564\\\"\u003edhyāna\u003c/span\u003e in the form realm.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Bṛhatphala\",\"tibetan\":\"འབྲས་བུ་ཆེ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bṛhatphala\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’bras bu che\"}},{\"uuid\":\"37f167ba-e5a2-46bc-a572-5195d9c77832\",\"authority\":\"717656e9-9bb2-4815-b3d1-47629d304f2c\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2496\\\"\u003eLicchavī\u003c/span\u003e youth.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003esangs rgyas skyabs\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Buddhapālita\",\"tibetan\":\"སངས་རྒྱས་སྐྱོང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"buddhapālita\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sangs rgyas skyong\"}},{\"uuid\":\"4e6fc7b2-160e-4c57-bfa1-a6888da1bb02\",\"authority\":\"4e929bf4-3650-4dfd-b6a8-2d4d8877b580\",\"definition\":\"$3a\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"caitya, cetiya, stūpa\",\"tibetan\":\"མཆོད་རྟེན།, མཆོད་རྟེན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"caitya, stūpa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mchod rten, mchod rten\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a554ea8c-d3e8-4db4-8f02-731bdd5078f8\",\"authority\":\"4e929bf4-3650-4dfd-b6a8-2d4d8877b580\",\"definition\":\"$3b\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"caitya, cetiya, stūpa\",\"tibetan\":\"མཆོད་རྟེན།, མཆོད་རྟེན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"caitya, stūpa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mchod rten, mchod rten\"}},{\"uuid\":\"03f8cdba-1bb6-4bc4-b3c7-d42fedeb80fc\",\"authority\":\"5349bf73-7ea5-48da-a21b-ee83ceeb976a\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e“Circular Enclosure”; there are at least three interpretations of what this name refers to. In the \u003ccite class=\\\"title text-en\\\" lang=\\\"en\\\"\u003eKṣitigarbha Sūtra\u003c/cite\u003e it is a mountain that contains the hells. In that case, it is equivalent to the Vaḍaba submarine mountain of fire, also said to be the entrance to the hells. More commonly, it is the name of the outer ring of mountains at the edge of the flat disk that is the world, with \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2940\\\"\u003eSumeru\u003c/span\u003e in the center. This is also equated with Vaḍaba, as it is the heat of the mountain range that evaporates the ocean so that it does not overflow. \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-3198\\\"\u003eJambudvīpa\u003c/span\u003e, the world of humans, is in this sea to \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2940\\\"\u003eSumeru\u003c/span\u003e’s south. However, the term is also used to mean the entire disk, including \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2940\\\"\u003eMeru\u003c/span\u003e and the paradises above it. An alternate form is Cakravāla.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Cakravāḍa\",\"tibetan\":\"ཁོར་ཡུག\",\"sanskrit\":\"cakravāḍa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"khor yug\"}},{\"uuid\":\"9953004c-5b0d-443b-9386-76c5aa37c286\",\"authority\":\"a4267ba1-f3d9-47a7-90c9-a1f25b234cfe\",\"definition\":\"$3c\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"cakravartin\",\"tibetan\":\"ཁོར་ལོས་སྒྱུར་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"cakravartin\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"khor los sgyur ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"83f5bfd8-cca1-4a1f-8b9b-933c62c531d5\",\"authority\":\"e62e1a69-9abb-465b-af41-efec40b7f37f\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA substance derived from the wood of the Kapur tree (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eDryobalanops aromatica\u003c/em\u003e) and also from the unrelated camphor laurel (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eCinnamomum camphora\u003c/em\u003e). \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"camphor\",\"tibetan\":\"ག་བུར།\",\"sanskrit\":\"karpūra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ga bur\"}},{\"uuid\":\"60e5e25f-dfc6-4957-a2b8-79862e890ce8\",\"authority\":\"4d246768-fa01-435d-a37c-5b8c4e4ce277\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA fierce goddess.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003ema rungs pa\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Caṇḍā\",\"tibetan\":\"གདོལ་པ་མོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"caṇḍā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gdol pa mo\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7a1acb8d-370c-492b-a420-9e5bacd6c434\",\"authority\":\"5731404d-6786-47a9-bc92-7715ff372817\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe lowest and most disparaged class of people within the caste system of ancient India, they fall outside of the caste system altogether due to their low rank in society.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"caṇḍāla\",\"tibetan\":\"གདོལ་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"caṇḍāla\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gdol pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"51ebf6c1-8c83-49b2-aff2-52417ab7ec82\",\"authority\":\"418ed4ff-54de-457b-b6e9-3c1c1ff804ba\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA fierce goddess.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003egdug pa\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Caṇḍālikā\",\"tibetan\":\"གཏུམ་མོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"caṇḍālikā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gtum mo\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0043bcae-82a2-4dc5-8dcf-5a1b18e0d2d6\",\"authority\":\"fd348767-3348-494b-b6aa-6e3967fde2be\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2555\\\"\u003eyakṣa\u003c/span\u003e king.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Candana\",\"tibetan\":\"ཙནྡན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"candana\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tsan+dan\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a9886d5c-4958-42cc-8547-9d8f0c6d1992\",\"authority\":\"4eaa6436-712f-4bfa-886d-12c67ddc1b50\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA fierce goddess.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003elag na dbyug thogs\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Caṇḍikā\",\"tibetan\":\"གཏུམ་མོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"caṇḍikā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gtum mo\"}},{\"uuid\":\"dc9f5c38-74b6-4cb1-b330-bd98ea8189cf\",\"authority\":\"7f0ab25f-2d83-40e9-bf60-876fc12b56d5\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eElettria cardamomum\u003c/em\u003e. A digestive medicine in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2445\\\"\u003eĀyurveda\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Degé 557: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003esmug smel\u003c/em\u003e. Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003esu ki ma le\u003c/em\u003e.)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"cardamom\",\"tibetan\":\"སུག་སྨེལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sūkṣmelā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sug smel\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f73cdd6f-c91b-4939-ac45-a7d06babf99c\",\"authority\":\"7925fffd-7fb2-46e8-865a-87d1f4259429\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne of the heavens of Buddhist cosmology, lowest among the six heavens of the desire realm (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003ekāmadhātu\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003e’dod khams\u003c/em\u003e). Dwelling place of the Four Great Kings (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003ecaturmahārāja\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003ergyal chen bzhi\u003c/em\u003e), traditionally located on a terrace of Sumeru, just below the Heaven of the Thirty-Three. Each cardinal direction is ruled by one of the Four Great Kings and inhabited by a different class of nonhuman beings as their subjects: in the east, Dhṛtarāṣṭra rules the gandharvas; in the south, Virūḍhaka rules the kumbhāṇḍas; in the west, Virūpākṣa rules the nāgas; and in the north, Vaiśravaṇa rules the yakṣas.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Cāturmahā­rāja­kāyika\",\"tibetan\":\"རྒྱལ་ཆེན་བཞིའི་རིས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"cāturmahā­rāja­kāyika\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rgyal chen bzhi’i ris\"}},{\"uuid\":\"6223d32c-0cca-447c-9411-0abfa0ed50d6\",\"authority\":\"002b6453-96f8-4fee-9f19-6a1890b3bbd7\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2555\\\"\u003eyakṣa\u003c/span\u003e king.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Chagalapāda\",\"tibetan\":\"ར་རྐང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"chagalapāda\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ra rkang\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5ac7ccd7-439b-4654-8843-aed37b612482\",\"authority\":\"d86a37f2-ebca-4f3d-baa7-4aef9cf16315\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThis is a product of the chir pine, also known as the long leaf pine: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003ePinus roxbhurghii\u003c/em\u003e or \u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003ePinus longifolia\u003c/em\u003e. It is used in Āyurvedic medicine. Also known in Sanskrit as \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eśrīveṣṭa\u003c/em\u003e, which appears to be the version in the manuscript from which the Tibetan was transliterated.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003ethang chu\u003c/em\u003e.)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"chir pine rosin\",\"tibetan\":\"ཤི་རི་བི་སྟ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"nīveṣṭaka, śrīveṣṭaka\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"shi ri bi sta\"}},{\"uuid\":\"51cfcf89-cd79-4ef3-9ff7-fc09b3fc1433\",\"authority\":\"454327be-1163-4202-b892-6731525162d6\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eCinnamonum tamale\u003c/em\u003e. Specifically, the Indian species of cinnamon, which has medicinal properties.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"cinnamon\",\"tibetan\":\"ཤིང་ཚ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"tvaca\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"shing tsha\"}},{\"uuid\":\"eb20f3ae-f850-4295-b88f-77d622eecbb9\",\"authority\":\"3de6cd3e-8a58-4e7d-9eea-3f1e52305366\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2555\\\"\u003eyakṣa\u003c/span\u003e king.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Citrasena\",\"tibetan\":\"སྣ་ཚོགས་སྡེ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"citrasena\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sna tshogs sde\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b3d5a0e8-79a4-40e4-9579-4fa540e5bf12\",\"authority\":\"717410b9-5207-4200-9b0f-9e66bdb46e1d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA goddess who later becomes the bodhisattva Cittaratnārcī.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Cittaratnārcī, Ratnārcī\",\"tibetan\":\"རིན་ཆེན་འོད་འཕྲོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ratnārcī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rin chen ’od ’phro\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f00df407-dd9e-41d4-9e8b-b92b156f2a09\",\"authority\":\"4eaa75fb-0a4f-42d6-8f39-1ba8a5fe0cfc\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2471\\\"\u003edeva\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Clear Insight\",\"tibetan\":\"ཤེས་རབ་གསལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"shes rab gsal\"}},{\"uuid\":\"80e0d4f9-c1ea-4e78-b4aa-46d849e8efbf\",\"authority\":\"2d0f0029-b1fe-417e-99bb-bdb29c94f787\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA buddha.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003ernam dag zla ba’i ’od zer mtshan grags rgyal po\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Completely Pure Moonlight Sign Renowned King\",\"tibetan\":\"ཟླ་འོད་རྣམ་དག་གྲགས་པའི་ཏོག་གི་རྒྱལ་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"zla ’od rnam dag grags pa’i tog gi rgyal po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a3d8c9cc-f6cd-48a8-b5f8-b4effbc098af\",\"authority\":\"0ca37cf1-6546-4004-bbf8-7a8ae0ccf099\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA fierce goddess.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 556 Degé: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003edung can\u003c/em\u003e. Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003edung chen\u003c/em\u003e. Toh 555 Narthang: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003erung chen\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Conch Shell\",\"tibetan\":\"དུང་ཅན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dung can\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c984dd02-88e2-4f00-a348-cf795744824f\",\"authority\":\"ec5082de-9d9b-4768-aae0-2ba0728cc37d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eSee the “\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-3201\\\"\u003efour confidences\u003c/span\u003e.”\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"confidence\",\"tibetan\":\"མི་འཇིགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vaiśāradya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mi ’jigs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"bc0e600b-8310-4ed6-8b4f-6e7495ab723b\",\"authority\":\"18756169-ecb5-4a4a-8882-2a7893895442\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAnother name for Agni, the god of fire.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 557: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003esbyin sreg za\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Consumer of Burnt Offerings\",\"tibetan\":\"བསྲེག་བྱ་ཟ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bsreg bya za\"}},{\"uuid\":\"e7fafd8f-5a23-44ca-b982-c530fa90f8d9\",\"authority\":\"ad254600-3b05-4817-8793-c7c9ef7b42e8\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe sixth of the twelve links or phases of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2562\\\"\u003edependent origination\u003c/span\u003e, which is the contact between the sensory consciousnesses and organs with sensory objects.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"contact\",\"tibetan\":\"རེག་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sparśa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"reg pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a6137041-6685-4790-a1bf-98fe7720b26e\",\"authority\":\"1c9a7c26-5e34-4ac0-a357-419317725ec0\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eSaussurea lappa\u003c/em\u003e. This is a 3–4-foot-tall shrub. Alternatively identified as \u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eSaussurea costus\u003c/em\u003e and \u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eCostus speciosus\u003c/em\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Bagchi edition: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eturuṣka\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"costus root\",\"tibetan\":\"རུ་རྟ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kuṣṭha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ru rta\"}},{\"uuid\":\"9fa15c72-a6ef-433c-b817-da97a403cf09\",\"authority\":\"9eedb485-4be3-4a9c-8221-9d58992ea7ce\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA buddha.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003espobs rab dgongs\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Courageous Established Intention\",\"tibetan\":\"སྤོབས་པས་བཀོད་པར་དགོངས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"spobs pas bkod par dgongs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"526737ed-20ae-4c3b-a4c5-17675082f5dd\",\"authority\":\"5b7522e4-308d-409d-b16e-3779842331b4\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eCheilocostus speciosus\u003c/em\u003e. This rhizome is used in Āyurvedic medicine to treat fever, rash, asthma, bronchitis, and intestinal worms.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"crepe ginger\",\"tibetan\":\"ཛྷ་མ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vyāmaka\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dz+ha ma\"}},{\"uuid\":\"1d1c2898-dbc2-4207-917a-5a890db7df77\",\"authority\":\"76657027-9197-400b-a5b8-cadc3b1f1af5\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2471\\\"\u003edeva\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003enyon mongs pa yongs su spangs pa\u003c/em\u003e; Degé Toh 556: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003enyong mongs nad sel\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Curing Affliction, Remover of Affliction\",\"tibetan\":\"ཉོན་མོངས་ནད་སེལ།, ཉོན་མོངས་ནད་སེལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nyon mongs nad sel, nyon mongs nad sel\"}},{\"uuid\":\"37d938d2-8b9e-4c2b-99c3-3e87e5e836c3\",\"authority\":\"76657027-9197-400b-a5b8-cadc3b1f1af5\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bodhisattva.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003enyon mongs pa’i nad rnam par sel ba\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Curing Affliction, Remover of Affliction\",\"tibetan\":\"ཉོན་མོངས་ནད་སེལ།, ཉོན་མོངས་ནད་སེལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nyon mongs nad sel, nyon mongs nad sel\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ca16fc7e-12ae-457f-aebb-fffa56c8654a\",\"authority\":\"d1febedb-9d2f-49ff-8461-be559f8a78c4\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA resin from the tree known as sarjarasa, sarja, white dammar, or Indian copal tree (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eVateria indica\u003c/em\u003e). The white dammar resin is used in incense and Āyurvedic medicine.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003esa rdza ra sa\u003c/em\u003e.)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"dammar gum\",\"tibetan\":\"སྲ་རྩི།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sarjarasa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sra rtsi\"}},{\"uuid\":\"eb798991-a7c3-403d-9071-323b1dd8f1cf\",\"authority\":\"ec0b77ec-1588-4802-b72f-9ccde2733577\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThis is the Śākya Daṇḍapāṇi who, in the \u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eLalitavistara Sūtra\u003c/cite\u003e (\u003ccite class=\\\"title text-en\\\" lang=\\\"en\\\"\u003e\u003ca target=\\\"_blank\\\" href=\\\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh95.html\\\" title=\\\"The Play in Full\\\"\u003eThe Play in Full\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/cite\u003e), is described as the father of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2895\\\"\u003eGopā\u003c/span\u003e, the Buddha’s wife. There are others of that name, such as the brother of the Buddha’s mother, \u003cspan\u003e\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2742\\\"\u003eMāyā\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e, and also the uncle of the Buddha’s other wife, Yaśodharā. However, that Daṇḍapāṇi was a member of the neighboring Koliya clan. There is also a contrasting account of a Śākya Daṇḍapāṇi who is said to have been a follower of Devadatta and who was dissatisfied by the Buddha’s answers when he met him in Kapilavastu, the capital of the Śākya clan. His nickname, “Cane Holder,” is said to be because he always carried a golden cane.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Daṇḍapāṇi\",\"tibetan\":\"ལག་ན་བེ་ཅོན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"daṇḍapāṇi\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lag na be con\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f8703e2c-28d1-4072-87d5-c8898004245d\",\"authority\":\"f856854b-2f97-4d78-be64-3a695244fc89\",\"definition\":\"$3d\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"defilements\",\"tibetan\":\"ཟག་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"āsrava, āśrava\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"zag pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2dd55171-519a-484c-a429-7a83bfef6390\",\"authority\":\"5d4bc623-32db-41b1-8b96-ff9544329ece\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThis refers to the dependent nature of phenomena. One of the three natures that are a central philosophy of the Yogācāra tradition.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"dependent\",\"tibetan\":\"གཞན་དབང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"paratantra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gzhan dbang\"}},{\"uuid\":\"59767f12-0e96-4bb4-8975-ba7b9a279e86\",\"authority\":\"7c76567b-2f1b-4a24-a261-ff3975b05630\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eSee “\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-3213\\\"\u003etwelve phases of dependent origination\u003c/span\u003e.”\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"dependent origination\",\"tibetan\":\"རྟེན་ཅིང་འབྲེལ་པར་འབྱུང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"pratītyasamutpāda\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rten cing ’brel par ’byung ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a09787ca-2952-4bf6-a04c-bde6f4cf3e40\",\"authority\":\"87f6ed5d-68a9-4ddd-8744-81855f2d8943\",\"definition\":\"$3e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"deva\",\"tibetan\":\"ལྷ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"deva\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lha\"}},{\"uuid\":\"79869af1-9ffa-45e1-9ef0-f5da257c2883\",\"authority\":\"28f0af52-2ca2-45db-87bb-dd59af025247\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA female being in the paradises from the base of Mount \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2940\\\"\u003eSumeru\u003c/span\u003e upward. Also can refer to a female deity or goddess in the human world. See also “\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2471\\\"\u003edeva\u003c/span\u003e.”\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"devī\",\"tibetan\":\"ལྷ་མོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"devī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lha mo\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c161a89c-8874-435b-a0cf-5dda3a665750\",\"authority\":\"0baf976f-a73f-4674-bea3-56e3d670ba1a\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe term \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003edhāraṇī\u003c/em\u003e has the sense of something that “holds” or “retains,” and so it can refer to the special capacity of practitioners to memorize and recall detailed teachings. It can also refer to a verbal expression of the teachings‍—an incantation, spell, or mnemonic formula‍—that distills and “holds” essential points of the Dharma and is used by practitioners to attain mundane and supramundane goals. The same term is also used to denote texts that contain such formulas.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"dhāraṇī, retention\",\"tibetan\":\"གཟུངས་སྔགས།, གཟུངས།, གཟུངས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dhāraṇī, dhāraṇī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gzungs, gzungs, gzungs sngags\"}},{\"uuid\":\"46efeb6b-88fc-404c-a409-46b148a31cf0\",\"authority\":\"0baf976f-a73f-4674-bea3-56e3d670ba1a\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAn exceptional power of mental retention. The term \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2472\\\"\u003edhāraṇī\u003c/span\u003e has the sense of something that “holds” or “retains,” and it can also refer to a verbal expression of the teachings‍—an incantation, spell, or mnemonic formula that distills and “holds” essential points of the Dharma and is used by practitioners to attain mundane and supramundane goals.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"dhāraṇī, retention\",\"tibetan\":\"གཟུངས་སྔགས།, གཟུངས།, གཟུངས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dhāraṇī, dhāraṇī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gzungs, gzungs, gzungs sngags\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5256ac41-c3df-43dd-8601-ded0a94fe9a5\",\"authority\":\"95006a51-abbb-4bdc-8d06-6cfc6ccc0689\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bodhisattva.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Dharaṇīśvararāja\",\"tibetan\":\"གཟུངས་ཀྱི་དབང་ཕྱུག་རྒྱལ་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dharaṇīśvararāja\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gzungs kyi dbang phyug rgyal po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0a6167f8-dde3-4a27-9610-5a006a6f7516\",\"authority\":\"6e5dc81d-3c8a-493e-9a77-987aa0ef3895\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eIn its earliest use it generally meant that though the corporeal body of the Buddha had perished, his “body of the Dharma” continued. It also referred to the Buddha’s realization of reality, to his qualities as a whole, or to his teachings as embodying him. It later came to be synonymous with enlightenment or buddhahood, a “body” that can only be “seen” by a buddha.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Dharma body\",\"tibetan\":\"ཆོས་ཀྱི་སྐུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dharmakāya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"chos kyi sku\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0bb9956b-39a4-4769-a0f3-f1ae1a69f236\",\"authority\":\"ebb48fae-4edb-40ff-b9e7-188a2a3f4a98\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA synonym for the ultimate nature of reality. The term is interpreted variously and can be translated according to context as “Dharma realm,” “Dharma element,” “the realm of phenomena,” or “the element of phenomena.”\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Dharma realm\",\"tibetan\":\"ཆོས་ཀྱི་དབྱིངས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dharmadhātu\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"chos kyi dbyings\"}},{\"uuid\":\"adee8b8e-5c28-4af7-ad3a-7a092cacba74\",\"authority\":\"5b2ed3c9-0e7b-459e-8cc5-95afa7a3810a\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eSpeaker or reciter of scriptures. In early Buddhism a section of the saṅgha would consist of \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003ebhāṇakas\u003c/em\u003e, who, particularly before the teachings were written down and were only transmitted orally, were a key factor in the preservation of the teachings. Various groups of dharmabhāṇakas specialized in memorizing and reciting a certain set of sūtras or vinaya.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"dharmabhāṇaka\",\"tibetan\":\"ཆོས་སྨྲ་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dharmabhāṇaka\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"chos smra ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"9fda5726-1115-4887-a239-7573df656507\",\"authority\":\"87f71c36-2b30-4b5d-827a-42b9e76dcc7f\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2496\\\"\u003eLicchavī\u003c/span\u003e youth.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003echos byin\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Dharmadatta\",\"tibetan\":\"ཆོས་སྦྱིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dharmadatta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"chos sbyin\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2bfb32d5-be96-448f-959c-22c20746d8e5\",\"authority\":\"6386e1c7-2ccd-4ff1-a655-d3f1ca46d4fb\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA buddha.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Dharmadhvaja\",\"tibetan\":\"ཆོས་ཀྱི་རྒྱལ་མཚན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dharmadhvaja\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"chos kyi rgyal mtshan\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7601da1e-595f-4cac-b032-f25da4ba4d4e\",\"authority\":\"39357dfd-aea6-4bc2-a28f-f89d9966cd20\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2496\\\"\u003eLicchavī\u003c/span\u003e youth.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003echos skyabs\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Dharmapāla\",\"tibetan\":\"ཆོས་སྐྱོང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dharmapāla\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"chos skyong\"}},{\"uuid\":\"1cd2a4c8-2b35-4488-be93-2d0f242583fc\",\"authority\":\"a98141d1-4884-4201-ae9a-efa646c007ad\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA great bodhisattva, residing in a divine city called Gandhavatī, who teaches the Prajñāpāramitā three times a day. He is known for becoming the \u003cspan\u003eteacher\u003c/span\u003e of the bodhisattva Sadāprarudita, who decides to sell his flesh and blood in order to make offerings to him and receive his teachings. This story is told in \u003ccite class=\\\"title text-en\\\" lang=\\\"en\\\"\u003e\u003ca target=\\\"_blank\\\" href=\\\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh10.html\\\" title=\\\"The Perfection of Wisdom in Eighteen Thousand Lines\\\"\u003eThe Perfection of Wisdom in Eighteen Thousand Lines\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/cite\u003e (Toh 10, ch. 85–86). It can also be found quoted in several works, such as \u003ccite class=\\\"title text-en\\\" lang=\\\"en\\\"\u003eThe Words of My Perfect Teacher\u003c/cite\u003e (\u003ccite class=\\\"title text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003ekun bzang bla ma’i zhal lung\u003c/cite\u003e) by Patrul Rinpoche.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Dharmodgata\",\"tibetan\":\"ཆོས་འཕགས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dharmodgata\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"chos ’phags\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c0b79d0f-260a-4af7-b74a-a62f42950334\",\"authority\":\"3e1eb21a-0018-417c-946d-1e5d73b2c584\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne way of describing experience and the world in terms of eighteen elements (eye and form, ear and sound, nose and smell, tongue and taste, body and physical objects, and mind and mental phenomena, to which the six consciousnesses are added). Also refers here to the four elements of earth, water, fire, and wind.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"dhātu\",\"tibetan\":\"ཁམས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dhātu\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"khams\"}},{\"uuid\":\"34ee7b74-4c29-427c-b1cc-73098c8a2964\",\"authority\":\"b14e9896-8b44-45ed-9b7d-5692e266740f\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2867\\\"\u003eFour Mahārājas\u003c/span\u003e, he is the guardian deity for the east and lord of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2486\\\"\u003egandharvas\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Dhṛtarāṣṭra\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡུལ་འཁོར་སྲུང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dhṛtarāṣṭra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"yul ’khor srung\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7df1427c-236b-4443-b0e5-2a5da6419026\",\"authority\":\"72b9bc1c-896f-4242-998d-15fd6a7a4b90\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eDhyāna\u003c/em\u003e is defined as one-pointed abiding in an undistracted state of mind, free from afflicted mental states. Four states of \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003edhyāna\u003c/em\u003e are identified as being conducive to birth within the form realm. In the context of the Mahāyāna, it is the fifth of the six perfections. It is commonly translated as “concentration,” “meditative concentration,” and so on.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"dhyāna\",\"tibetan\":\"བསམ་གཏན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dhyāna\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bsam gtan\"}},{\"uuid\":\"1cd15e37-74a4-4aba-9a5f-404c78034ff1\",\"authority\":\"dbe5f228-6837-4e2e-b3af-e1e937d13be8\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe name of an \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2480\\\"\u003eeon\u003c/span\u003e. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Difficult to Conquer King of Radiance\",\"tibetan\":\"རྒྱལ་བར་དཀའ་བའི་འོད་ཀྱི་རྒྱལ་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"durjayaprabharāja\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rgyal bar dka’ ba’i ’od kyi rgyal po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b4f56932-04e1-4e0c-90a5-533402ff3330\",\"authority\":\"bfe4d3f5-e5a5-413c-b53e-94a7b3146f21\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA designation used for a group of languages spoken in the south of India, including Telugu, Kannada, Malayalam, and Tamil.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Dravidian\",\"tibetan\":\"དྲཱ་བི་ཌ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"drāviḍa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"drA bi Da\"}},{\"uuid\":\"61a9d519-40bc-47f2-8204-a84f6ee5ef65\",\"authority\":\"82cb487f-34c0-4275-a48a-3324b6aae30a\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe goddess of the earth.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003esra ba\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Dṛḍhā\",\"tibetan\":\"བརྟན་མ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dṛḍhā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"brtan ma\"}},{\"uuid\":\"49c93315-1451-4874-87c0-974a619ab4e8\",\"authority\":\"8b088036-c076-45f4-b62e-f5ec97f661c7\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe principal buddha of the northern direction.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003ernga sgra skyabs\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Dundubhisvara\",\"tibetan\":\"རྔ་སྒྲ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dundubhisvara\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rnga sgra\"}},{\"uuid\":\"df742301-a2f1-43ee-ab72-6150dc202923\",\"authority\":\"fee65798-f1d9-4da1-80cc-583748d79580\",\"definition\":\"$3f\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"eight liberations\",\"tibetan\":\"རྣམ་པར་གྲོལ་བ་བརྒྱད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"aṣṭavimokṣa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rnam par grol ba brgyad\"}},{\"uuid\":\"4169778b-b61e-4543-9188-38e7df4afde9\",\"authority\":\"36fb77c8-5c43-415f-beeb-09e3e1f4797f\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA set of circumstances that do not provide the freedom to practice the Buddhist path: being born in the realms of (1) the hells, (2) hungry ghosts (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003epretas\u003c/em\u003e), (3) animals, or (4) long-lived gods, or in the human realm among (5) barbarians or (6) extremists, (7) in places where the Buddhist teachings do not exist, or (8) without adequate faculties to understand the teachings where they do exist.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"eight unfavorable states\",\"tibetan\":\"མི་ཁོམ་པ་བརྒྱད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"aṣṭākṣaṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mi khom pa brgyad\"}},{\"uuid\":\"99b9bf82-62aa-48b6-8fac-9e917973c3bd\",\"authority\":\"94abea97-e08e-42b5-8572-1a426431c53e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe eight vows taken by a layperson for just one day, usually a full-moon or new-moon day: no killing, no stealing, celibacy, no lying, no intoxicants, no sitting on a high chair, no singing or dancing, no wearing of adornments or perfumes.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"eight vows\",\"tibetan\":\"གསོ་སྦྱོང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"poṣadha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gso sbyong\"}},{\"uuid\":\"078683f8-28ea-4af5-8a96-968eed6c76c3\",\"authority\":\"dc256341-133d-4ef5-b7e8-cb69d77b1bea\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThere are eighteen such qualities unique to a buddha, which consist of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2533\\\"\u003eten strengths\u003c/span\u003e, the four fearlessnesses, three mindfulnesses, and great compassion.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"eighteen unique qualities of a buddha, unique qualities of a buddha\",\"tibetan\":\"སངས་རྒྱས་གྱི་ཆོས་མ་འདྲེས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"āveṇika­buddha­dharma\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sangs rgyas gyi chos ma ’dres pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"1214ac9b-cd30-4785-96f5-43fbe6970113\",\"authority\":\"69e209c0-8d07-4b75-871c-3a28170d6198\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA set of eighty bodily characteristics borne by buddhas and universal emperors. They are considered “minor” in terms of being secondary to the thirty-two major marks of a great being. These can be found listed, for example, in Prajñāpāramitā sūtras (see \u003ca target=\\\"_blank\\\" href=\\\"https://read.84000.co/translation/UT22084-026-001.html#UT22084-026-001-5841\\\" title=\\\"Toh 9\\\"\u003eToh 9\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca target=\\\"_blank\\\" href=\\\"https://read.84000.co/translation/UT22084-029-001.html#UT22084-029-001-5663\\\" title=\\\"Toh 10\\\"\u003eToh 10\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca target=\\\"_blank\\\" href=\\\"https://read.84000.co/translation/UT22084-031-002.html#UT22084-031-002-292\\\" title=\\\"Toh 11\\\"\u003eToh 11\u003c/a\u003e) or in \u003ccite class=\\\"title text-en\\\" lang=\\\"en\\\"\u003eThe Play in Full\u003c/cite\u003e (Toh 95, \u003ca target=\\\"_blank\\\" href=\\\"https://read.84000.co/translation/UT22084-046-001.html#UT22084-046-001-476\\\" title=\\\"7.100\\\"\u003e7.100\u003c/a\u003e) and many other sūtras.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"eighty features\",\"tibetan\":\"དཔེ་བྱད་བཟང་པོ་བརྒྱད་ཅུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"aśītyanuvyañjana\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dpe byad bzang po brgyad cu\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f319605c-f007-4840-a761-76a0ad6aacf4\",\"authority\":\"5f36f403-6912-417c-bcc4-6b415bd5845d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA nāga king often present in the retinue of the Buddha Śākyamuni. According to the Vinaya, in the time of the Buddha Kāśyapa he had been a monk (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003ebhikṣu\u003c/em\u003e) who angrily cut down a thorny bush at the entrance of his cave because it always snagged his robes. Cutting down bushes or even grass is contrary to the monastic rules and he did not confess his action. Therefore, he was reborn as a nāga with a tree growing out of his head, which caused him great pain whenever the wind blew. This tale is found represented in ancient sculpture and is often quoted to demonstrate how small misdeeds can lead to great consequences. See, e.g., Patrul Rinpoche, \u003ccite class=\\\"title text-en\\\" lang=\\\"en\\\"\u003eThe Words of My Perfect Teacher\u003c/cite\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003eela’i lo ma\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Elapatra\",\"tibetan\":\"ཨེ་ལའི་འདབ་མ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"elapatra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"e la’i ’dab ma\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c73b5e86-3fdb-4c2c-8a69-e6b7e4c5cbe9\",\"authority\":\"9692559e-037d-4ec3-acf1-df2ebffe2597\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eManifestations of the Buddha, particularly as the principal buddha of an age, that are perceivable by ordinary beings.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"emanation body, illusory body\",\"tibetan\":\"སྤྲུལ་པའི་སྐུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"nirmitakāya, nirmāṇakāya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sprul pa’i sku\"}},{\"uuid\":\"1e7fa671-a07c-41c2-ac36-bd729926ac4d\",\"authority\":\"3467af23-ec7c-47ca-ae1a-7636b24a4165\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe enjoyment body denotes the luminous, immaterial, and unimpeded reflection-like forms that become spontaneously present and naturally manifest to tenth level bodhisattvas.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eDegé 557: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003esha mi\u003c/em\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"enjoyment body\",\"tibetan\":\"ལོང་སྤྱོད་རྫོགས་པའི་སྐུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"saṃbhogakāya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"long spyod rdzogs pa’i sku\"}},{\"uuid\":\"928932c0-6792-4c7e-a680-51bed7aee745\",\"authority\":\"73ad2262-b388-42c1-b3d4-30f1f6a507fc\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA cosmic period of time, sometimes equivalent to the time when a world system appears, exists, and disappears. According to the traditional Abhidharma understanding of cyclical time, a great eon (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003emahākalpa\u003c/em\u003e) is divided into eighty lesser eons. In the course of one great eon, the universe takes form and later disappears. During the first twenty of the lesser eons, the universe is in the process of creation and expansion; during the next twenty it remains; during the third twenty, it is in the process of destruction; and during the last quarter of the cycle, it remains in a state of empty stasis. A fortunate, or good, eon (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003ebhadrakalpa\u003c/em\u003e) refers to any eon in which more than one buddha appears.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"eon\",\"tibetan\":\"བསྐལ་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kalpa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bskal pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"854be481-bcd5-45d1-9b5f-e8b70ff40096\",\"authority\":\"bfe15f8c-1c0b-4fcf-94e2-99a90c7c2394\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA buddha.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Equally Seeing\",\"tibetan\":\"མཉམ་པར་གཟིགས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mnyam par gzigs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"87dd20a5-cd48-4889-821e-a7e8257b068b\",\"authority\":\"74fb59d7-a1fa-4805-8fb7-2965b34975dc\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of the future buddha whom the goddess \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2785\\\"\u003eRatnārcī\u003c/span\u003e is prophesied to become.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Essence of Illustrious Precious Radiance\",\"tibetan\":\"རིན་པོ་ཆེའི་འོད་དཔལ་གྱི་སྙིང་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rin po che’i ’od dpal gyi snying po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"50a299a0-dabb-478d-9b4a-0499dcd6e8ee\",\"authority\":\"8b13ef63-6ef2-4b21-9818-93ffbb1f678b\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2555\\\"\u003eyakṣa\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003epad ma ’od\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Essence of Lotus Radiance\",\"tibetan\":\"པདྨོའི་འོད་ཀྱི་སྙིང་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"pad+mo’i ’od kyi snying po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0f1a5dc6-f421-427a-a215-5335fbb89637\",\"authority\":\"257dc956-a3b3-4ced-a43d-4996bf0a5716\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA buddha in the distant future who is \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2792\\\"\u003eRūpyaprabha\u003c/span\u003e, the son of the bodhisattva \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2790\\\"\u003eRuciraketu\u003c/span\u003e in the time of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2797\\\"\u003eŚākyamuni\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eSuvarṇaketuprabha\u003c/em\u003e; \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003egser tog ’od\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Essence of the Radiance of a Hundred Golden Lights\",\"tibetan\":\"གསེར་བརྒྱའི་འོད་ཟེར་དུ་སྣང་བའི་སྙིང་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gser brgya’i ’od zer du snang ba’i snying po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a421de4e-da29-416c-b7eb-ba30a100163f\",\"authority\":\"b3de60ff-c2d1-4490-9324-a1446024fc61\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA buddha.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Exalted Light Rays\",\"tibetan\":\"འོད་ཟེར་མཐོ་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’od zer mtho ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"558ca933-65c5-44ad-8e08-b4577fef78cb\",\"authority\":\"dd59dcad-cbd9-4632-9b44-ba0799255931\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA buddha.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003ePadmavijaya\u003c/em\u003e; \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003ernam par rgyal ba’i pad ma\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Excellent Lotus\",\"tibetan\":\"པདྨ་དམ་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"pad+ma dam pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"fd7bdd27-46ed-4c05-9c6c-6045fe0c7e34\",\"authority\":\"b0b34e6d-6ef5-4d2a-8989-b380b2fe1666\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bodhisattva.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eViśuddhaprajñā\u003c/em\u003e; \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003eshes rab rnam par dag pa\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Extremely Pure Intelligence\",\"tibetan\":\"ཤིན་ཏུ་རྣམ་དག་བློ་གྲོས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"shin tu rnam dag blo gros\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ff6edbee-10df-4177-b75c-70b2b808f640\",\"authority\":\"c30352bd-e590-4af5-afdd-956b58f0ccda\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bodhisattva.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003e’od rgyan chen po\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Extremely Radiant Array\",\"tibetan\":\"ཤིན་ཏུ་འོད་བཀོད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"shin tu ’od bkod\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d2f43dfb-9961-4059-bee2-32b704884515\",\"authority\":\"bd9c72df-c429-494d-a34c-6dab44cd0342\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eTrigonella corniculata\u003c/em\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555 has \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003espri ka spo\u003c/em\u003e. Toh 557 translates as \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003e’u su\u003c/em\u003e.)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"fenugreek\",\"tibetan\":\"སྤྲྀ་ཀ\",\"sanskrit\":\"spṛkā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"spr-i ka\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ff99b818-8f03-4066-a206-dbb804c6dbcb\",\"authority\":\"41ba6b2d-c49a-4313-85a1-664b22b9e846\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe mythological flower of the fig tree, said to appear on rare occasions, such as the birth of a buddha. The actual fig tree flower is contained within the fruit. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"fig tree flower\",\"tibetan\":\"ཨུ་དུམ་བཱ་ར།\",\"sanskrit\":\"udumbara\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"u dum bA ra\"}},{\"uuid\":\"462e98db-df71-41ce-a887-83dcc04f94d0\",\"authority\":\"5943359f-c56a-4546-9eac-d3cceb1e939e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bodhisattva.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eViryatapas\u003c/em\u003e; \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003ebrtson ’grus dka’ thub\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Firm Effort\",\"tibetan\":\"བརྩོན་འགྲུས་བརྟན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"brtson ’grus brtan\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b63f158f-3aaa-4dc9-bb9b-61a3ebff3ac8\",\"authority\":\"16634033-bb38-49c5-9048-21ff9b967e91\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe five degenerations are (1) the degeneration of life span, (2) the degeneration of views, (3) the degeneration of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2558\\\"\u003eafflictions\u003c/span\u003e, (4) the degeneration of beings, and (5) the degeneration of the era.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"five degenerations\",\"tibetan\":\"སྙིགས་མ་རྣམ་པ་ལྔ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"pañcakaṣāya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"snyigs ma rnam pa lnga\"}},{\"uuid\":\"65e50e3e-c2ad-4aa3-b391-9f055f541525\",\"authority\":\"476b6731-6bce-414d-8b7c-886957fbc273\",\"definition\":\"$40\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"five kinds of obscurations\",\"tibetan\":\"སྒྲིབ་པ་རྣམ་པ་ལྔ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"pañcanīvaraṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sgrib pa rnam pa lnga\"}},{\"uuid\":\"9bf44f16-bce8-4db4-bca7-98441af92d5b\",\"authority\":\"f029e524-ebb2-4fa0-8f20-41c07ac946b7\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe five skandhas, or aggregates, are form, feeling, perception, \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2483\\\"\u003eformation\u003c/span\u003e, and consciousness. On the individual level the five aggregates refer to the basis upon which the mistaken idea of a self is projected.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"five skandhas, skandhas\",\"tibetan\":\"ཕུང་པོ་ལྔ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"pañcaskandha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"phung po lnga\"}},{\"uuid\":\"64506262-075c-4d8b-a6e2-fcc1f40036da\",\"authority\":\"da1cbe63-d5d7-4ee7-b579-8f13a92555e3\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe meaning of this term varies according to context. As one of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2569\\\"\u003eskandhas\u003c/span\u003e it refers to various mental activities. In terms of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-3213\\\"\u003etwelve phases of dependent origination\u003c/span\u003e it is the second, “formation” or “creation,” referring to activities with karmic results. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"formation\",\"tibetan\":\"འདུ་བྱེད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"saṃskāra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’du byed\"}},{\"uuid\":\"eb2c4c18-56a5-473e-87cd-dcf5f9869133\",\"authority\":\"4fd43520-939f-4f26-98c3-f8e40155dada\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThis refers to the four \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2464\\\"\u003econfidences\u003c/span\u003e or fearlessnesses (as translated into Tibetan) of a buddha: full \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2464\\\"\u003econfidence\u003c/span\u003e that (1) they are fully awakened; (2) they have removed all \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2470\\\"\u003edefilements\u003c/span\u003e; (3) they have taught about the obstacles to liberation; and (4) they have shown the path to liberation. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"four confidences\",\"tibetan\":\"མི་འཇིགས་པ་བཞི།\",\"sanskrit\":\"caturvaiśāradya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mi ’jigs pa bzhi\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d5db140f-bef5-4ec8-bb78-8ce31db8f39c\",\"authority\":\"a8e1f71c-9f29-461d-9f42-687c48d43e34\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe discernments of meaning, phenomena, language, and eloquence.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"four discernments\",\"tibetan\":\"སོ་སོ་ཡང་དག་པར་རིག་པ་བཞི།\",\"sanskrit\":\"catuḥpratisaṃvid\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"so so yang dag par rig pa bzhi\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0eb1982c-19be-4eb5-8ee3-dca0a2aa252d\",\"authority\":\"5f9ba324-e348-415a-afcd-5b81b4a6855b\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eWalking, standing, sitting, and lying down. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"four kinds of physical actions\",\"tibetan\":\"སྤྱོད་ལམ་རྣམ་པ་བཞི།\",\"sanskrit\":\"caturvidham īryāpatham\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"spyod lam rnam pa bzhi\"}},{\"uuid\":\"772224d0-971a-49ab-8f56-49664a2477ad\",\"authority\":\"d0099514-8ec5-4014-9139-eb47d42c74a0\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eFour gods who live on the lower slopes (fourth level) of Mount Meru in the eponymous Heaven of the Four Great Kings (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eCāturmahā­rājika\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003ergyal chen bzhi’i ris\u003c/em\u003e) and guard the four cardinal directions. Each is the leader of a nonhuman class of beings living in his realm. They are Dhṛtarāṣṭra, ruling the gandharvas in the east; Virūḍhaka, ruling over the kumbhāṇḍas in the south; Virūpākṣa, ruling the nāgas in the west; and Vaiśravaṇa (also known as Kubera) ruling the yakṣas in the north. Also referred to as Guardians of the World or World Protectors (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003elokapāla\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003e’jig rten skyong ba\u003c/em\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Four Mahārājas\",\"tibetan\":\"རྒྱལ་པོ་ཆེན་པོ་བཞི།\",\"sanskrit\":\"caturmahārāja\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rgyal po chen po bzhi\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d8333d1e-9682-4b7c-8b0e-a3d08e75f4ef\",\"authority\":\"f9dcdbaf-6f68-48a3-968f-cd02684619e7\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe ancient Indian army was composed of four branches (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003ecaturaṅga\u003c/em\u003e)‍—infantry, cavalry, chariots, and elephants.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"fourfold army\",\"tibetan\":\"དཔུང་གི་ཚོགས་ཡན་ལག་བཞི།\",\"sanskrit\":\"caturaṅgabalakāya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dpung gi tshogs yan lag bzhi\"}},{\"uuid\":\"faf62992-77ce-4ac2-944b-a66ec4863aad\",\"authority\":\"b6a7ab7d-69dc-4e76-a0b9-bd5895d5e672\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e Also known as olibanum, this is a resin from trees of the genus \u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eBoswellia\u003c/em\u003e, in this case, \u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eBoswellia serrata\u003c/em\u003e, “Indian frankincense.” It is also known as \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003esalai\u003c/em\u003e and \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eśallakī\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003etilakalka\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003evṛścika\u003c/em\u003e, and \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eturuṣka\u003c/em\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Bagchi edition: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003esihlaka\u003c/em\u003e. Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003esa la ki\u003c/em\u003e.)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"frankincense\",\"tibetan\":\"དུ་རུ་སྐ།, ས་ལ་ཀི\",\"sanskrit\":\"śallaki\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"du ru ska, sa la ki\"}},{\"uuid\":\"9e639ef1-5a68-4ae3-9c7f-8a12f268513c\",\"authority\":\"f46d0f19-ab96-472f-a8d5-37b0679e92ff\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA mountain north of the Himalayas, said to be fifty \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2557\\\"\u003eyojanas\u003c/span\u003e from Mount Kailash. In other sūtras, it is translated as \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003espos ngad can\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003espos ngad ldang\u003c/em\u003e, or \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003espos nad ldan\u003c/em\u003e. Mount Gandhamardan in Orissa, India, was at one time a center for Buddhist study and practice.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Gandhamādana\",\"tibetan\":\"སྤོས་ཀྱི་ངད་ལྡང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"gandhamādana\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"spos kyi ngad ldang ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"e5ecdd12-cdf7-40f9-8159-f2a466a8563e\",\"authority\":\"74461fd0-5ed8-4923-b6bb-16bb40dfa426\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA class of generally benevolent nonhuman beings who inhabit the skies, sometimes said to inhabit fantastic cities in the clouds, and more specifically to dwell on the eastern slopes of Mount Meru, where they are ruled by the Great King Dhṛtarāṣṭra. They are most renowned as celestial musicians who serve the gods. In the Abhidharma, the term is also used to refer to the mental body assumed by sentient beings during the intermediate state between death and rebirth. Gandharvas are said to live on fragrances (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003egandha\u003c/em\u003e) in the desire realm, hence the Tibetan translation \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003edri za\u003c/em\u003e, meaning “scent eater.”\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"gandharva\",\"tibetan\":\"དྲི་ཟ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"gandharva\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dri za\"}},{\"uuid\":\"dc6807a0-2fe4-4e30-a622-969e73ebef7a\",\"authority\":\"7a42d538-cbe0-4c84-8ee8-0e0872af7522\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2555\\\"\u003eyakṣa\u003c/span\u003e king.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Gandharva\",\"tibetan\":\"དྲི་ཟ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"gandharva\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dri za\"}},{\"uuid\":\"90b14b9b-aa32-458f-88b3-235142dbefbf\",\"authority\":\"7710024b-0c49-4569-8c67-49029ae3307f\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe elephant-headed deity, more popularly known as Ganesh and associated with overcoming obstacles. The son of Śiva.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Ganeśa\",\"tibetan\":\"ཚོགས་བདག\",\"sanskrit\":\"ganeśa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tshogs bdag\"}},{\"uuid\":\"9e8dcefa-ed96-45be-8284-93d779464b51\",\"authority\":\"290a98ad-e838-4074-ac32-84874d57c777\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA female disciple of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2587\\\"\u003eTathāgata\u003c/span\u003e \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2726\\\"\u003eGreat Mass of Light\u003c/span\u003e who became a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2460\\\"\u003ecakravartin\u003c/span\u003e king eighty-four thousand times and eventually the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2587\\\"\u003eTathāgata\u003c/span\u003e \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-3279\\\"\u003eRatnārci\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Gaṅgadevī\",\"tibetan\":\"གང་གཱའི་ལྷ་མོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"gaṅgadevī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gang gA’i lha mo\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f1f547b8-a278-490a-9223-f949fcad521b\",\"authority\":\"062f7b7f-39dc-4bcc-a998-f5cf2636a853\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe Gaṅgā, or Ganges in English, is considered to be the most sacred river of India, particularly within the Hindu tradition. It starts in the Himalayas, flows through the northern plains of India, bathing the holy city of Vārāṇasī, and meets the sea at the Bay of Bengal, in Bangladesh. In the sūtras, however, this river is mostly mentioned not for its sacredness but for its abundant sands‍—noticeable still today on its many sandy banks and at its delta‍—which serve as a common metaphor for infinitely large numbers.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAccording to Buddhist cosmology, as explained in the \u003ccite class=\\\"title text-en\\\" lang=\\\"en\\\"\u003eAbhidharmakośa\u003c/cite\u003e, it is one of the four rivers that flow from Lake Anavatapta and cross the southern continent of Jambudvīpa‍—the known human world or more specifically the Indian subcontinent. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Ganges\",\"tibetan\":\"གང་གཱ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"gaṅgā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gang gA\"}},{\"uuid\":\"63a551d2-800b-4bc7-802d-cecec8515ad2\",\"authority\":\"ba7579fc-ce40-4ade-b704-5f7d033091cc\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eIn Indian mythology, the garuḍa is an eagle-like bird that is regarded as the king of all birds, normally depicted with a sharp, owl-like beak, often holding a snake, and with large and powerful wings. They are traditionally enemies of the nāgas. In the Vedas, they are said to have brought nectar from the heavens to earth. \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eGaruḍa\u003c/em\u003e can also be used as a proper name for a king of such creatures.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"garuḍa\",\"tibetan\":\"ནམ་མཁའ་ལྡིང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"garuḍa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nam mkha’ lding\"}},{\"uuid\":\"75515b84-5048-4e80-912e-05ad16932c85\",\"authority\":\"4cb75fa0-53e1-4799-9bd5-368cd78d3a95\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe brother of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2745\\\"\u003eNadīkāśyapa\u003c/span\u003e and \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2844\\\"\u003eUruvilva­kāśyapa\u003c/span\u003e. A practitioner of fire offering at Uruvilva (Bodhgayā), he and his two hundred students were converted to becoming \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2450\\\"\u003ebhikṣus\u003c/span\u003e of the Buddha. He and his brothers and their students were the third group to become followers of the Buddha after his enlightenment.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Gayākāśyapa\",\"tibetan\":\"ག་ཡཱ་འོད་སྲུང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"gayākāśyapa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ga yA ’od srung\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b42cf2c8-dbcd-4d9d-a3cb-65927ccdbde0\",\"authority\":\"23706636-07a1-45a5-9cda-9beab9f0cd57\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe great goddess Śrī, better known as Lakṣmī, who promises to aid those who recite this sūtra and to ensure its preservation so that beings will have good fortune. She dwells in a palace in the paradise of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2902\\\"\u003eAlakāvati\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Goddess Śrī, Śrī\",\"tibetan\":\"དཔལ་གྱི་ལྷ་མོ།, དཔལ།, ལྷ་མོ་དཔལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śrī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dpal, dpal gyi lha mo, lha mo dpal\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ce4453f2-e94f-4575-9fad-8936db171dc3\",\"authority\":\"bdca19c6-0382-4360-a1cc-70885cf1c7ef\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bodhisattva.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Golden City Mountain\",\"tibetan\":\"གསེར་གྱི་གྲོང་ཁྱེར་རི་བོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gser gyi grong khyer ri bo\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f73b1614-329a-489d-9e5f-48330f86edc3\",\"authority\":\"dd6f5e45-b505-48ab-8c5d-5137df29072a\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bodhisattva.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003egser mdzod\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Golden Essence\",\"tibetan\":\"གསེར་གྱི་སྙིང་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gser gyi snying po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"233dbec8-065f-452e-8983-ff75162cd133\",\"authority\":\"12f5814e-6832-4b57-86f2-5604faf9ddab\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2503\\\"\u003enāga\u003c/span\u003e king.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003egser gyi bzhin\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Golden Face\",\"tibetan\":\"གསེར་གདོང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gser gdong\"}},{\"uuid\":\"797a0bad-d1b1-4825-b16a-d7c98c0efdc9\",\"authority\":\"d351c6d2-a0cc-40ea-95f7-75726af4f08f\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA wife of the Buddha \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2797\\\"\u003eŚākyamuni\u003c/span\u003e when he was Prince Siddhārtha, and the daughter of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2636\\\"\u003eDaṇḍapāṇi\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Gopā\",\"tibetan\":\"ས་འཚོ་མ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"gopā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sa ’tsho ma\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0eaea7f5-9690-4a21-a84e-e80e30593a6f\",\"authority\":\"f75e45c7-02dd-4b8b-b51f-d5f18332df93\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eFemale cow herders or milk maids, the gopis are well known from their role in the mythology of Kṛṣṇa, in particular, \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-089-013-2773\\\"\u003eRādhā\u003c/span\u003e, who became his lover. \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003erdzi’i bu mo\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"gopi\",\"tibetan\":\"ཕྱུགས་རྫི།\",\"sanskrit\":\"gopī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"phyugs rdzi\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b711bcfc-11bb-4058-9a7c-9464a0a7605e\",\"authority\":\"b175bdcd-940c-49d8-9261-20e78f5b3e33\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bodhisattva.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003esprin chen mun pa rnam par sel ba\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Great Cloud Clearing Darkness\",\"tibetan\":\"སྤྲིན་ཆེན་མུན་སེལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sprin chen mun sel\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d710ef5e-5d1d-4329-a674-246838b2e85f\",\"authority\":\"f7fb3337-7413-4fba-b6c8-3ef745c4f9c4\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bodhisattva.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003esprin chen lta ba’i rab rib rnam par sel ba\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Great Cloud Clearing Obscured Vision\",\"tibetan\":\"སྤྲིན་ཆེན་རབ་རིབ་སེལ་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sprin chen rab rib sel ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"19b25ab8-71e3-47f1-b8b7-072500f756a2\",\"authority\":\"7003439f-d8d8-4a5e-9e49-ee7d5c230194\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bodhisattva.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003esprin chen ’od gtsang\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Great Cloud Completely Pure Radiance\",\"tibetan\":\"སྤྲིན་ཆེན་རྣམ་དག་འོད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sprin chen rnam dag ’od\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7d51b120-f00b-461d-b4e2-8fa82862f550\",\"authority\":\"d6d53162-9fca-4439-a1f7-5d3a0eb071c5\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bodhisattva.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(Toh 555: \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eMahā­megha­prajñā­samavarṣa\u003c/em\u003e; \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003esprin chen shes rab char yongs su snyoms pa\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Great Cloud Constant Wisdom Rain\",\"tibetan\":\"སྤྲིན་ཆེན་ཤེས་རབ་ཀུན་དུ་འཆར།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sprin chen shes rab kun du ’char\"}},{\"uuid\":\"e777c39d-95d9-4e15-913c-258